{"title_page": "Leader of the Band", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Leader of the Band\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Dan Fogelberg]]\n| album      = [[The Innocent Age]]\n| B-side     = Times Like These\n| released   = 1981\n| format     = [[7\"]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Folk rock]]\n| length     = 4:21\n| label      = [[Full Moon Records (US)|Full Moon]]/[[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = Dan Fogelberg\n| producer   = Dan Fogelberg, Marty Lewis\n| prev_title = [[Hard to Say]]\n| prev_year  = 1981\n| next_title = [[Run for the Roses (song)|Run for the Roses]]\n| next_year  = 1981\n}}\n\n\"'''Leader of the Band'''\" is a song written by [[Dan Fogelberg]] from his 1981 album ''[[The Innocent Age]]''. The song was written as a tribute to his father, Lawrence Fogelberg, a musician and the leader of a band, who was still alive at the time the song was released.<ref> {{cite web\n|url = http://www.danfogelberg.com/faqs.html\n|title = Dan Fogelberg Official Website Frequently Asked Questions (As answered in 2003)\n|date = 2003\n|accessdate = 2010-07-11\n|quote = \"Leader of the Band\" was written for my father Lawrence Fogelberg who was a musician, educator, and band leader. I was so gratified that I was able to give him that song before he passed on.\n}}\n</ref>  Lawrence died in August 1982, but not before this hit song made him a celebrity with numerous media interviews interested in him as its inspiration.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fogelberg|first1=Dan|title=FAQ's|url=https://www.danfogelberg.com/faqs|website=danfogelberg.com|accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nReleased as a [[single (music)|single]] at the end of 1981, the tribute peaked at #9 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (1996)</ref> in March 1982.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SCQEAAAAMBAJ|title=Billboard|last=Inc|first=Nielsen Business Media|date=1982-03-06|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref> It became Fogelberg's second #1 song on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks|Adult Contemporary chart]], following his 1980 hit \"[[Longer]]\".<ref>Hyatt, Wesley (1999). ''The Billboard Book of #1 Adult Contemporary Hits'' (Billboard Publications)\n</ref>\n\n==Other versions==\n[[Lucie Arnaz]] has performed a version of the song as a tribute to her late father, [[Desi Arnaz]].\n\n[[Regine Velasquez]] recorded this song in 2008 for her album ''[[Low Key]]'', and she also performed the song to her father, Gerardo Velasquez, he was still alive.\n\nZac Brown recorded this song in 2017 as part of a tribute album to Dan Fogelberg. He also dedicated it to his father.\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Chart (1982)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|9|artist=Dan Fogelberg|accessdate=November 24, 2018|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardadultcontemporary|1|artist=Dan Fogelberg|accessdate=November 24, 2018|rowheader=true}}\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year-end chart (1982) !! Rank\n|-\n|[[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1982|US Top Pop Singles (''Billboard'')]]<ref>{{cite magazine |date=December 25, 1982 |title=Talent in Action : Top Pop Singles |page=TIA-20 |magazine=Billboard |volume=94 |issue=51 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|35\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of number-one adult contemporary singles of 1982 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|dan-fogelberg|leader-of-the-band}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Dan Fogelberg}}\n\n[[Category:1981 singles]]\n[[Category:Dan Fogelberg songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Adult Contemporary number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Dan Fogelberg]]\n[[Category:RPM Adult Contemporary number-one singles]]\n[[Category:1981 songs]]\n[[Category:Full Moon Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about fathers]]\n\n{{1980s-pop-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Leader of the Band\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Dan Fogelberg]]\n| album      = [[The Innocent Age]]\n| B-side     = Times Like These\n| released   = 1981\n| format     = [[7\"]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Folk rock]]\n| length     = 4:21\n| label      = [[Full Moon Records (US)|Full Moon]]/[[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = Dan Fogelberg\n| producer   = Dan Fogelberg, Marty Lewis\n| prev_title = [[Hard to Say]]\n| prev_year  = 1981\n| next_title = [[Run for the Roses (song)|Run for the Roses]]\n| next_year  = 1981\n}}\n\n\"'''Leader of the Band'''\" is a song written by [[Dan Fogelberg]] from his 1981 album ''[[The Innocent Age]]''. The song was written as a tribute to his father, Lawrence Fogelberg, a musician and the leader of a band, who was still alive at the time the song was released.<ref> {{cite web\n|url = http://www.danfogelberg.com/faqs.html\n|title = Dan Fogelberg Official Website Frequently Asked Questions (As answered in 2003)\n|date = 2003\n|accessdate = 2010-07-11\n|quote = \"Leader of the Band\" was written for my father Lawrence Fogelberg who was a musician, educator, and band leader. I was so gratified that I was able to give him that song before he passed on.\n}}\n</ref>  Lawrence died in August 1982, but not before this hit song made him a celebrity with numerous media interviews interested in him as its inspiration.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fogelberg|first1=Dan|title=FAQ's|url=https://www.danfogelberg.com/faqs|website=danfogelberg.com|accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nReleased as a [[single (music)|single]] at the end of 1981, the tribute peaked at #9 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (1996)</ref> in March 1982.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SCQEAAAAMB