{"title_page": "Achallader Castle", "text_new": "[[File:Achallader Farm Tower - geograph.org.uk - 55403.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Ruins of Achallader Castle]]\n'''Achallader Castle''' ([[Scottish Gaelic]]: ''Caisteal Achaladair'') is a ruined 16th-century tower house under the shadow of [[Beinn Achaladair]], about 3.5 miles north of [[Bridge of Orchy]], [[Argyll and Bute]], [[Scotland]].  Its name is from [[Scottish Gaelic language|Gaelic]], meaning field of hard water.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\n==History==\nAchallader Castle was built near the northern end of Loch Tulla, close to the Bridge of Orchy, sometime in the 16th century and added to over the decades by various Clans<ref>{{cite web|last=Mason|first=Margaret|title=The Ancient Fletchers|url=http://www.spaceless.com/fletcher/flet2.htm}}</ref>; mainly the McHoughtons, of which Jimmy McHoughton is the youngest generation.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} It is accepted that the Fletcher's, known then as Macinleister \"were the first to 'raise smoke and boil water' on the Braes of Glenorchy\" although the MacGregors were also a ruling Clan of the area in the 15th century.  Sir [[Duncan Campbell of Glen Orchy|Duncan Campbell]] of [[Glen Orchy]] acquired the castle and surrounding lands through his treachery and betrayal of the Chief of the Mcinleisters in 1587.\n\nIt is said that when the Fletchers owned Achallader, Sir Duncan Campbell - known as Black Duncan - ordered an English servant (or soldier) to pasture his horse in the Fletchers\u2019 corn.  When warned off by the Fletchers - in Gaelic - he did not understand; when he did not remove his horse they shot him.  Black Duncan, affecting concern that the Fletcher laird would be hanged for the killing, advised him to flee to France.  Before he fled he passed the property to Black Duncan, supposedly until his return, to prevent it being forfeited to the Crown.  The Fletchers never recovered the property. The [[Clan MacGregor|MacGregors]] burnt the castle in 1603.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mason|first=Margaret|title=The Ancient Fletchers|url=http://www.spaceless.com/fletcher/flet2.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 1683 a Commission for the settlement of the [[Scottish Highlands|Highlands]], led by Sir William Drummond of [[Cromlix]] stayed at the castle, welcoming, among others McIain, a future victim, with his clan, of the [[massacre of Glencoe]]. In 1689, with [[William III of England|William III]] and [[Mary II of England|Mary II]] now reigning, the McIain\u2019s returning from their victory at [[Battle of Killiecrankie|Killiecrankie]] and repulse at [[Dunkeld]], pulled down what they could of the castle.  It was never restored.\n\nIn June 1691 [[John Campbell, 1st Earl of Breadalbane and Holland|John, Earl of Breadalbane]], empowered by King William to treat with the clans, conferred with the highland chiefs in the ruin of the castle.  By a mixture of threats, promises of bribes, and duplicity, he persuaded most of the clans - but not the McIains - to enter a treaty.  This included secret provisions, which he later denied, including the right of the chiefs to request relief from their oaths of allegiance from the exiled [[James II of England|James VII and II]].  The promised bribes did not materialise.\n\n==Description==\nThe castle formerly rose to three storeys and a [[garret]], well defended by shot-holes.  Now only two walls, one with a trace of [[corbel]]ling, remain, sheltering the farm buildings of Achallader Farm. It is protected as a [[scheduled monument]].<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=SM4136|desc=Achallader Castle & burial ground|access-date=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ruined castles in Argyll and Bute]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Ancient Monuments in Argyll and Bute]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Achallader Farm Tower - geograph.org.uk - 55403.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Ruins of Achallader Castle]]\n'''Achallader Castle''' ([[Scottish Gaelic]]: ''Caisteal Achaladair'') is a ruined 16th-century tower house under the shadow of [[Beinn Achaladair]], about 3.5 miles north of [[Bridge of Orchy]], [[Argyll and Bute]], [[Scotland]].  Its name is from [[Scottish Gaelic language|Gaelic]], meaning field of hard water.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\n==History==\nAchallader Castle was built near the northern end of Loch Tulla, close to the Bridge of Orchy, sometime in the 16th century and added to over the decades by various Clans; mainly the McHoughtons, of which Jimmy McHoughton is the youngest generation. {{Citation needed|date=June 2019}}  It is accepted that the Fletcher's, known then as Macinleister \"were the first to 'raise smoke and boil water' on the Braes of Glenorchy\" although the MacGregors were also a ruling Clan of the area in the 15th century.  Sir [[Duncan Campbell of Glen Orchy|Duncan Campbell]] of [[Glen Orchy]] acquired the castle and surrounding lands through his treachery and betrayal of the Chief of the Mcinleisters in 1587.\n\nIt is said that when the Fletchers owned Achallader, Sir Duncan Campbell - known as Black Duncan - ordered an English servant (or soldier) to pasture his horse in the Fletchers\u2019 corn.  When warned off by the Fletchers - in Gaelic - he did not understand; when he did not remove his horse they shot him.  Black Duncan, affecting concern that the Fletcher laird would be hanged for the killing, advised him to flee to France.  Before he fled he passed the property to Black Duncan, supposedly until his return, to prevent it being forfeited to the Crown.  The Fletchers never recovered the property. The [[Clan MacGregor|MacGregors]] burnt the castle in 1603.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mason|first=Margaret|title=The Ancient Fletchers|url=http://www.spaceless.com/fletcher/flet2.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 1683 a Commission for the settlement of the [[Scottish Highlands|Highlands]], led by Sir William Drummond of [[Cromlix]] stayed at the castle, welcoming, among others McIain, a future victim, with his clan, of the [[massacre of Glencoe]]. In 1689, with [[William III of England|William III]] and [[Mary II of England|Mary II]] now reigning, the McIain\u2019s returning from their victory at [[Battle of Killiecrankie|Killiecrankie]] and repulse at [[Dunkeld]], pulled down what they could of the castle.  It was never restored.\n\nIn June 1691 [[John Campbell, 1st Earl of Breadalbane and Holland|John, Earl of Breadalbane]], empowered by King William to treat with the clans, conferred with the highland chiefs in the ruin of the castle.  By a mixture of threats, promises of bribes, and duplicity, he persuaded most of the clans - but not the McIains - to enter a treaty.  This included secret provisions, which he later denied, including the right of the chiefs to request relief from their oaths of allegiance from the exiled [[James II of England|James VII and II]].  The promised bribes did not materialise.\n\n==Description==\nThe castle formerly rose to three storeys and a [[garret]], well defended by shot-holes.  Now only two walls, one with a trace of [[corbel]]ling, remain, sheltering the farm buildings of Achallader Farm. It is protected as a [[scheduled monument]].<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=SM4136|desc=Achallader Castle & burial ground|access-date=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ruined castles in Argyll and Bute]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Ancient Monuments in Argyll and Bute]]\n", "name_user": "Ssfletch", "label": "safe", "comment": "Citation added in first paragraph", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Achallader_Castle"}
{"title_page": "Eunice Golden", "text_new": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{Infobox artist\n|name=Eunice Golden\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_name=\n|birth_date={{birth year and age|1927}}\n|birth_place=New York City, New York\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|nationality=American\n|movement=[[Figurative art]], [[feminist art]]\n|awards=\n|patrons=\n|imagesize=\n|field=[[Painting]], [[photography]], [[filmmaking]]\n|training=\n|works=\n|influenced by=\n|influenced=\n}}\n\n'''Eunice Golden''' (born 1927) is an American [[Feminism|feminist]] [[Painting|painter]] from New York City, known for exploring sexuality using the male nude.<ref name=\"Parrish\">{{Cite web|url=http://artists.parrishart.org/index.php/Detail/Entity/Show/entity_id/231|title=Parrish East End Stories: Artists of the East End|website=parrishart.org|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref> Her work has been shown at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], [[Brooklyn Museum]], [[Bronx Museum of the Arts]], Westbeth Gallery, and [[Soho20 Chelsea|SOHO20 Gallery]], among others.<ref name=WebsiteCV/>\n\n== Early life, education, and political involvement ==\nEunice Golden's father fled [[Russia]] after a [[pogrom]] and her mother was the American-born daughter of Russian immigrants.<ref name=Levin>{{cite journal|title=Censorship, Politics and Sexual Imagery in the Work of Jewish-American Feminist Artists|last=Levin|first=Gail|journal=Nashim: A Journal of Jewish Women's Studies & Gender Issues|date=Fall 2007|pages=63\u201396}}</ref> She was raised in [[Brooklyn]].<ref name=Levin/> Golden studied [[psychology]] at the [[University of Wisconsin]] before leaving school to focus on her art.<ref name=FeministArtBase>{{cite web|title=Feminist Art Base: Eunice Golden|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/eascfa/feminist_art_base/eunice-golden|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref> She rebelled against the [[patriarchy|patriarchal]] views of her father and sought \"to demystify the male nude and sexuality,\" as noted by the art historian [[Gail Levin (art historian)|Gail Levin]].<ref name=Levin/> Golden's work paralleled ideas that emerged in [[women's liberation movement]] of the late 1960s and early 1970s.<ref name=FeministArtBase/> In 1971, Golden joined the Ad Hoc Women Artists' Committee (est. 1970), a subgroup of the [[Art Workers' Coalition]] that picketed the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] in a series of actions over four months.<ref name=Ault>{{cite book|title=Alternative New York, 1965-1985: A Cultural Politics Book for the Social Text Collective|editor-last=Ault|editor-first=Julie|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|pages=28\u201329}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973, Golden joined the \"Fight Censorship Group,\" which was organized by [[Anita Steckel]] in response to restrictions imposed on the sexually explicit works in Steckel's solo exhibition, ''The Sexual Politics of Feminist Art'' (1973), at [[Rockland Community College]].<ref name=Levin/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://broadstrokes.org/2014/01/28/anita-steckel-fighting-censorship-and-double-standards/|title=Anita Steckel: Fighting Censorship and Double Standards|website=Broad Strokes: National Museum of Women in the Arts|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref> In addition to Steckel and Golden, \"Fight Censorship\" included [[Judith Bernstein]], [[Louise Bourgeois]], [[Martha Edelheit]], Joan Glueckman, [[Juanita McNeely]], [[Barbara Nessim]], [[Joan Semmel]], Anne Sharpe, and [[Hannah Wilke]].<ref name=Levin/><ref name=WACK>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=maLpAAAAMAAJ|title=WACK! Art and the Feminist Revolution|editor-last=Butler|editor-first=Cornelia H.|publisher=Museum of Contemporary Art|location=Los Angeles|date=2007}}</ref> Also in 1973, Golden was a founding member of the all-women [[cooperative]] art gallery [[Soho20 Chelsea|SOHO20]],<ref name=BroudeGarrard>{{cite book|editor1-last=Broude|editor1-first=Norma|editor2-last=Garrard|editor2-first=Mary D.|title=The Power of Feminist Art: The American Movement of the 1970s, History and Impact|publisher=Harry N. Abrams, Inc.|location=New York|date=1994}}</ref> where her work was exhibited until 1981.<ref name=FeministArtBaseCV>{{Cite web|url=https://d1lfxha3ugu3d4.cloudfront.net/fab/cvs/310.pdf|title=Eunice Golden, CV|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Work ==\nGolden's paintings in the 1960s and 1970s focused on the male nude as a way to explore sexuality, struggle, and desire.<ref name=WACK/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/04/11/arts/art-in-review-eunice-golden.html|title=Art In Review: Eunice Golden|last=Cotter|first=Holland|date=11 April 2003|newspaper=New York Times|access-date=5 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/02/13/female-artists-male-muses_n_6669670.html|title=10 Amazing Female Artists and Their Male Muses|last=Lavin|first=Talia|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=13 February 2015|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref> She later explained that her early paintings of the male anatomy were not \"heretical\" or \"revolutionary\" but \"a stream of consciousness outpouring of emotionally and sensually charged images that reflected who I was: a heterosexual woman with erotic needs and fantasies, yet struggling to redefine myself. ... In retrospect, I saw that I had unwittingly addressed, on a subliminal level, ideologies, experiences, and perceptions of a broad audience.\"<ref name=FeministArtBase/> By the mid-1970s, Golden's feminist position was necessary to understand the larger impact of her erotic work.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Reviews|last=Heinemann|first=Susan|journal=Artforum|date=March 1974|volume=12|number=7|pages=79\u201380}}</ref> In particular, her ''Male Landscapes'' addressed the \"phallacy\" of male power as Golden's voyeuristic role reversed the erotic gaze from the long-established notion of the male as viewer and female as sexualized object.<ref name=FeministArtBase/> The art critic [[Peter Frank (art critic)|Peter Frank]] recognized the \"visual power\" her ''Male Landscapes'' as \"quite compelling.\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=On Art|last=Frank|first=Peter|journal=[[SoHo Weekly News]]|date=13 December 1973}}</ref> In 1977, her ''Landscape #160'' was included in ''Nothing But Nudes'', an exhibition at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], and was praised in [[Art International]] by [[Carter Ratcliff]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Remarks on the Nude|last=Ratcliff|first=Carter|journal=Art International|volume=21|number=2|date=March\u2013April 1977|pages=60\u201365, 73}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973, Golden began to explore performance, body-art, photography and film.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gCe58DI3e6kC|title=Women's Camera Work: Self/Body/Other in American Visual Culture|last=Davidov|first=Judith Fryer|date=1998|publisher=Duke University Press}}</ref> Her group of films, ''Blue Bananas and Other Meats'' (1973), extends the painted ''Male Landscapes'' into performances in which the male body is covered with an assortment of foods, much like the ''Spring Banquet'' by the [[Surrealism|Surrealist]] artist [[Meret Oppenheim]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Reviews|last=Moore|first=Alan|journal=Artforum|date=March 1975|volume=13|number=7|page=73}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, her work focused on portraits and satiric anthropomorphic studies. In the 1990s she completed her ''Swimmers'' series, which was centered around the closeness of mother and child.<ref name=Parrish/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eunicegolden.com/eunicegolden.com/The_Swimmers_1992-99.html|title=The Swimmers 1992-99|website=www.eunicegolden.com|access-date=6 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions<ref name=WebsiteCV>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eunicegolden.com/Eunicegolden.com/CV.html|title=Eunice Golden: CV|website=www.eunicegolden.com|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>==\n\n===Selected solo exhibitions and film screenings===\n\n* ''Blue Bananas and Other Meats'' (film screening), [[Pollock-Krasner House and Study Center]], East Hampton, NY, 2010<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.27east.com/news/article.cfm/Springs/299786/Notes-from-Springs-September-8|title=Springs News\u2014Notes from Springs, September 8|last=Manning|first=Ronnie Miller|date=7 September 2010|website=www.27east.com|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Paintings, Drawings, Photoworks from the Late 1960s and 1970s'', Mitchell Algus Gallery, New York, NY, 2003\n* ''Sometimes in Nature'', Clayton Liberatore Gallery, Bridgehampton, NY, 2002\n* ''The Swimmers'', Clayton Liberatore Gallery, Bridgehampton, NY, 2001<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://easthamptonstar.com/Archive/2/Opinion-Many-Faces-Cindy-Sherman|title=Opinion: The Many Faces of Cindy Sherman|last=Littman|first=Brett|journal=East Hampton Star|date=24 August 2000|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Three Decades: 1970-2000'', Westbeth Gallery, New York, NY, 2000<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://easthamptonstar.com/Archive/1/Galleries-2|title=At The Galleries|last=Sansegundo|first=Sheridan|journal=East Hampton Star|date=25 May 2000|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Abstract Paintings'', Prism Gallery, Port Jefferson, NY, 1998\n* ''Creatures'', Elaine Benson Gallery, Bridgehampton, NY, 1994\n* ''Primal Creatures'', Westbeth Gallery, New York, NY, 1983\n* ''Dreamscapes'', SOHO20 Gallery, New York, NY, 1980\n* ''The Past Ten Years'', [[Fairleigh Dickinson University]], Hackensack, NJ, 1979\n* ''Portraits'', SOHO20 Gallery, New York, NY, 1979\n* ''Body-Landscapes'' [[Arizona State University]], Tempe, AZ, 1977\n* ''Body-Landscapes'', [[University of South Dakota]], Vermillion, SD, 1976\n* ''Body-Landscapes'', SOHO20 Gallery, New York, NY, 1976\n* ''Eunice Golden'', SOHO20 Gallery, New York, NY, 1974\n* ''Eunice Golden'', SOHO20 Gallery, New York, NY, 1973\n* ''Metamorphosis Series/Rape Series'', Westbeth Gallery, New York, NY, 1973\n* ''Overview 1968-1973''. Westbeth Gallery, New York, NY, 1971\n* ''Recent Paintings and Works on Paper'', [[Hudson River Museum]], Yonkers, NY, 1969\n* ''Recent Paintings and Drawings'', Mari Galleries, Larchmont, NY, 1967\n* ''Paintings, Drawings, Collages'', Gallery 84, New York, NY, 1967\n\n===Selected group exhibitions===\n* ''Concept, Performance, Documentation, Language'', Mitchell Algus Gallery, New York, NY, 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mitchellalgusgallery.com/concept-performance-documentation-language-exhibition-information/|title=Press release for ''Concept, Performance, Documentation, Language''|website=mitchellalgusgallery.com|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Sequence and Consequence'', Steven Kasher Gallery, New York, NY, 2006\n* ''The F Word'', Mitchell Algus Gallery, New York, NY, 2004\n* ''IDEA Photographic, After Modernism'', Museum of Fine Arts, Santa Fe, NM, 2002-2003\n* ''Personal and Political: The Women's Art Movement, 1969-1975'', Guild Hall Museum, East Hampton, NY, 2002<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/11/arts/art-review-two-nods-to-feminism-long-snubbed-by-curators.html|title=Art Review: Two Nods to Feminism, Long Snubbed by Curators|last=Cotter|first=Holland|date=11 October 2002|newspaper=New York Times|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Landscape Today: East End Views'', Guild Hall Museum, East Hampton, NY, 1994\n* ''Contemporary Crafts'', Guild Hall Museum, East Hampton, NY, 1991-1992\n\n== Publications ==\n* Golden,Eunice; Kenny, Kay (Spring-Summer 1982). \"Sexuality in Art: Two Decades from a Feminist Perspective.\" ''[[Woman's Art Journal]]'' '''3''' (1):14-15.\n* Golden, Eunice (Spring 1981). [http://heresiesfilmproject.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/heresies12.pdf \"The Male Nude in Women\u2019s Art\u2014Dialectics of a Feminist Iconography.\"] [[Heresies: A Feminist Publication on Art and Politics|Heresies]] #12, '''3''' (4): 40\u201342.\n* Golden, Eunice (May\u2013June 1975). \"On the Censorship of Phallic Imagery.\" ''Artworkers News''. p.&nbsp;3.\n* Golden, Eunice (April 1967). \"On the Business of Art.\" ''Artworkers News''. p.&nbsp;26.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.eunicegolden.com}}\n* [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/eunice-golden-papers-8225 Eunice Golden Papers, 1945-2002, 1963-1979, Archives of American Art, Smithsonian]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golden, Eunice}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American erotic artists]]\n[[Category:American women painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American painter}}\n{{Infobox artist\n|name=Eunice Golden\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_name=\n|birth_date={{birth year and age|1927}}\n|birth_place=New York City, New York\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|nationality=American\n|movement=[[Figurative art]], [[feminist art]]\n|awards=\n|patrons=\n|imagesize=\n|field=[[Painting]], [[photography]], [[filmmaking]]\n|training=\n|works=\n|influenced by=\n|influenced=\n}}\n\n'''Eunice Golden''' (born 1927) is an American [[Feminism|feminist]] [[Painting|painter]] from New York City, known for exploring sexuality using the male nude.<ref name=\"Parrish\">{{Cite web|url=http://artists.parrishart.org/index.php/Detail/Entity/Show/entity_id/231|title=Parrish East End Stories: Artists of the East End|website=parrishart.org|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref> Her work has been shown at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], [[Brooklyn Museum]], [[Bronx Museum of the Arts]], Westbeth Gallery, and [[Soho20 Chelsea|SOHO20 Gallery]], among others.<ref name=WebsiteCV/>\n\n== Early life, education, and political involvement ==\nEunice Golden's father fled [[Russia]] after a [[pogrom]] and her mother was the American-born daughter of Russian immigrants.<ref name=Levin>{{cite journal|title=Censorship, Politics and Sexual Imagery in the Work of Jewish-American Feminist Artists|last=Levin|first=Gail|journal=Nashim: A Journal of Jewish Women's Studies & Gender Issues|date=Fall 2007|pages=63\u201396}}</ref> She was raised in [[Brooklyn]].<ref name=Levin/> Golden studied [[psychology]] at the [[University of Wisconsin]] before leaving school to focus on her art.<ref name=FeministArtBase>{{cite web|title=Feminist Art Base: Eunice Golden|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/eascfa/feminist_art_base/eunice-golden|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref> She rebelled against the [[patriarchy|patriarchal]] views of her father and sought \"to demystify the male nude and sexuality,\" as noted by the art historian [[Gail Levin (art historian)|Gail Levin]].<ref name=Levin/> Golden's work paralleled ideas that emerged in [[women's liberation movement]] of the late 1960s and early 1970s.<ref name=FeministArtBase/> In 1971, Golden joined the Ad Hoc Women Artists' Committee (est. 1970), a subgroup of the [[Art Workers' Coalition]] that picketed the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] in a series of actions over four months.<ref name=Ault>{{cite book|title=Alternative New York, 1965-1985: A Cultural Politics Book for the Social Text Collective|editor-last=Ault|editor-first=Julie|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|pages=28\u201329}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973, Golden joined the \"Fight Censorship Group,\" which was organized by [[Anita Steckel]] in response to restrictions imposed on the sexually explicit works in Steckel's solo exhibition, ''The Sexual Politics of Feminist Art'' (1973), at [[Rockland Community College]].<ref name=Levin/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://broadstrokes.org/2014/01/28/anita-steckel-fighting-censorship-and-double-standards/|title=Anita Steckel: Fighting Censorship and Double Standards|website=Broad Strokes: National Museum of Women in the Arts|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref> In addition to Steckel and Golden, \"Fight Censorship\" included [[Judith Bernstein]], [[Louise Bourgeois]], [[Martha Edelheit]], Joan Glueckman, [[Juanita McNeely]], [[Barbara Nessim]], [[Joan Semmel]], Anne Sharpe, and [[Hannah Wilke]].<ref name=Levin/><ref name=WACK>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=maLpAAAAMAAJ|title=WACK! Art and the Feminist Revolution|editor-last=Butler|editor-first=Cornelia H.|publisher=Museum of Contemporary Art|location=Los Angeles|date=2007}}</ref> Also in 1973, Golden was a founding member of the all-women [[cooperative]] art gallery [[Soho20 Chelsea|SOHO20]],<ref name=BroudeGarrard>{{cite book|editor1-last=Broude|editor1-first=Norma|editor2-last=Garrard|editor2-first=Mary D.|title=The Power of Feminist Art: The American Movement of the 1970s, History and Impact|publisher=Harry N. Abrams, Inc.|location=New York|date=1994}}</ref> where her work was exhibited until 1981.<ref name=FeministArtBaseCV>{{Cite web|url=https://d1lfxha3ugu3d4.cloudfront.net/fab/cvs/310.pdf|title=Eunice Golden, CV|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Work ==\nGolden's paintings in the 1960s and 1970s focused on the male nude as a way to explore sexuality, struggle, and desire.<ref name=WACK/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/04/11/arts/art-in-review-eunice-golden.html|title=Art In Review: Eunice Golden|last=Cotter|first=Holland|date=11 April 2003|newspaper=New York Times|access-date=5 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/02/13/female-artists-male-muses_n_6669670.html|title=10 Amazing Female Artists and Their Male Muses|last=Lavin|first=Talia|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=13 February 2015|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref> She later explained that her early paintings of the male anatomy were not \"heretical\" or \"revolutionary\" but \"a stream of consciousness outpouring of emotionally and sensually charged images that reflected who I was: a heterosexual woman with erotic needs and fantasies, yet struggling to redefine myself. ... In retrospect, I saw that I had unwittingly addressed, on a subliminal level, ideologies, experiences, and perceptions of a broad audience.\"<ref name=FeministArtBase/> By the mid-1970s, Golden's feminist position was necessary to understand the larger impact of her erotic work.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Reviews|last=Heinemann|first=Susan|journal=Artforum|date=March 1974|volume=12|number=7|pages=79\u201380}}</ref> In particular, her ''Male Landscapes'' addressed the \"phallacy\" of male power as Golden's voyeuristic role reversed the erotic gaze from the long-established notion of the male as viewer and female as sexualized object.<ref name=FeministArtBase/> The art critic [[Peter Frank (art critic)|Peter Frank]] recognized the \"visual power\" her ''Male Landscapes'' as \"quite compelling.\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=On Art|last=Frank|first=Peter|journal=[[SoHo Weekly News]]|date=13 December 1973}}</ref> In 1977, her ''Landscape #160'' was included in ''Nothing But Nudes'', an exhibition at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], and was praised in [[Art International]] by [[Carter Ratcliff]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Remarks on the Nude|last=Ratcliff|first=Carter|journal=Art International|volume=21|number=2|date=March\u2013April 1977|pages=60\u201365, 73}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973, Golden began to explore performance, body-art, photography and film.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gCe58DI3e6kC|title=Women's Camera Work: Self/Body/Other in American Visual Culture|last=Davidov|first=Judith Fryer|date=1998|publisher=Duke University Press}}</ref> Her group of films, ''Blue Bananas and Other Meats'' (1973), extends the painted ''Male Landscapes'' into performances in which the male body is covered with an assortment of foods, much like the ''Spring Banquet'' by the [[Surrealism|Surrealist]] artist [[Meret Oppenheim]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Reviews|last=Moore|first=Alan|journal=Artforum|date=March 1975|volume=13|number=7|page=73}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, her work focused on portraits and satiric anthropomorphic studies. In the 1990s she completed her ''Swimmers'' series, which was centered around the closeness of mother and child.<ref name=Parrish/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eunicegolden.com/eunicegolden.com/The_Swimmers_1992-99.html|title=The Swimmers 1992-99|website=www.eunicegolden.com|access-date=6 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions<ref name=WebsiteCV>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eunicegolden.com/Eunicegolden.com/CV.html|title=Eunice Golden: CV|website=www.eunicegolden.com|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>==\n\n===Selected solo exhibitions and film screenings===\n\n* ''Blue Bananas and Other Meats'' (film screening), [[Pollock-Krasner House and Study Center]], East Hampton, NY, 2010<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.27east.com/news/article.cfm/Springs/299786/Notes-from-Springs-September-8|title=Springs News\u2014Notes from Springs, September 8|last=Manning|first=Ronnie Miller|date=7 September 2010|website=www.27east.com|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Paintings, Drawings, Photoworks from the Late 1960s and 1970s'', Mitchell Algus Gallery, New York, NY, 2003\n* ''Sometimes in Nature'', Clayton Liberatore Gallery, Bridgehampton, NY, 2002\n* ''The Swimmers'', Clayton Liberatore Gallery, Bridgehampton, NY, 2001<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://easthamptonstar.com/Archive/2/Opinion-Many-Faces-Cindy-Sherman|title=Opinion: The Many Faces of Cindy Sherman|last=Littman|first=Brett|journal=East Hampton Star|date=24 August 2000|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Three Decades: 1970-2000'', Westbeth Gallery, New York, NY, 2000<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://easthamptonstar.com/Archive/1/Galleries-2|title=At The Galleries|last=Sansegundo|first=Sheridan|journal=East Hampton Star|date=25 May 2000|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Abstract Paintings'', Prism Gallery, Port Jefferson, NY, 1998\n* ''Creatures'', Elaine Benson Gallery, Bridgehampton, NY, 1994\n* ''Primal Creatures'', Westbeth Gallery, New York, NY, 1983\n* ''Dreamscapes'', SOHO20 Gallery, New York, NY, 1980\n* ''The Past Ten Years'', [[Fairleigh Dickinson University]], Hackensack, NJ, 1979\n* ''Portraits'', SOHO20 Gallery, New York, NY, 1979\n* ''Body-Landscapes'' [[Arizona State University]], Tempe, AZ, 1977\n* ''Body-Landscapes'', [[University of South Dakota]], Vermillion, SD, 1976\n* ''Body-Landscapes'', SOHO20 Gallery, New York, NY, 1976\n* ''Eunice Golden'', SOHO20 Gallery, New York, NY, 1974\n* ''Eunice Golden'', SOHO20 Gallery, New York, NY, 1973\n* ''Metamorphosis Series/Rape Series'', Westbeth Gallery, New York, NY, 1973\n* ''Overview 1968-1973''. Westbeth Gallery, New York, NY, 1971\n* ''Recent Paintings and Works on Paper'', [[Hudson River Museum]], Yonkers, NY, 1969\n* ''Recent Paintings and Drawings'', Mari Galleries, Larchmont, NY, 1967\n* ''Paintings, Drawings, Collages'', Gallery 84, New York, NY, 1967\n\n===Selected group exhibitions===\n* ''Concept, Performance, Documentation, Language'', Mitchell Algus Gallery, New York, NY, 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mitchellalgusgallery.com/concept-performance-documentation-language-exhibition-information/|title=Press release for ''Concept, Performance, Documentation, Language''|website=mitchellalgusgallery.com|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Sequence and Consequence'', Steven Kasher Gallery, New York, NY, 2006\n* ''The F Word'', Mitchell Algus Gallery, New York, NY, 2004\n* ''IDEA Photographic, After Modernism'', Museum of Fine Arts, Santa Fe, NM, 2002-2003\n* ''Personal and Political: The Women's Art Movement, 1969-1975'', Guild Hall Museum, East Hampton, NY, 2002<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/11/arts/art-review-two-nods-to-feminism-long-snubbed-by-curators.html|title=Art Review: Two Nods to Feminism, Long Snubbed by Curators|last=Cotter|first=Holland|date=11 October 2002|newspaper=New York Times|access-date=25 February 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Landscape Today: East End Views'', Guild Hall Museum, East Hampton, NY, 1994\n* ''Contemporary Crafts'', Guild Hall Museum, East Hampton, NY, 1991-1992\n\n== Publications ==\n* Golden,Eunice; Kenny, Kay (Spring-Summer 1982). \"Sexuality in Art: Two Decades from a Feminist Perspective.\" ''[[Woman's Art Journal]]'' '''3''' (1):14-15.\n* Golden, Eunice (Spring 1981). [http://heresiesfilmproject.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/heresies12.pdf \"The Male Nude in Women\u2019s Art\u2014Dialectics of a Feminist Iconography.\"] [[Heresies: A Feminist Publication on Art and Politics|Heresies]] #12, '''3''' (4): 40-42.\n* Golden, Eunice (May\u2013June 1975). \"On the Censorship of Phallic Imagery.\" ''Artworkers News''. p.&nbsp;3.\n* Golden, Eunice (April 1967). \"On the Business of Art.\" ''Artworkers News''. p.&nbsp;26.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.eunicegolden.com}}\n* [http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/eunice-golden-papers-8225 Eunice Golden Papers, 1945-2002, 1963-1979, Archives of American Art, Smithsonian]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golden, Eunice}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American erotic artists]]\n[[Category:American women painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women artists]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublications:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 40-42 \u2192 40\u201342", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eunice_Golden"}
{"title_page": "Melinda Gebbie", "text_new": "{{short description|American comics artist and writer}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox comics creator\n| image         = Melinda Gebbie at TAM London 2010.JPG\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Melinda Gebbie at [[The Amazing Meeting]] in [[London]] in 2010\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    =\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco]], [[California]]\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| cartoonist    = \n| write         = y\n| art           = \n| pencil        = y\n| ink           = y\n| edit          = \n| publish       = \n| letter        = \n| color         = \n| alias         = \n| notable works = ''[[Lost Girls (graphic novel)|Lost Girls]]''<br />''[[Cobweb (comics)|Cobweb]]''\n| awards        = \n| website       = \n| sortkey       = Gebbie, Melinda\n| subcat        = American\n}}\n[[File:MelindaGebbie.jpg|thumb|upright|Melinda Gebbie in 1982]]\n\n'''Melinda Gebbie''' is an American [[comics artist]] and writer, known for her participation in the underground comix movement. She is also known for creating the controversial work ''Fresca Zizis''  and her contributions to ''Wimmen's Comix,'' as well as her work with her husband [[Alan Moore]] on the three-volume graphic novel ''[[Lost Girls (graphic novel)|Lost Girls]]'' and the <nowiki/>''[[Tomorrow Stories]]'' anthology series.\n\n== Personal life ==\nMelinda Gebbie was born in San Francisco.  She became interested in comics in 1973, when she met writer/artist [[Lee Marrs]] at a publishers' fair.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lambiek.net/artists/g/gebbie_melinda.htm|title=Melinda Gebbie|website=lambiek.net|language=en|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> In 1984 Gebbie married Adam Cornford, a poet from California, however their marriage was short lived. Their marriage is believed to have been an inspiration for his poetry collection ''Animations''.{{Citation needed|date=November 2017|reason=The former citation for this was a Wikipedia mirror, so it was removed}} She married Alan Moore, in 2007.\n\n==Career==\nMelinda Gebbie contributed her first comic strip to ''[[Wimmen's Comix]]'' #3, the inceptive all-women anthology published by [[Last Gasp]]. She wrote and drew short stories for ''Wimmen's Comix'' and many other anthologies, including ''[[Tits & Clits Comix]]'', ''Wet Satin'', and ''[[Anarchy Comics]]''. In 1977 she completed her own solo comic book, ''[[Fresca Zizis]],'' which was later banned in Britain in 1985 for obscenity, and still is to this day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cbldf.org/2013/09/melinda-gebbie-discusses-lost-girls-censorship-at-edinburgh-book-fest/|title=Melinda Gebbie Discusses Lost Girls, Censorship at Edinburgh Book Fest {{!}} Comic Book Legal Defense Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, she moved to England to work on the animated film adaptation of [[Raymond Briggs]]' ''[[When the Wind Blows (graphic novel)|When the Wind Blows]]''. Following this, she worked in a variety of illustration and office jobs and continued making short stories for anthologies such as ''[[Strip AIDS]]'' and ''Heartbreak Hotel''. In the early 1990s, Alan Moore and Gebbie began collaborating on ''[[Lost Girls (graphic novel)|Lost Girls]]'', a story in which the female protagonists of ''[[Peter and Wendy]]'', ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'', and ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'' meet and share sexual stories and experiences.  Moore wrote the story, and Gebbie illustrated it.  The story was finished in 2006.  Meanwhile, she and Moore created [[Cobweb (character)|Cobweb]], a mysterious heroine who appeared in twelve issues of the Moore-written anthology ''[[Tomorrow Stories]]'' between 1999 and 2002.\n\n=== Feminism in the Underground Comix Movement ===\nHilary Chute claims that the underground comix movement was parallel to second-wave feminism because it gave women comic artists the ability to establish work that was political and freely explore and publish their artistic expression.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Autobiographical Comics|last=Kunka|first=Andrew|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|year=2017|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Autobiographical comics were popular among the underground comix industry due to groups of people being underrepresented in the mainstream comics industry. Although they weren't completely autobiographical, comics like ''[[Tits & Clits Comix|Tits & Clits]], [[Wimmen's Comix]],'' and ''[[Twisted Sisters (comic)|Twisted Sisters]]'' contained many stores that touched on the comic artists' personal experiences. Their stories discussed topics that weren't represented in the male-dominated mainstream and underground comix, because it addressed women's point of view on sex, masturbation, abuse, coming out, and menstruation.<ref name=\":0\" /> Many of the male anthologies created in the underground kept women from collaborating with them, which prompted the creation of all-girl collaborated comics like ''[[It Ain't Me Babe]]'' and ''Wimmen's Comix''.<ref name=\":0\" /> Although the series of publication wasn't consistent, ''Wimmen's Comix'' published 17 issues from 1972\u20131992.\n\n=== Fresca Zizis (Last Gasp, 1977) ===\nIn 1977, Melinda Gebbie produced her first solo work, ''Fresca Zizis''. The title means \"fresh cocks\" in Italian. During the 1980s, her comic book was banned in Britain for obscenity due to its pornographic illustrations.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Complete Wimmen's Comix, Volume 2|last=|first=|publisher=Fantagraphics Books|year=2016|isbn=|location=|pages=700}}</ref> ''Fresca Zizis'' is semi-autobiographical and includes Gebbie's past experiences with childhood abuse and sex, as well as portraits and stories of fellow cartoonist friends such as [[Trina Robbins]] and [[Lee Marrs]].<ref name=\"melindagebbie.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://melindagebbie.com/documentary/documentary_comics.html|title=The Bad Girl, Sad Girl, Mad Girl Art of Melinda Gebbie|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Gebbie describes that it \"deals with the cruelty of lovers, the excesses of youth, and the states of depression and dreams - a warning and a comfort to those who venture out too deep.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://honesterotica.com/portfolios/309|title=Fresca Zizis {{!}} honesterotica|website=honesterotica.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-30}}</ref> When Gebbie was put on trial to defend the 'obscenity' in her work, she explained that the illustrations from the comic book come from her own experiences and argued that the people who put her through those experiences should be seen as obscene rather than her work, which is portrayed in her comic called 'Public Enemy' in ''Anarchy Comics'' issue #4.<ref name=\"melindagebbie.com\"/>\n\n=== Lost Girls (Top Shelf, 2006) ===\nThe graphic novel ''Lost Girls'' was illustrated by Gebbie and written by her husband Alan Moore. It took Gebbie 16 years to illustrate the comic due to the layering techniques used to create the shimmering, children's book-like effect, which was done by her use of water colors and 12-14 layers of colored pencils.<ref name=\"melindagebbie.com\"/> ''Lost Girls'' follows the story of three young girls that come from popular fiction; Alice from ''[[Through the Looking-Glass|Through the Looking Glass]]'', Dorothy from ''The Wizard of Oz'', and Wendy from ''Peter and Wendy''. The three female protagonists meet at an Austrian hotel and share with each other their past sexual fantasies and experiences in flashbacks, while also meeting others who are staying at the hotel and having sex with them. The stories of each female protagonist's sexual experience is integrated within their original narratives from popular fiction. Due to the [[Coroners and Justice Act 2009|Coroners and Justice Act]], many comic artists thought the book would be banned in the UK because of its depictions of child pornography, however, it is still sold in the UK.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/graphic-artists-condemn-plans-to-ban-erotic-comics-1652270.html|title=Graphic artists condemn plans to ban erotic comics|date=2009-03-23|work=The Independent|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''[[Fresca Zizis]]'' ([[Last Gasp Publishing]], 1977)\n*''[[Lost Girls (graphic novel)|Lost Girls]]'' (with writer [[Alan Moore]], [[Top Shelf Productions]], 2006, {{ISBN|1-891830-74-0}})\n\n===Anthologies===\n* ''[[Cobweb (comics)|Cobweb]]'' (with writer [[Alan Moore]], in ''[[Tomorrow Stories]]'' #1\u20138, [[America's Best Comics]]/[[Wildstorm]], 1999\u20132002)\n*''Heartbreak Hotel''\n*''Strip AIDS''\n* \"''The Cockpit''\"  (in ''Wet Satin'' #1, Last Gasp Publishing)\n* \"''My Three Swans''\", in ''[[Young Lust (comics)|Young Lust]]'' #6 (Last Gasp Publishing)\n*''[[Wimmen's Comix]]'' #4\u20137 (Last Gasp Publishing)\n*''[[Anarchy Comics]]'' (Last Gasp Publishing)\n* ''24 Panels:'' \"If Einstein's Right...\" (with writer Alan Moore, [[Image Comics]], 2018)<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/aug/20/disgrace-and-shame-alan-moore-points-to-boris-johnson-in-grenfell-fire-comic</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{gcdb|type=credit|search=Melinda+Gebbie|title=Melinda Gebbie}}\n*[http://lambiek.net/artists/g/gebbie_melinda.htm Melinda Gebbie] at [[Lambiek]]'s Comiclopedia\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website |http://www.melindagebbie.com }}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=creator |id= 3904 |title= Melinda Gebbie }}\n* {{IMDb name |3024758 }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://lambiek.net/magazines/wimmenscomix.htm |series= Comics history |title= Wimmen's Comix (1970 - 1991) |work= Comiclopedia |publisher= [[Lambiek]] }}\n\n===Interviews===\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.adnstream.com/video/FaVmTuxKeh/Melinda-Gebbie |format= podcast |title= Melinda Gebbie |series= Interview |publisher= ADN Stream }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://suicidegirls.com/interviews/Lost%20Girls%20artist%20Melinda%20Gebbie |title= Lost Girls artist Melinda Gebbie |publisher= [[SuicideGirls.com]] |date= June 6, 2006 }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.readysteadybook.com/Article.aspx?page=melindagebbie |title= Melinda Gebbie |series= Interview |publisher= Ready Steady Book |date= Sep 11, 2006 }}\n\n{{Underground comix cartoonists}}\n{{Alan Moore}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gebbie, Melinda}}\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:American female comics artists]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:American erotic artists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Female comics writers]]\n[[Category:Alan Moore]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American comics artist and writer}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox comics creator\n| image         = Melinda Gebbie at TAM London 2010.JPG\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Melinda Gebbie at [[The Amazing Meeting]] in [[London]] in 2010\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    =\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco]], [[California]]\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| cartoonist    = \n| write         = y\n| art           = \n| pencil        = y\n| ink           = y\n| edit          = \n| publish       = \n| letter        = \n| color         = \n| alias         = \n| notable works = ''[[Lost Girls (graphic novel)|Lost Girls]]''<br />''[[Cobweb (comics)|Cobweb]]''\n| awards        = \n| website       = \n| sortkey       = Gebbie, Melinda\n| subcat        = American\n}}\n[[File:MelindaGebbie.jpg|thumb|upright|Melinda Gebbie in 1982]]\n\n'''Melinda Gebbie''' is an American [[comics artist]] and writer, known for her participation in the underground comix movement. She is also known for creating the controversial work ''Fresca Zizis''  and her contributions to ''Wimmen's Comix,'' as well as