 three young girls that come from popular fiction; Alice from ''[[Through the Looking-Glass|Through the Looking Glass]]'', Dorothy from ''The Wizard of Oz'', and Wendy from ''Peter and Wendy''. The three female protagonists meet at an Austrian hotel and share with each other their past sexual fantasies and experiences in flashbacks, while also meeting others who are staying at the hotel and having sex with them. The stories of each female protagonist's sexual experience is integrated within their original narratives from popular fiction. Due to the [[Coroners and Justice Act 2009|Coroners and Justice Act]], many comic artists thought the book would be banned in the UK because of its depictions of child pornography, however, it is still sold in the UK.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/graphic-artists-condemn-plans-to-ban-erotic-comics-1652270.html|title=Graphic artists condemn plans to ban erotic comics|date=2009-03-23|work=The Independent|access-date=2017-12-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''[[Fresca Zizis]]'' ([[Last Gasp Publishing]], 1977)\n*''[[Lost Girls (graphic novel)|Lost Girls]]'' (with writer [[Alan Moore]], [[Top Shelf Productions]], 2006, {{ISBN|1-891830-74-0}})\n\n===Anthologies===\n* ''[[Cobweb (comics)|Cobweb]]'' (with writer [[Alan Moore]], in ''[[Tomorrow Stories]]'' #1\u20138, [[America's Best Comics]]/[[Wildstorm]], 1999\u20132002)\n*''Heartbreak Hotel''\n*''Strip AIDS''\n* \"''The Cockpit''\"  (in ''Wet Satin'' #1, Last Gasp Publishing)\n* \"''My Three Swans''\", in ''[[Young Lust (comics)|Young Lust]]'' #6 (Last Gasp Publishing)\n*''[[Wimmen's Comix]]'' #4\u20137 (Last Gasp Publishing)\n*''[[Anarchy Comics]]'' (Last Gasp Publishing)\n* ''24 Panels:'' \"If Einstein's Right...\" (with writer Alan Moore, [[Image Comics]], 2018)<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/aug/20/disgrace-and-shame-alan-moore-points-to-boris-johnson-in-grenfell-fire-comic</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{gcdb|type=credit|search=Melinda+Gebbie|title=Melinda Gebbie}}\n*[http://lambiek.net/artists/g/gebbie_melinda.htm Melinda Gebbie] at [[Lambiek]]'s Comiclopedia\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website |http://www.melindagebbie.com }}\n* {{comicbookdb|type=creator |id= 3904 |title= Melinda Gebbie }}\n* {{IMDb name |3024758 }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://lambiek.net/magazines/wimmenscomix.htm |series= Comics history |title= Wimmen's Comix (1970 - 1991) |work= Comiclopedia |publisher= [[Lambiek]] }}\n\n===Interviews===\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.adnstream.com/video/FaVmTuxKeh/Melinda-Gebbie |format= podcast |title= Melinda Gebbie |series= Interview |publisher= ADN Stream }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://suicidegirls.com/interviews/Lost%20Girls%20artist%20Melinda%20Gebbie |title= Lost Girls artist Melinda Gebbie |publisher= [[SuicideGirls.com]] |date= June 6, 2006 }}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.readysteadybook.com/Article.aspx?page=melindagebbie |title= Melinda Gebbie |series= Interview |publisher= Ready Steady Book |date= Sep 11, 2006 }}\n\n{{Underground comix cartoonists}}\n{{Alan Moore}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gebbie, Melinda}}\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:American female comics artists]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:American erotic artists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Female comics writers]]\n[[Category:Alan Moore]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFeminism in the Underground Comix Movement:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1972-1992 \u2192 1972\u20131992", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melinda_Gebbie"}
{"title_page": "Drubskin", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| birth_date = August 14, 1973\n| birth_place = [[Derby, Connecticut]]\n| nationality = US\n| website = {{url|http://drubskin.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Drubskin''', also known as '''\"Drub\"''' (born August 14, 1973; in [[Derby, Connecticut]])<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://nosafeword.com/posts/75_drubskin/|title=Episode 75 \u2013 Drubskin {{!}} NoSafeWord.com|website=nosafeword.com|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref> is a [[fetish artist]] known for his [[homoerotic]] illustrations and [[Erotic comics|erotic comic book]] work. He is based in [[San Diego, California]], and has ties to [[Skinheads Against Racial Prejudice]] and the [[punk subculture|punk]] subculture.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDrawing since the age of 15,<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.leslielohman.org/the-archive/no12/erotic-artist-drub-12.html|title=Leslie Lohman Museum of Gay and Lesbian Art - THE ARCHIVE: No. 13: Summer 2004|website=www.leslielohman.org|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref> Drub's illustrations incorporate various fetishistic interests in footwear, sportswear, subculture-specific clothing, rubber, [[sado-masochism]], and watersports. Most of the men he depicts are part of the [[punk subculture|punk]], [[skinhead]], and [[working class]] communities, drawn in a homo-masculine manner. His work is typically done in a comic book style, with bright colors and heavy line weight.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1991 he moved from Connecticut to Kansas City, Missouri to attend the [[Kansas City Art Institute]] where he eventually earned his Bachelor of Fine Arts in Illustration.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/drubskin.htm|title=Drubskin|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref> In 1995 he was asked to write a first-hand account of his sexual exploits in the punk and skinhead scene for a [[webzine]] called ''Nightcharm'', as a way to promote his art. His pseudonym ''Drub'' is derived from his writing style, as a play on the verb which means to beat or thrash.{{Citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\nHis website and column garnered him attention from the gay male community at large and by 2000 his work began appearing in gay magazines worldwide. Drub began exhibiting his work in the 2000s and in 2003 he had his first international solo art exhibition at Mr. B's in Amsterdam.<ref name=\":2\" /> Drub has also shown his work in galleries in Los Angeles, Toronto, Berlin, Amsterdam, and participates annually in the [[Seattle Erotic Art Festival]]. He has had work published in several publications, including ''[[Freshmen (magazine)|Freshmen]]'', ''Instigator'' and ''[[Blue (Australian magazine)|Blue magazine]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> He sells hand-illustrated greeting cards for Mr. B in Amsterdam and Berlin, and The Leatherman in New York City.\n\n==Features and published works==\n\n* ''Freshmen Magazine'', 2002, illustration for story \"Chemistry\"\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20110816153513/http://www.solanasonline.com/ Solanas Online]'' \u2013 Issue 2, 2003, Drub Coloring Book\n* ''Instigator Magazine'' \u2013 2/15/04 \u2013 Featured Artist\n* ''Blue Magazine'', Issue 52 \u2013 9/01/04 \u2013 Featured Artist\n* ''Turnover,'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20111001041445/http://www.apla.org/publications/turnover/web/Malware.pdf Malware], ed. AIDS Project Los Angeles: The Institute for Gay Men's Health, 2005, {{ISBN|0-9759225-4-8}}\n* BuzzcockNYC Monthly Party, 8/31/06 \u2013 New York City, poster art\n* ''Best Gay Erotica 2007'', \"The Welcome Back Fuck\", ed. [[Richard Labont\u00e9|Richard Labonte]], written by [[Dale Lazarov]], 2007, {{ISBN|1-57344-260-7}}\n* ''Hard To Swallow Comics #3'', \"Dem Bones\", All Thumbs Press/Marginalized Publications, 2007, {{ISBN|978-0-9778011-2-1}}\n* ''Best Erotic Comics 2009'', \"Dem Bones\", ed. [[Greta Christina]], [[Last Gasp]], 2009, {{ISBN|0-86719-711-0}}\n\n==Gallery shows==\n\n* ''Drubbish Show'', Fluke Gallery, Kansas City, Missouri - May 31, 2002\n* ''Drub(x)3 Art Exhibition'' \u2013 Mr. B, Amsterdam/Berlin - 4/12/03\n* ''Seattle Erotic Art Festival'' \u2013 Consolidated Works, Seattle, WA - 1/30/04 to 2/1/04\n* ''5\u00d75=25'' \u2013 Galeria ARTopia, Albuquerque, NM - 7/31/04\n* ''Seattle Erotic Art Festival'' (Invited Artist) \u2013 Consolidated Works, Seattle, WA - 4/16/05\n* ''Seattle Erotic Art Festival'' (Featured Artist/Advertising) \u2013 Consolidated Works, Seattle, WA - 5/01/06\n* ''Toonfetish'' \u2013 Antebellum Gallery, Los Angeles, CA - 6/30/07\n* ''Seattle Erotic Art Festival'' (Invited Artist) - Seattle Center Exhibition Hall, Seattle, WA - 3/1/08\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:American erotic artists]]\n[[Category:Fetish artists]]\n[[Category:Gay artists]]\n[[Category:LGBT comics creators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pseudonymous artists]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| birth_date = August 14, 1973\n| birth_place = [[Derby, Connecticut]]\n| nationality = US\n| website = {{url|http://drubskin.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Drubskin''', also known as '''\"Drub\"''' (born August 14, 1973; in [[Derby, Connecticut]])<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://nosafeword.com/posts/75_drubskin/|title=Episode 75 \u2013 Drubskin {{!}} NoSafeWord.com|website=nosafeword.com|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref> is a [[fetish artist]] known for his [[homoerotic]] illustrations and [[Erotic comics|erotic comic book]] work. He is based in [[San Diego, California]], and has ties to [[Skinheads Against Racial Prejudice]] and the [[punk subculture|punk]] subculture.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDrawing since the age of 15,<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.leslielohman.org/the-archive/no12/erotic-artist-drub-12.html|title=Leslie Lohman Museum of Gay and Lesbian Art - THE ARCHIVE: No. 13: Summer 2004|website=www.leslielohman.org|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref> Drub's illustrations incorporate various fetishistic interests in footwear, sportswear, subculture-specific clothing, rubber, [[sado-masochism]], and watersports. Most of the men he depicts are part of the [[punk subculture|punk]], [[skinhead]], and [[working class]] communities, drawn in a homo-masculine manner. His work is typically done in a comic book style, with bright colors and heavy line weight.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1991 he moved from Connecticut to Kansas City, Missouri to attend the [[Kansas City Art Institute]] where he eventually earned his Bachelor of Fine Arts in Illustration.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/drubskin.htm|title=Drubskin|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref> In 1995 he was asked to write a first-hand account of his sexual exploits in the punk and skinhead scene for a [[webzine]] called ''Nightcharm'', as a way to promote his art. His pseudonym ''Drub'' is derived from his writing style, as a play on the verb which means to beat or thrash.{{Citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\nHis website and column garnered him attention from the gay male community at large and by 2000 his work began appearing in gay magazines worldwide. Drub began exhibiting his work in the 2000s and in 2003 he had his first international solo art exhibition at Mr. B's in Amsterdam.<ref name=\":2\" /> Drub has also shown his work in galleries in Los Angeles, Toronto, Berlin, Amsterdam, and participates annually in the [[Seattle Erotic Art Festival]]. He has had work published in several publications, including ''[[Freshmen (magazine)|Freshmen]]'', ''Instigator'' and ''[[Blue (Australian magazine)|Blue magazine]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> He sells hand-illustrated greeting cards for Mr. B in Amsterdam and Berlin, and The Leatherman in New York City.\n\n==Features and published works==\n\n* ''Freshmen Magazine'', 2002, illustration for story \"Chemistry\"\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20110816153513/http://www.solanasonline.com/ Solanas O