{"title_page": "Cleveland Browns relocation controversy", "text_new": "{{short description|Complicated NFL franchise move}}\n[[File:Cleveland Municipal Stadium last game played in the stadium December 17, 1995.jpg|thumb|200px|upright|[[Cleveland Stadium]], where the Browns played until [[1995 NFL season|1995]].]]\n\nThe '''Cleveland Browns relocation controversy''', sometimes called \"'''The Move'''\" by fans,<ref>{{cite book|last=Dyer|first=Bob|title=The Top 20 Moments in Cleveland Sports History: Tremendous Tales of Heroes and Heartbreaks|year=2007|publisher=Gray & Company|pages=277\u2013291|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Ss1kgr1u-EC&pg=PA277 |isbn=9781598510300|accessdate=June 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=LeBron James makes his pick: He's going to Miami|url=http://www.nba.com/2010/news/07/08/lebron.decision/index.html|agency=Associated Press|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 9, 2010|accessdate=July 10, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100711003820/http://www.nba.com/2010/news/07/08/lebron.decision/index.html|archive-date=July 11, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> was the decision by then-Browns owner [[Art Modell]] to [[relocation of professional sports teams|move]] the [[National Football League]] (NFL)'s [[Cleveland Browns]] from its long-time home of [[Cleveland]] to [[Baltimore]] during the [[1995 NFL season]]. Subsequent legal actions by the city of Cleveland and Browns season ticket holders led the NFL to broker a compromise that saw the Browns franchise, history, records, and intellectual property remain in Cleveland. In return, Modell was permitted to establish a new franchise, the [[Baltimore Ravens]] and was allowed to transfer the football organization under his control to the new franchise. The Ravens are officially regarded by the NFL as an [[expansion team]] that began play in {{nfly|1996}}. As nobody was prepared to purchase and operate a franchise for the [[1996 NFL season|1996 season]] in [[Cleveland Stadium]], the NFL deactivated the Browns franchise and the city of Cleveland agreed to demolish the stadium and build a [[FirstEnergy Stadium (Cleveland)|new stadium]] on the same site. In exchange the NFL agreed to reactivate the Browns by the [[1999 NFL season|1999 season]] by adding a team or moving one from another city. In 1998, the NFL decided to establish its 31st football organization in Cleveland and sold the Browns franchise to a new owner for $530 million.<ref name=\"Lerner wins Browns\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir |first=Richard |title=Lerner Wins Browns for $530 Million |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/09/sports/pro-football-lerner-wins-browns-for-530-million.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Up1RTEd?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/09/sports/pro-football-lerner-wins-browns-for-530-million.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=September 9, 1998 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The \"new\" Browns recruited players through an [[1999 NFL expansion draft|expansion draft]] and resumed play in 1999.\n\nThis compromise, which was unprecedented in North American professional sports, has since been cited in franchise moves and agreements in other leagues, including ones in [[Major League Baseball]], [[Major League Soccer]], the [[National Basketball Association]], and the [[National Hockey League]].\n\n==Dissatisfaction with Cleveland Stadium==\n[[File:1980-modell-browns crop.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Art Modell.]]\n\nIn 1975, knowing that Municipal Stadium was costing the city over $300,000 annually to operate, then-Browns owner [[Art Modell]] signed a 25-year lease in which he agreed to incur these expenses in exchange for: quasi-ownership of the stadium, a portion of his annual profits, and capital improvements to the stadium at his expense.<ref>{{cite book |last=Henkel |first=Frank |title=Cleveland Browns History |publisher=Arcadia |date=2005 |pages=102 }}</ref> Modell's new company, Stadium Corporation, paid the city annual rents of $150,000 for the first five years and $200,000 afterwards.\n\nModell had originally promised never to move the Browns. He had publicly criticized the [[History of the Baltimore Colts|Baltimore Colts]]' [[Baltimore Colts relocation to Indianapolis|move]] to [[Indianapolis]], and had testified in favor of the NFL in court cases where the league unsuccessfully tried to stop [[Al Davis]] from moving the [[Oakland Raiders]] to Los Angeles.\n\nHowever, Modell refused to share the suite revenue with the [[Cleveland Indians]], who also played at Cleveland Stadium, even though much of the revenues were generated during baseball games.\n\nIn 1990, the Indians convinced local governments and voters to build a new ballpark and give the suite revenue to the baseball corporation.<ref name=\"SIMunson1\">{{cite web|last=Munson|first=Lester|title=A Busted Play|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1995/12/04/208720/a-busted-play|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=December 4, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=henkel102>{{harvnb|Henkel|2005|p=102}}</ref> Modell, mistakenly believing that his revenues were not endangered, decided not to participate in the [[Gateway Sports and Entertainment Complex|Gateway Project]] that built [[Jacobs Field]] for the Indians and [[Gund Arena]] for the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].<ref name=ModellRefuse>{{cite news|last=Naymik|first=Mark|title=Art Modell was offered a stadium for the Cleveland Browns and passed|url=http://www.cleveland.com/naymik/index.ssf/2012/09/art_modell_gateway_stadium.html|work=[[The Plain Dealer]]|date=September 13, 2012|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> Modell's assumptions proved incorrect, and Stadium Corporation's suite revenues declined sharply when the Indians moved to Jacobs Field in 1994.<ref name=henkel102/> Soaring player salaries and deficits put additional financial pressure on the Browns' owner. Modell claimed to have lost $21 million between 1993 and 1994.<ref name=\"McFaddenNYTimes\">{{cite news|last=McFadden|first=Robert D.|title=Art Modell, Owner of Browns, Then Ravens, Dies at 87|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/sports/football/art-modell-nfl-owner-of-browns-then-ravens-is-dead-at-87.html?pagewanted=all|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 6, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625035500/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/sports/football/art-modell-nfl-owner-of-browns-then-ravens-is-dead-at-87.html?pagewanted=all|archivedate=June 25, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=February 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Announcing the move==\nAfter Modell realized how much revenue he lost from the Indians moving out of Cleveland Stadium, he requested an issue be placed on the ballot to provide $175 million in tax dollars to refurbish the outmoded and declining Cleveland Stadium.<ref name=NYTSmith>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Timothy|title=Baltimore Browns May Be a Done Deal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/04/sports/football-baltimore-browns-may-be-a-done-deal.html?src=pm&pagewanted=all|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 4, 1995|accessdate=March 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nEntering the [[1995 NFL season|1995 season]], the Browns, coached by [[Bill Belichick]], were coming off a [[1994\u201395 NFL playoffs|playoff season]] in which the team finished 11\u20135 and advanced to the second round of the playoffs.  ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' predicted that the Browns would represent the [[American Football Conference|AFC]] in [[Super Bowl XXX]] at the end of the season, and the team started 3-1, but they then lost their next three games.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zimmerman|first=Paul|title=Postseason Predictions|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1007071/index.htm|work=Sports Illustrated|date=September 4, 1995|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628174746/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1007071/index.htm|archivedate=June 28, 2010|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=1995browns>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1995.htm|title=1995 Cleveland Browns|publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 1995, with the team at 4\u20135,<ref name=1995browns/> Modell announced in a press conference at [[Camden Yards]] that he had signed a deal to move the Browns to [[Baltimore]] in [[1996 NFL season|1996]] \u2013 a move which would return the NFL to that city since the [[History of the Baltimore Colts|Colts]] [[Baltimore Colts relocation to Indianapolis|moved]] to [[Indianapolis]] after the [[1983 NFL season|1983 season]].<ref name=henkel102/><ref name=\"Morgan1\">{{cite news|last=Morgan|first=Jon|title=Unforgettable is what it's been|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/bal-modell110696-story.html|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 6, 1996|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> Modell said he felt the city of Cleveland did not have the funding nor political will to build a first-class stadium.<ref name=\"InsideBrownsDeal\">{{cite news|last=Morgan|first=Jon|title=Inside the Browns Deal|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/bal-modell121795-story.html|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=December 17, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> The very next day, on November 7, Cleveland voters overwhelmingly approved the aforementioned tax issue to remodel Cleveland Stadium.<ref name=\"sandomir\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|title=A City Fights To Save The Browns|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/12/sports/pro-football-a-city-fights-to-save-the-browns.html?ref=art_modell&pagewanted=all|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 12, 1995|accessdate=August 7, 2010}}</ref> Despite this, Modell ruled out a reversal of his decision, saying his relationship with Cleveland had been irrevocably severed. \"The bridge is down, burned, disappeared\", he said. \"There's not even a canoe there for me.\"<ref name=\"Modell bridges burned\">{{cite news|title=Modell: franchise movement is bad (but I'm still going)|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=November 8, 1995|agency=Associated Press|page=25}}</ref>\n\n==Initial reaction==\nThe City of Cleveland sued Modell, the Browns, Stadium Corp, the [[Maryland Stadium Authority]], and the authority's director, John A. Moag Jr., in ''City of Cleveland v. Cleveland Browns, et al.'', Cuyahoga County Court of Common Pleas Case No. CV-95-297833, for breaching the Browns' lease, which required the team to play its home games at Cleveland Stadium for several years beyond 1995, filing an injunction to keep the Browns in the city until at least 1998. Several other lawsuits were filed by fans and ticket holders.<ref name=\"sandomir\"/><ref name=\"SIRushin1\">{{cite news|last=Rushin|first=Steve|title=The Heart of a City: Cleveland won round 1 in what will be an agonizing battle to hold on to its beloved Browns|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1995/12/04/208707/the-heart-of-a-city-cleveland-won-round-1-in-what-will-be-an-agonizing-battle-to-hold-on-to-its-beloved-browns|work=Sports Illustrated|date=December 4, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> The [[United States Congress]] even held hearings on the matter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-863689.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104145105/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-863689.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-11-04|title=Franchise Relocation Curb Sought on Hill|work=Washington Post|accessdate=2010-08-07|date=1995-11-30}}</ref><ref name=\"CSPAN Debate\">{{cite video|title=Cleveland Browns Move to Baltimore Debate|url=http://www.c-span.org/video/?68668-1/cleveland-browns-move-baltimore-debate|publisher=[[C-SPAN]]|date=December 1, 1995|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nActor/comedian [[Drew Carey]] returned to his hometown of Cleveland on November 26, 1995, to host \"Fan Jam\" in protest of the proposed move. A protest was held in [[Pittsburgh]] during the Browns' game there against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], but [[Monday Night Football|ABC]], the network broadcasting the game (and also the home of [[The Drew Carey Show|Carey's new sitcom that had just premiered]]), declined to cover or mention the protest. That game was one of the few instances that Steelers fans and Browns fans were supportive of each other, as fans in Pittsburgh felt that Modell was robbing their team of their long-standing [[Browns-Steelers rivalry|rivalry with the Browns]].<ref name=\"sandomir\"/> Browns fans reacted with anger to the news,<ref name=\"SIRushin1\"/> wearing hats and T-shirts that read \"Muck Fodell\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alandlarry.photoshelter.com/image/I00002URgxShCx8g|title=Muck Fodell|date=September 4, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn the field, the Browns stumbled to finish 5\u201311 after the announcement, ahead of only the [[expansion team|expansion]] [[Jacksonville Jaguars]], to whom they lost twice, in the [[AFC North|AFC Central]], becoming the first team in the NFL's modern era to lose twice to a first-year expansion team.<ref name=1995browns/> Virtually all of the team's sponsors pulled their support,<ref name=\"sandomir\"/> leaving Cleveland Stadium devoid of advertising during the team's final weeks.  After the announcement, the team lost all their home games except the final, in which they defeated the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] 26-10.<ref name=henkel103/> The game itself was [[National Football League television blackout policies|blacked out on television]] locally, but [[NFL on NBC|NBC]] did broadcast extensive pregame coverage from Cleveland.\n\n==Settlement==\nAfter extensive talks between the NFL, the Browns, and officials of the two cities, Cleveland accepted a legal settlement that would keep the Browns legacy in Cleveland. On February 9, 1996, the NFL announced that the Browns franchise would be 'deactivated' for three years, and that [[FirstEnergy Stadium (Cleveland)|a new stadium]] would be built for a new Browns team, as either an expansion team or a team moved from another city, that would begin play in 1999. Modell would in turn then be granted a new franchise (the 31st NFL franchise), for Baltimore. Because he was permitted to retain the current contracts of players and other football personnel, and changed the name of his corporate entity from Cleveland Browns, Inc. to Baltimore Ravens, Inc.,<ref>https://caselaw.findlaw.com/oh-supreme-court/1184303.html</ref> Modell is typically reckoned to have moved the football organization, but not the franchise itself. The settlement stipulated that the reactivated team for Cleveland would retain the Browns' name, colors, history, records, awards, and archives. The move was approved by league owners after a 25\u20132 vote with three abstentions.<ref name=henkel103>{{harvnb|Henkel|2005|p=103}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Agreement between the NFL, Cleveland |url= http://www.nfl.com/browns/agreement.html |work=[[NFL.com]] |date=February 8, 1996 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/19961112100905/http://www.nfl.com/browns/agreement.html|archivedate=November 12, 1996|accessdate=June 4, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Shapiro |first=Leonard |title=Owners Approve Move of NFL Team to Baltimore |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1996/02/10/owners-approve-move-of-nfl-team-to-baltimore/62005513-0215-46f0-9236-2eefbaae9583/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=February 10, 1996|accessdate=September 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn additional stipulation was that in any future realignment plan, the Browns would be placed in a division with the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] and [[Cincinnati Bengals]], because of long-standing rivalries with those two teams.<ref name=realign>{{cite news|last=Stellino|first=Vito|title=NFL to try realign play|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1999-10-07/sports/9910070115_1_nfc-central-nfc-west-division-afc-central|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=October 7, 1999|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> Upon their reactivation in 1999, the Browns were placed back in the AFC Central with the Steelers and Bengals, as well as the Ravens, [[Tennessee Titans|Titans]], and [[Jacksonville Jaguars|Jaguars]]. This arrangement put teams from Baltimore, Cleveland and Pittsburgh in the same division for the first time in NFL history. When the NFL realigned into divisions of four teams for the [[2002 NFL season|2002 season]], Cleveland, Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, and Baltimore remained together in the new [[AFC North]]. Tennessee, Jacksonville, [[Indianapolis Colts|Indianapolis]] (from the [[AFC East]]), and the new [[Houston Texans]] were placed in the new [[AFC South]].\n\nThe only other active NFL team to temporarily suspend operations without merging with another was Cleveland's previous NFL team, the [[Cleveland Rams]], during the 1943 season at the height of [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ech.cwru.edu/ech-cgi/article.pl?id=CR3|title=The Cleveland Rams|work=Encyclopedia of Cleveland History|publisher=[[Case Western Reserve University]]|accessdate=2009-01-12}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath and legacy==\nThe return of the NFL to Baltimore compelled the departure of the professional football team already in Baltimore at the time, the [[Grey Cup]] champion [[Baltimore Stallions]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] (CFL). Although they had drawn respectable fan support during their two seasons in Baltimore, Stallions owner [[Jim Speros]] knew his team could not compete with an NFL team and opted to establish a new franchise in [[Montreal]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Klingaman|first=Mike|title=Once, the Stallions rode high|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2000-11-26/sports/0011260151_1_baltimore-stallions-grey-cup-stallions-won/2|newspaper=The Baltimore Sun|date=November 26, 2000|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> They subsequently adopted the name and assumed the history of the team that previously played in the city, the [[Montreal Alouettes|Alouettes]], who had ceased operations in 1987. Like the Browns, the Alouettes (who incidentally were originally founded in 1946, the same year as the Browns) were formally recognized as having resumed operations after a hiatus although unlike the Browns, the decision to reactivate the Montreal franchise in such a manner that it was considered a continuation of the previous franchise had not been previously planned and was made retroactively at the time of their revival. Much of the Stallions' roster and most of the Stallions' other football personnel made the move to Montreal, although unlike Modell, Speros was not formally given the sort of successor rights to existing contracts that would have allowed him to transplant his football organization to Montreal in the same manner was done from Cleveland to Baltimore - this would have been problematic due to the CFL's requirement that the re-activated Alouettes adhere to roster limits on American players (then called \"imports\") that the defunct U.S. CFL teams had not been bound to. The ability of Speros to retain the core of his championship roster to the point that the transaction superficially appeared to be a \"move\" was the result of a [[gentlemen's agreement]] between Speros and the other CFL teams. CFL commissioner [[Larry Smith (Canadian politician)|Larry Smith]], an Alouettes alumnus who was keen to ensure the revived Montreal franchise was an immediate contender, had pressured the other CFL teams to agree not to aggressively pursue what were technically [[free agent]]s.\n\nFocus groups, a telephone survey, and a fan contest were all held to help select a new name for Modell's team. Starting with a list of over 100 possible names, the team's management reduced it to 17. From there, focus groups of a total of 200 Baltimore area residents reduced the list of names to six, and then a phone survey of 1000 people trimmed it down to three, Marauders, Americans, and Ravens. Finally, a fan contest drawing 33,288 voters picked \"[[Baltimore Ravens|Ravens]]\", a name that alludes to the famous poem, \"[[The Raven]]\", by [[Edgar Allan Poe]], who spent the latter part of his life in Baltimore, and is also buried there.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baltimore Ravens History|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/teams/baltimore-ravens/team-history/|publisher=[[Pro Football Hall of Fame]]|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> The team also adopted purple and black as their team colors, a stark contrast to the brown and orange colors of the Browns.<ref>{{cite web|title=Naming Baltimore's Team: Ravens|url=http://www.baltimoreravens.com/team/history/naming-baltimores-team.html|publisher=Baltimore Ravens|accessdate=June 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708123713/http://www.baltimoreravens.com/team/history/naming-baltimores-team.html|archive-date=July 8, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The former Colts Marching Band, which remained in Baltimore after the Colts moved to Indianapolis, was subsequently renamed the [[Baltimore's Marching Ravens]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Band History|url=http://www.baltimoreravens.com/ravenstown/marching-ravens/history.html|publisher=Baltimore Ravens|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> Along with the [[San Francisco 49ers]], [[Buffalo Bills]], and [[Washington Redskins]], the Ravens are one of only four NFL teams with an official [[marching band]].\n\nModell's move to Baltimore came amid an unprecedented flurry of similar threats \u2014 and actual moves \u2014<ref name=\"SIKing1\">{{cite news|last=King|first=Peter|title=Down...And Out: Citing his crushing debts, Art Modell is taking his Browns to Baltimore|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1995/11/13/208163/downand-out-citing-his-crushing-debts-art-modell-is-taking-his-browns-to-baltimore|magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=November 13, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"SICrothers1\">{{cite news|last=Crothers|first=Tim|title=The Shakedown: Greedy owners are threatening to move their teams if demands for new stadiums, better lease deals, etc., aren't met|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1995/06/19/204044/the-shakedown-greedy-owners-are-threatening-to-move-their-teams-if-demands-for-new-stadiums-better-lease-deals-etc-arent-met|magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=June 19, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> that fueled 12 new stadiums throughout the NFL. The Seahawks, Buccaneers, Bengals, Lions, Cardinals, and Bears used the threat of moving to coerce their respective cities to build new stadiums with public funds.<ref name=\"SIKing1\" /><ref name=\"SICrothers1\"/> Modell's team was one of four that actually moved between [[1995 NFL season|1995]] and [[1997 NFL season|1997]]: Los Angeles lost [[History of the National Football League in Los Angeles|both of its teams]] for the 1995 season, as the [[Oakland Raiders|Raiders]] moved back to Oakland and the [[Los Angeles Rams|Rams]] moved east to St. Louis (the Rams would later move back to Los Angeles in 2016); and the [[History of the Houston Oilers|Houston Oilers]] move to [[Tennessee]] in 1997, where they become the [[Tennessee Titans]] two years later.\n\nAfter several NFL teams threatened to move to Cleveland to become the reactivated Browns (most notably the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Williams|first=Charean|title=Tampa Still Hopeful Bucs Will Stay Put|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-12-07/sports/9512061680_1_tampa-bay-buccaneers-joel-glazer-cleveland/2|newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|date=December 7, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref>), the NFL decided in 1998 to make the reactivated Browns an [[expansion team]], which while it temporarily gave the league an odd number of teams (causing at least one team to be off in each of the 17 weeks of the NFL season from 1999\u20132001), it also eliminated any possibility of an existing franchise giving up its own identity for the Browns and thus prevented more [[lawsuit]]s. In an ironic twist, [[Al Lerner]]\u2014who helped Modell move to Baltimore\u2014was granted ownership of the reactivated Browns;<ref name=\"lerner\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|title=PRO FOOTBALL; Lerner Wins Browns for $530 Million|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/09/sports/pro-football-lerner-wins-browns-for-530-million.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 9, 1998|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> his son [[Randy Lerner|Randy]] took over ownership after Al's death in 2002 before selling the team to [[Pilot Flying J]] CEO [[Jimmy Haslam]] in 2012. From its beginning, the odd number of teams and the ensuing awkward scheduling was considered a temporary arrangement pending the addition of a 32nd NFL franchise \u2013 although Los Angeles was heavily favored, it was ultimately the [[Houston Texans]] who were created as the 32nd team to replace the [[Tennessee Titans|Oilers]] in [[Houston|Houston, Texas]] for the [[2002 NFL season]] to give the league once again an even number of teams. Following this decision, Los Angeles became the favored destination for owners threatening to move their teams until the [[History of the St. Louis Rams|St. Louis Rams]] finally returned to Los Angeles for the [[2016 NFL season|2016 season]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Rams to Return to Los Angeles|url=http://www.therams.com/news-and-events/article-1/Rams-to-Return-to-Los-Angeles/802b4e16-671e-4864-97b6-943115cdc4cf|publisher=St. Louis Rams|date=January 12, 2016|accessdate=January 13, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120221040/http://www.therams.com/news-and-events/article-1/Rams-to-Return-to-Los-Angeles/802b4e16-671e-4864-97b6-943115cdc4cf|archive-date=January 20, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> followed by the [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]] (who had previously called L.A. home in the early days of the [[American Football League]]) one year later.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chargers to Relocate to Los Angeles|url=https://www.chargers.com/news/2017/01/12/chargers-relocate-los-angeles|publisher=San Diego Chargers|date=January 12, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112171416/https://www.chargers.com/news/2017/01/12/chargers-relocate-los-angeles|archivedate=January 12, 2017|accessdate=June 10, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe reactivated Browns have had only two winning seasons since returning to the NFL in 1999: a 9\u20137 finish in [[2002 Cleveland Browns season|2002]] which also saw the team clinch a [[wild card (sports)|wild card]] spot in the playoffs, and a 10\u20136 finish in [[2007 Cleveland Browns season|2007]] while barely missing the playoffs. Meanwhile, the Ravens have been more successful, reaching the playoffs eight times since [[2000 NFL season|2000]] and winning [[Super Bowl XXXV]] and [[Super Bowl XLVII]], often to the dismay of Browns fans.<ref name=henkel103/><ref name=dismay>{{cite web|author=NFL Network|title=Top 10 snakebit franchises|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d8186c861/article/top-10-snakebit-franchises|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|date=May 31, 2010|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> Longtime [[placekicker]] [[Matt Stover]] was the last remaining Ravens player that played for the Modell-owned Browns \u2013 he departed the Ravens following the [[2008 NFL season|2008 season]] when the team chose not to re-sign him, finishing his career with the Indianapolis Colts.<ref name=stover>{{cite news|last=Grossi|first=Tony|title=Indianapolis Colts kicker Matt Stover has many ties to Cleveland Browns|url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2010/02/the_colts_matt_stover_has_many.html|newspaper=[[The Plain Dealer]]|date=February 5, 2010|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> General manager and former Browns [[tight end]] [[Ozzie Newsome]] (who was in a front-office role under Modell in Cleveland) remained with the Ravens until his retirement in 2018.\n\nThe move would also have an effect in [[Pittsburgh]]. Steelers owner [[Dan Rooney]] was one of two owners to oppose Modell's move to Baltimore because of a mutual respect for the team and the fans. Because of the move, the [[Browns\u2013Steelers rivalry]], arguably one of the most heated rivalries in the NFL, has somewhat cooled in Pittsburgh due to the new Browns' lack of success. The [[Steelers\u2013Ravens rivalry]] is considered the [[spiritual successor]] by fans in Pittsburgh and is one of the most heated current rivalries in the NFL.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 New NFL Rivalries|url=http://images.si.com/multimedia/photo_gallery/2005/12/15/gallery.newrivals/content.9.html|magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=December 15, 2005|accessdate=June 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219071621/http://images.si.com/multimedia/photo_gallery/2005/12/15/gallery.newrivals/content.9.html|archive-date=February 19, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Since returning to the NFL, the Browns and Steelers rivalry has been largely one-sided in favor of Pittsburgh; although the rivalry is not as intense in Pittsburgh, Browns fans still consider it their top rivalry despite the Browns' recent struggles against the Steelers.\n\nBecause of continual financial hardships, the NFL directed Modell to initiate the sale of his franchise. On March 27, 2000, NFL owners approved the sale of 49 percent of the Ravens to [[Steve Bisciotti]].<ref name=bisciotti1>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=APAB&d_place=APAB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F89B8E00CF79536&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Bisciotti approved as co-owner of Ravens|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=2011-03-12|date=2000-03-27}}</ref> In the deal, Bisciotti had an option to purchase the remaining 51 percent for $325 million in 2004 from Art Modell. On April 8, 2004, the NFL approved Steve Bisciotti's purchase of the majority stake in the club.<ref name=bisciotti2>{{cite news|title=Bisciotti takes control of Ravens|url=http://www.nfl.com/teams/story/BAL/7242066|agency=Associated Press|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|date=April 8, 2004|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616162759/http://www.nfl.com/teams/story/BAL/7242066|archivedate=June 16, 2004|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Modell later retired and had relinquished control of the Ravens, he is still despised in Cleveland, not only for moving the Browns, but also for his firing of legendary head coach [[Paul Brown]] in 1963. Some considered the Browns' move and subsequent lawsuits costing Modell a spot in the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]], which is in [[Canton, Ohio]], 60 miles south of Cleveland and is both part of the Cleveland television market and part of the Browns' territorial rights.<ref name=LivingstonModell>{{cite news|last=Livingston|first=Bill|title=Upon further review, Art Modell's case for Canton gets weaker every year|url=http://www.cleveland.com/livingston/index.ssf/2010/12/upon_further_review_art_modell.html|newspaper=[[The Plain Dealer]]|date=December 12, 2010|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Clayton|first=John|title=Modell was mostly a model owner|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/8344634/nfl-modell-was-model-owner-many-ways|publisher=ESPN|date=September 6, 2012|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> Modell died in 2012, having never returned to Cleveland.<ref name=\"McFaddenNYTimes\" /> The Browns were the only home team that did not acknowledge, much less commemorate, Modell's death the following Sunday. The team opted not to do so at the request of David Modell, who feared that the announcement would be met with anger by Browns fans still upset about the move.<ref>https://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2012/09/cleveland_browns_cancel_their.html</ref>\n\n==Effect on teams in other sports leagues==\n\n===Major League Baseball===\n*The [[Minnesota Twins]], when they signed their deal with [[Hennepin County, Minnesota]] for [[Target Field]] in 2006, agreed to a provision that was signed into law that allows the state of Minnesota the right of first refusal to buy the team if it is ever sold. Also, it requires that the name, colors, [[World Series]] trophies, and history of the team remain in Minnesota if the Twins are ever moved out of state. The deal is similar to what Modell agreed to with the city of Cleveland during the move.\n\n===Major League Soccer===\n*In December 2005, the [[San Jose Earthquakes]] moved to [[Houston]] to become the [[Houston Dynamo]]. At the time, it was announced by the league that while players and staff would move with the team, the team name, colors, logo, and records (including two championship trophies) would stay in San Jose for when a new expansion team arrives.<ref>{{cite news|last=Halpin|first=Jason|title=Earthquakes set to move to Houston|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2010/01/22/earthquakes-set-move-houston|publisher=MLS Digital|date=December 15, 2005|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=San Jose's MLS team moving to Houston|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/mls/quakes/2005-12-15-relocation-houston_x.htm|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=December 15, 2005|accessdate=2009-03-02}}</ref> In 2008, the Earthquakes returned under the ownership of [[Lew Wolff]].\n*The Browns move in 1996 had a direct effect on a proposed move of [[Columbus Crew SC]] to [[Austin, Texas]]; the Modell Law, which was implemented in 1996, prohibits sports teams that benefited from public facilities or financial assistance from moving to another city without a six-month notice and an attempt to sell the team to a local ownership group. A lawsuit was filed by Ohio Attorney General [[Mike DeWine]] and the [[Columbus, Ohio|city of Columbus]]. Rather ironically, Cleveland Browns owner [[Jimmy Haslam|Jimmy]] and [[Dee Haslam]], along with other investors, offered to buy the Columbus Crew in order to keep them in Columbus.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Statement from Dee and Jimmy Haslam on interest in Columbus Crew|url=https://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/statement-from-dee-and-jimmy-haslam-on-interest-in-columbus-crew|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=ClevelandBrowns.com|date=October 12, 2018|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> The proposed sale would sell the operational rights of the Crew to the new buyers, while previous Crew owner [[Anthony Precourt]] would keep his equity stake in MLS, and would have ownership of a [[Austin FC|new franchise in Austin]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wahl |first1=Grant |title=Columbus Crew Set to Avoid Austin Move After New Local Buyers Emerge |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2018/10/12/columbus-crew-saved-austin-move-precourt-haslam-mls |accessdate=3 December 2018 |publisher=Sports Illustrated |date=12 October 2018}}</ref> The sale of the Crew to Haslam's ownership group was announced as agreed to on December 28, 2018, and was completed in January 2019. As part of the deal, the lawsuit was dismissed that day; the Modell Law remains untested as a result.<ref>{{cite news|last=Carlisle|first=Jeff|title=MLS: Haslam family has 'agreement in principle' to take over Columbus Crew SC|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/major-league-soccer/story/3738154/mls-haslam-family-has-agreement-in-principle-to-take-over-columbus-crew-sc|agency=ESPN|date=December 28, 2018|accessdate=2018-12-28}}</ref>\n\n===National Hockey League===\n*After the [[Quebec Nordiques]] moved to [[Denver]] in 1995 to become the [[Colorado Avalanche]], the franchise's retired numbers, name, logos, and historical stats remained in Quebec City and are expected to be used by any [[Potential National Hockey League expansion#Quebec City|future Quebec City NHL franchise]] that may be established or move there. Upon arrival at Denver, the Nordiques' retired numbers were placed back into circulation.\n*In 2011, a team took the name of a city's previous team (as the Baltimore Stallions did when the Ravens forced their move to Montreal). That saga began in 1996, when the [[Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)|Winnipeg Jets]] left [[Manitoba]] for [[Phoenix, Arizona]], and become the [[Phoenix Coyotes]]. Thirteen years later, the [[Phoenix Coyotes bankruptcy and sale|Coyotes went bankrupt]] and were taken over by the league. Winnipeg-based [[True North Sports & Entertainment]] offered to buy the team and return it to Winnipeg, where it presumably would have re-assumed the Jets' name and history. The NHL turned down that proposal \u2014 they were still looking for an owner to operate the franchise in Phoenix, whose municipal government had agreed to subsidize the team's financial losses \u2014 but said that moving the team back to Winnipeg was their preferred backup option. But when the [[Atlanta Thrashers]] came up for sale a year later, the league decided that there was no chance of finding an owner to operate a franchise in Georgia, so they arranged for True North to purchase the Atlanta franchise and move it to Winnipeg for the {{NHL Year|2011}} NHL season. The league decided to let True North and the [[Winnipeg Jets|new Jets]] use the identity of the old Winnipeg team, but not its history, which remained in Arizona with the Coyotes. The new Jets organization highlighted this change by quickly re-issuing the team's #9 jersey \u2014 retired by the old Jets in honor of superstar [[Bobby Hull]] \u2014 to forward [[Evander Kane]], who had worn the number in Atlanta.\n\n===National Basketball Association===\n*The [[Seattle SuperSonics relocation to Oklahoma City|Seattle SuperSonics' move to Oklahoma City]] in 2008 included an agreement that the [[Seattle SuperSonics|SuperSonics]]' name, logo, colors, and history would all be left in [[Seattle]]. This also includes banners and trophies, which would be displayed in [[Museum of History & Industry (MOHAI)|a museum]] until a new franchise is brought to Seattle to be hung from the rafters of its arena.<ref>{{cite press release|title=THE PROFESSIONAL BASKETBALL CLUB, LLC AND CITY OF SEATTLE SETTLEMENT AGREEMENT|url=http://www.seattle.gov/Documents/Departments/CityAttorney/Reports/2008SonicsSettlementAgreement.pdf#page=3|publisher=City of Seattle, Washington|date=July 2, 2008|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> The original franchise, now the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]], continue to keep the SuperSonics tie-ins, including records, championships, and retired numbers, until a new SuperSonics franchise is brought to Seattle. Both the Thunder and a potential new SuperSonics franchise would \"share\" the original SuperSonics history.\n*Similar to the Winnipeg Jets scenario in the NHL, the NBA first entered [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]] in {{nbay|1988|start}} in the form of the [[Charlotte Hornets]]. That team remained in Charlotte until moving to [[New Orleans]] after the {{nbay|2001|app=season}}, retaining the Hornets name. The league returned to Charlotte for the {{nbay|2004|app=season}} with a new team, the Charlotte Bobcats. After the New Orleans franchise changed its name to the [[New Orleans Pelicans|Pelicans]] after the {{nbay|2012|app=season}}, the Bobcats announced that they would reclaim the \"Hornets\" name effective with the {{nbay|2014|app=season}}. When the name change from Bobcats to Hornets became official in May 2014, it was also announced that the Hornets, Pelicans, and the NBA had reached an agreement that all history and records of the original Charlotte Hornets would be transferred to the revived Hornets. As a result, the Hornets are now considered to have been established in 1988, suspended operations in 2002, and resumed in 2004 (as the Bobcats, then again changing their name back to the Hornets in 2014), while the Pelicans are now considered a 2002 expansion team.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Charlotte Hornets Name Returns to Carolinas|url=http://www.nba.com/hornets/charlotte-hornets-name-returns-carolinas|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=Hornets.com|date=May 20, 2014|accessdate=May 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Relocation of professional sports teams]]\n* [[Cleveland sports curse]]\n* [[Browns\u2013Ravens rivalry]]\n* [[History of the Cleveland Browns]]\n* [[History of the Baltimore Ravens]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|title=Cleveland Browns History|author=Henkel, Frank M.|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7385-3428-2|ref=CITEREFHenkel2005}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.latimes.com/sports/bal-modell121795,0,1763650,full.story Inside the Browns deal.] A ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' article on the Cleveland Browns' move.\n* {{YouTube|6J7Sc2Uaa0E|Cleveland Browns relocation}} on [[The NFL on NBC pregame show]].\n{{Cleveland Browns}}\n{{Baltimore Ravens}}\n{{NFL on NBC}}\n\n[[Category:National Football League controversies]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Ravens]]\n[[Category:National Football League franchise relocations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Complicated NFL franchise move}}\n[[File:Cleveland Municipal Stadium last game played in the stadium December 17, 1995.jpg|thumb|200px|upright|[[Cleveland Stadium]], where the Browns played until [[1995 NFL season|1995]].]]\n\nThe '''Cleveland Browns relocation controversy''', sometimes called \"'''The Move'''\" by fans,<ref>{{cite book|last=Dyer|first=Bob|title=The Top 20 Moments in Cleveland Sports History: Tremendous Tales of Heroes and Heartbreaks|year=2007|publisher=Gray & Company|pages=277\u2013291|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Ss1kgr1u-EC&pg=PA277 |isbn=9781598510300|accessdate=June 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=LeBron James makes his pick: He's going to Miami|url=http://www.nba.com/2010/news/07/08/lebron.decision/index.html|agency=Associated Press|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 9, 2010|accessdate=July 10, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100711003820/http://www.nba.com/2010/news/07/08/lebron.decision/index.html|archive-date=July 11, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> was the decision by then-Browns owner [[Art Modell]] to [[relocation of professional sports teams|move]] the [[National Football League]] (NFL)'s [[Cleveland Browns]] from its long-time home of [[Cleveland]] to [[Baltimore]] during the [[1995 NFL season]]. Subsequent legal actions by the city of Cleveland and Browns season ticket holders led the NFL to broker a compromise that saw the Browns franchise, history, records, and intellectual property remain in Cleveland. In return, Modell was permitted to establish a new franchise, the [[Baltimore Ravens]] and was allowed to transfer the football organization under his control to the new franchise. The Ravens are officially regarded by the NFL as an [[expansion team]] that began play in {{nfly|1996}}. As nobody was prepared to purchase and operate a franchise for the [[1996 NFL season|1996 season]] in [[Cleveland Stadium]], the NFL deactivated the Browns franchise and the city of Cleveland agreed to demolish the stadium and build a [[FirstEnergy Stadium (Cleveland)|new stadium]] on the same site. In exchange the NFL agreed to reactivate the Browns by the [[1999 NFL season|1999 season]] by adding a team or moving one from another city. In 1998, the NFL decided to establish its 31st football organization in Cleveland and sold the Browns franchise to a new owner for $530 million.<ref name=\"Lerner wins Browns\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir |first=Richard |title=Lerner Wins Browns for $530 Million |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/09/sports/pro-football-lerner-wins-browns-for-530-million.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68Up1RTEd?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/09/sports/pro-football-lerner-wins-browns-for-530-million.html |archivedate=June 17, 2012 |accessdate=June 1, 2012 |newspaper=New York Times |date=September 9, 1998 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The \"new\" Browns recruited players through an [[1999 NFL expansion draft|expansion draft]] and resumed play in 1999.\n\nThis compromise, which was unprecedented in North American professional sports, has since been cited in franchise moves and agreements in other leagues, including ones in [[Major League Baseball]], [[Major League Soccer]], the [[National Basketball Association]], and the [[National Hockey League]].\n\n==Dissatisfaction with Cleveland Stadium==\n[[File:1980-modell-browns crop.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Art Modell.]]\n\nIn 1975, knowing that Municipal Stadium was costing the city over $300,000 annually to operate, then-Browns owner [[Art Modell]] signed a 25-year lease in which he agreed to incur these expenses in exchange for: quasi-ownership of the stadium, a portion of his annual profits, and capital improvements to the stadium at his expense.<ref>{{cite book |last=Henkel |first=Frank |title=Cleveland Browns History |publisher=Arcadia |date=2005 |pages=102 }}</ref> Modell's new company, Stadium Corporation, paid the city annual rents of $150,000 for the first five years and $200,000 afterwards.\n\nModell had originally promised never to move the Browns. He had publicly criticized the [[History of the Baltimore Colts|Baltimore Colts]]' [[Baltimore Colts relocation to Indianapolis|move]] to [[Indianapolis]], and had testified in favor of the NFL in court cases where the league unsuccessfully tried to stop [[Al Davis]] from moving the [[Oakland Raiders]] to Los Angeles.\n\nHowever, Modell refused to share the suite revenue with the [[Cleveland Indians]], who also played at Cleveland Stadium, even though much of the revenues were generated during baseball games.\n\nIn 1990, the Indians convinced local governments and voters to build a new ballpark and give the suite revenue to the baseball corporation.<ref name=\"SIMunson1\">{{cite web|last=Munson|first=Lester|title=A Busted Play|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1995/12/04/208720/a-busted-play|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=December 4, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=henkel102>{{harvnb|Henkel|2005|p=102}}</ref> Modell, mistakenly believing that his revenues were not endangered, decided not to participate in the [[Gateway Sports and Entertainment Complex|Gateway Project]] that built [[Jacobs Field]] for the Indians and [[Gund Arena]] for the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].<ref name=ModellRefuse>{{cite news|last=Naymik|first=Mark|title=Art Modell was offered a stadium for the Cleveland Browns and passed|url=http://www.cleveland.com/naymik/index.ssf/2012/09/art_modell_gateway_stadium.html|work=[[The Plain Dealer]]|date=September 13, 2012|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> Modell's assumptions proved incorrect, and Stadium Corporation's suite revenues declined sharply when the Indians moved to Jacobs Field in 1994.<ref name=henkel102/> Soaring player salaries and deficits put additional financial pressure on the Browns' owner. Modell claimed to have lost $21 million between 1993 and 1994.<ref name=\"McFaddenNYTimes\">{{cite news|last=McFadden|first=Robert D.|title=Art Modell, Owner of Browns, Then Ravens, Dies at 87|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/sports/football/art-modell-nfl-owner-of-browns-then-ravens-is-dead-at-87.html?pagewanted=all|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 6, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625035500/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/sports/football/art-modell-nfl-owner-of-browns-then-ravens-is-dead-at-87.html?pagewanted=all|archivedate=June 25, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=February 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Announcing the move==\nAfter Modell realized how much revenue he lost from the Indians moving out of Cleveland Stadium, he requested an issue be placed on the ballot to provide $175 million in tax dollars to refurbish the outmoded and declining Cleveland Stadium.<ref name=NYTSmith>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Timothy|title=Baltimore Browns May Be a Done Deal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/04/sports/football-baltimore-browns-may-be-a-done-deal.html?src=pm&pagewanted=all|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 4, 1995|accessdate=March 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\nEntering the [[1995 NFL season|1995 season]], the Browns, coached by [[Bill Belichick]], were coming off a [[1994\u201395 NFL playoffs|playoff season]] in which the team finished 11\u20135 and advanced to the second round of the playoffs.  ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' predicted that the Browns would represent the [[American Football Conference|AFC]] in [[Super Bowl XXX]] at the end of the season, and the team started 3-1, but they then lost their next three games.<ref>{{cite news|last=Zimmerman|first=Paul|title=Postseason Predictions|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1007071/index.htm|work=Sports Illustrated|date=September 4, 1995|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628174746/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1007071/index.htm|archivedate=June 28, 2010|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=1995browns>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/1995.htm|title=1995 Cleveland Browns|publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com|accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 1995, with the team at 4\u20135,<ref name=1995browns/> Modell announced in a press conference at [[Camden Yards]] that he had signed a deal to move the Browns to [[Baltimore]] in [[1996 NFL season|1996]] \u2013 a move which would return the NFL to that city since the [[History of the Baltimore Colts|Colts]] [[Baltimore Colts relocation to Indianapolis|moved]] to [[Indianapolis]] after the [[1983 NFL season|1983 season]].<ref name=henkel102/><ref name=\"Morgan1\">{{cite news|last=Morgan|first=Jon|title=Unforgettable is what it's been|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/bal-modell110696-story.html|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 6, 1996|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> Modell said he felt the city of Cleveland did not have the funding nor political will to build a first-class stadium.<ref name=\"InsideBrownsDeal\">{{cite news|last=Morgan|first=Jon|title=Inside the Browns Deal|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/bal-modell121795-story.html|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=December 17, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> The very next day, on November 7, Cleveland voters overwhelmingly approved the aforementioned tax issue to remodel Cleveland Stadium.<ref name=\"sandomir\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|title=A City Fights To Save The Browns|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/12/sports/pro-football-a-city-fights-to-save-the-browns.html?ref=art_modell&pagewanted=all|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 12, 1995|accessdate=August 7, 2010}}</ref> Despite this, Modell ruled out a reversal of his decision, saying his relationship with Cleveland had been irrevocably severed. \"The bridge is down, burned, disappeared\", he said. \"There's not even a canoe there for me.\"<ref name=\"Modell bridges burned\">{{cite news|title=Modell: franchise movement is bad (but I'm still going)|newspaper=Toledo Blade|date=November 8, 1995|agency=Associated Press|page=25}}</ref>\n\n==Initial reaction==\nThe City of Cleveland sued Modell, the Browns, Stadium Corp, the [[Maryland Stadium Authority]], and the authority's director, John A. Moag Jr., in ''City of Cleveland v. Cleveland Browns, et al.'', Cuyahoga County Court of Common Pleas Case No. CV-95-297833, for breaching the Browns' lease, which required the team to play its home games at Cleveland Stadium for several years beyond 1995, filing an injunction to keep the Browns in the city until at least 1998. Several other lawsuits were filed by fans and ticket holders.<ref name=\"sandomir\"/><ref name=\"SIRushin1\">{{cite news|last=Rushin|first=Steve|title=The Heart of a City: Cleveland won round 1 in what will be an agonizing battle to hold on to its beloved Browns|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1995/12/04/208707/the-heart-of-a-city-cleveland-won-round-1-in-what-will-be-an-agonizing-battle-to-hold-on-to-its-beloved-browns|work=Sports Illustrated|date=December 4, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> The [[United States Congress]] even held hearings on the matter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-863689.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104145105/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-863689.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-11-04|title=Franchise Relocation Curb Sought on Hill|work=Washington Post|accessdate=2010-08-07|date=1995-11-30}}</ref><ref name=\"CSPAN Debate\">{{cite video|title=Cleveland Browns Move to Baltimore Debate|url=http://www.c-span.org/video/?68668-1/cleveland-browns-move-baltimore-debate|publisher=[[C-SPAN]]|date=December 1, 1995|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nActor/comedian [[Drew Carey]] returned to his hometown of Cleveland on November 26, 1995, to host \"Fan Jam\" in protest of the proposed move. A protest was held in [[Pittsburgh]] during the Browns' game there against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], but [[Monday Night Football|ABC]], the network broadcasting the game (and also the home of [[The Drew Carey Show|Carey's new sitcom that had just premiered]]), declined to cover or mention the protest. That game was one of the few instances that Steelers fans and Browns fans were supportive of each other, as fans in Pittsburgh felt that Modell was robbing their team of their long-standing [[Browns-Steelers rivalry|rivalry with the Browns]].<ref name=\"sandomir\"/> Browns fans reacted with anger to the news,<ref name=\"SIRushin1\"/> wearing hats and T-shirts that read \"Muck Fodell\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alandlarry.photoshelter.com/image/I00002URgxShCx8g|title=Muck Fodell|date=September 4, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn the field, the Browns stumbled to finish 5\u201311 after the announcement, ahead of only the [[expansion team|expansion]] [[Jacksonville Jaguars]], to whom they lost twice, in the [[AFC North|AFC Central]], becoming the first team in the NFL's modern era to lose twice to a first-year expansion team.<ref name=1995browns/> Virtually all of the team's sponsors pulled their support,<ref name=\"sandomir\"/> leaving Cleveland Stadium devoid of advertising during the team's final weeks.  After the announcement, the team lost all their home games except the final, in which they defeated the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] 26-10.<ref name=henkel103/> The game itself was [[National Football League television blackout policies|blacked out on television]] locally, but [[NFL on NBC|NBC]] did broadcast extensive pregame coverage from Cleveland.\n\n==Settlement==\nAfter extensive talks between the NFL, the Browns, and officials of the two cities, Cleveland accepted a legal settlement that would keep the Browns legacy in Cleveland. On February 9, 1996, the NFL announced that the Browns franchise would be 'deactivated' for three years, and that [[FirstEnergy Stadium (Cleveland)|a new stadium]] would be built for a new Browns team, as either an expansion team or a team moved from another city, that would begin play in 1999. Modell would in turn then be granted a new franchise (the 31st NFL franchise), for Baltimore. Because he was permitted to retain the current contracts of players and other football personnel, and changed the name of his corporate entity from Cleveland Browns, Inc. to Baltimore Ravens, Inc.,<ref>https://caselaw.findlaw.com/oh-supreme-court/1184303.html</ref> Modell is typically reckoned to have moved the football organization, but not the franchise itself. The settlement stipulated that the reactivated team for Cleveland would retain the Browns' name, colors, history, records, awards, and archives. The move was approved by league owners after a 25\u20132 vote with three abstentions.<ref name=henkel103>{{harvnb|Henkel|2005|p=103}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Agreement between the NFL, Cleveland |url= http://www.nfl.com/browns/agreement.html |work=[[NFL.com]] |date=February 8, 1996 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/19961112100905/http://www.nfl.com/browns/agreement.html|archivedate=November 12, 1996|accessdate=June 4, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Shapiro |first=Leonard |title=Owners Approve Move of NFL Team to Baltimore |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1996/02/10/owners-approve-move-of-nfl-team-to-baltimore/62005513-0215-46f0-9236-2eefbaae9583/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=February 10, 1996|accessdate=September 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn additional stipulation was that in any future realignment plan, the Browns would be placed in a division with the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] and [[Cincinnati Bengals]], because of long-standing rivalries with those two teams.<ref name=realign>{{cite news|last=Stellino|first=Vito|title=NFL to try realign play|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1999-10-07/sports/9910070115_1_nfc-central-nfc-west-division-afc-central|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=October 7, 1999|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> Upon their reactivation in 1999, the Browns were placed back in the AFC Central with the Steelers and Bengals, as well as the Ravens, [[Tennessee Titans|Titans]], and [[Jacksonville Jaguars|Jaguars]]. This arrangement put teams from Baltimore, Cleveland and Pittsburgh in the same division for the first time in NFL history. When the NFL realigned into divisions of four teams for the [[2002 NFL season|2002 season]], Cleveland, Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, and Baltimore remained together in the new [[AFC North]]. Tennessee, Jacksonville, [[Indianapolis Colts|Indianapolis]] (from the [[AFC East]]), and the new [[Houston Texans]] were placed in the new [[AFC South]].\n\nThe only other active NFL team to suspend operations without merging with another was Cleveland's previous NFL team, the [[Cleveland Rams]], during the 1943 season at the height of [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ech.cwru.edu/ech-cgi/article.pl?id=CR3|title=The Cleveland Rams|work=Encyclopedia of Cleveland History|publisher=[[Case Western Reserve University]]|accessdate=2009-01-12}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath and legacy==\nThe return of the NFL to Baltimore compelled the departure of the professional football team already in Baltimore at the time, the [[Grey Cup]] champion [[Baltimore Stallions]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] (CFL). Although they had drawn respectable fan support during their two seasons in Baltimore, Stallions owner [[Jim Speros]] knew his team could not compete with an NFL team and opted to establish a new franchise in [[Montreal]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Klingaman|first=Mike|title=Once, the Stallions rode high|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2000-11-26/sports/0011260151_1_baltimore-stallions-grey-cup-stallions-won/2|newspaper=The Baltimore Sun|date=November 26, 2000|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> They subsequently adopted the name and assumed the history of the team that previously played in the city, the [[Montreal Alouettes|Alouettes]], who had ceased operations in 1987. Like the Browns, the Alouettes (who incidentally were originally founded in 1946, the same year as the Browns) were formally recognized as having resumed operations after a hiatus although unlike the Browns, the decision to reactivate the Montreal franchise in such a manner that it was considered a continuation of the previous franchise had not been previously planned and was made retroactively at the time of their revival. Much of the Stallions' roster and most of the Stallions' other football personnel made the move to Montreal, although unlike Modell, Speros was not formally given the sort of successor rights to existing contracts that would have allowed him to transplant his football organization to Montreal in the same manner was done from Cleveland to Baltimore - this would have been problematic due to the CFL's requirement that the re-activated Alouettes adhere to roster limits on American players (then called \"imports\") that the defunct U.S. CFL teams had not been bound to. The ability of Speros to retain the core of his championship roster to the point that the transaction superficially appeared to be a \"move\" was the result of a [[gentlemen's agreement]] between Speros and the other CFL teams. CFL commissioner [[Larry Smith (Canadian politician)|Larry Smith]], an Alouettes alumnus who was keen to ensure the revived Montreal franchise was an immediate contender, had pressured the other CFL teams to agree not to aggressively pursue what were technically [[free agent]]s.\n\nFocus groups, a telephone survey, and a fan contest were all held to help select a new name for Modell's team. Starting with a list of over 100 possible names, the team's management reduced it to 17. From there, focus groups of a total of 200 Baltimore area residents reduced the list of names to six, and then a phone survey of 1000 people trimmed it down to three, Marauders, Americans, and Ravens. Finally, a fan contest drawing 33,288 voters picked \"[[Baltimore Ravens|Ravens]]\", a name that alludes to the famous poem, \"[[The Raven]]\", by [[Edgar Allan Poe]], who spent the latter part of his life in Baltimore, and is also buried there.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baltimore Ravens History|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/teams/baltimore-ravens/team-history/|publisher=[[Pro Football Hall of Fame]]|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> The team also adopted purple and black as their team colors, a stark contrast to the brown and orange colors of the Browns.<ref>{{cite web|title=Naming Baltimore's Team: Ravens|url=http://www.baltimoreravens.com/team/history/naming-baltimores-team.html|publisher=Baltimore Ravens|accessdate=June 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160708123713/http://www.baltimoreravens.com/team/history/naming-baltimores-team.html|archive-date=July 8, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The former Colts Marching Band, which remained in Baltimore after the Colts moved to Indianapolis, was subsequently renamed the [[Baltimore's Marching Ravens]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Band History|url=http://www.baltimoreravens.com/ravenstown/marching-ravens/history.html|publisher=Baltimore Ravens|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> Along with the [[San Francisco 49ers]], [[Buffalo Bills]], and [[Washington Redskins]], the Ravens are one of only four NFL teams with an official [[marching band]].\n\nModell's move to Baltimore came amid an unprecedented flurry of similar threats \u2014 and actual moves \u2014<ref name=\"SIKing1\">{{cite news|last=King|first=Peter|title=Down...And Out: Citing his crushing debts, Art Modell is taking his Browns to Baltimore|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1995/11/13/208163/downand-out-citing-his-crushing-debts-art-modell-is-taking-his-browns-to-baltimore|magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=November 13, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"SICrothers1\">{{cite news|last=Crothers|first=Tim|title=The Shakedown: Greedy owners are threatening to move their teams if demands for new stadiums, better lease deals, etc., aren't met|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1995/06/19/204044/the-shakedown-greedy-owners-are-threatening-to-move-their-teams-if-demands-for-new-stadiums-better-lease-deals-etc-arent-met|magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=June 19, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> that fueled 12 new stadiums throughout the NFL. The Seahawks, Buccaneers, Bengals, Lions, Cardinals, and Bears used the threat of moving to coerce their respective cities to build new stadiums with public funds.<ref name=\"SIKing1\" /><ref name=\"SICrothers1\"/> Modell's team was one of four that actually moved between [[1995 NFL season|1995]] and [[1997 NFL season|1997]]: Los Angeles lost [[History of the National Football League in Los Angeles|both of its teams]] for the 1995 season, as the [[Oakland Raiders|Raiders]] moved back to Oakland and the [[Los Angeles Rams|Rams]] moved east to St. Louis (the Rams would later move back to Los Angeles in 2016); and the [[History of the Houston Oilers|Houston Oilers]] move to [[Tennessee]] in 1997, where they become the [[Tennessee Titans]] two years later.\n\nAfter several NFL teams threatened to move to Cleveland to become the reactivated Browns (most notably the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Williams|first=Charean|title=Tampa Still Hopeful Bucs Will Stay Put|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1995-12-07/sports/9512061680_1_tampa-bay-buccaneers-joel-glazer-cleveland/2|newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|date=December 7, 1995|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref>), the NFL decided in 1998 to make the reactivated Browns an [[expansion team]], which while it temporarily gave the league an odd number of teams (causing at least one team to be off in each of the 17 weeks of the NFL season from 1999\u20132001), it also eliminated any possibility of an existing franchise giving up its own identity for the Browns and thus prevented more [[lawsuit]]s. In an ironic twist, [[Al Lerner]]\u2014who helped Modell move to Baltimore\u2014was granted ownership of the reactivated Browns;<ref name=\"lerner\">{{cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|title=PRO FOOTBALL; Lerner Wins Browns for $530 Million|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/09/sports/pro-football-lerner-wins-browns-for-530-million.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 9, 1998|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> his son [[Randy Lerner|Randy]] took over ownership after Al's death in 2002 before selling the team to [[Pilot Flying J]] CEO [[Jimmy Haslam]] in 2012. From its beginning, the odd number of teams and the ensuing awkward scheduling was considered a temporary arrangement pending the addition of a 32nd NFL franchise \u2013 although Los Angeles was heavily favored, it was ultimately the [[Houston Texans]] who were created as the 32nd team to replace the [[Tennessee Titans|Oilers]] in [[Houston|Houston, Texas]] for the [[2002 NFL season]] to give the league once again an even number of teams. Following this decision, Los Angeles became the favored destination for owners threatening to move their teams until the [[History of the St. Louis Rams|St. Louis Rams]] finally returned to Los Angeles for the [[2016 NFL season|2016 season]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Rams to Return to Los Angeles|url=http://www.therams.com/news-and-events/article-1/Rams-to-Return-to-Los-Angeles/802b4e16-671e-4864-97b6-943115cdc4cf|publisher=St. Louis Rams|date=January 12, 2016|accessdate=January 13, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120221040/http://www.therams.com/news-and-events/article-1/Rams-to-Return-to-Los-Angeles/802b4e16-671e-4864-97b6-943115cdc4cf|archive-date=January 20, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> followed by the [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]] (who had previously called L.A. home in the early days of the [[American Football League]]) one year later.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chargers to Relocate to Los Angeles|url=https://www.chargers.com/news/2017/01/12/chargers-relocate-los-angeles|publisher=San Diego Chargers|date=January 12, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112171416/https://www.chargers.com/news/2017/01/12/chargers-relocate-los-angeles|archivedate=January 12, 2017|accessdate=June 10, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe reactivated Browns have had only two winning seasons since returning to the NFL in 1999: a 9\u20137 finish in [[2002 Cleveland Browns season|2002]] which also saw the team clinch a [[wild card (sports)|wild card]] spot in the playoffs, and a 10\u20136 finish in [[2007 Cleveland Browns season|2007]] while barely missing the playoffs. Meanwhile, the Ravens have been more successful, reaching the playoffs eight times since [[2000 NFL season|2000]] and winning [[Super Bowl XXXV]] and [[Super Bowl XLVII]], often to the dismay of Browns fans.<ref name=henkel103/><ref name=dismay>{{cite web|author=NFL Network|title=Top 10 snakebit franchises|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d8186c861/article/top-10-snakebit-franchises|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|date=May 31, 2010|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref> Longtime [[placekicker]] [[Matt Stover]] was the last remaining Ravens player that played for the Modell-owned Browns \u2013 he departed the Ravens following the [[2008 NFL season|2008 season]] when the team chose not to re-sign him, finishing his career with the Indianapolis Colts.<ref name=stover>{{cite news|last=Grossi|first=Tony|title=Indianapolis Colts kicker Matt Stover has many ties to Cleveland Browns|url=http://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2010/02/the_colts_matt_stover_has_many.html|newspaper=[[The Plain Dealer]]|date=February 5, 2010|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> General manager and former Browns [[tight end]] [[Ozzie Newsome]] (who was in a front-office role under Modell in Cleveland) remained with the Ravens until his retirement in 2018.\n\nThe move would also have an effect in [[Pittsburgh]]. Steelers owner [[Dan Rooney]] was one of two owners to oppose Modell's move to Baltimore because of a mutual respect for the team and the fans. Because of the move, the [[Browns\u2013Steelers rivalry]], arguably one of the most heated rivalries in the NFL, has somewhat cooled in Pittsburgh due to the new Browns' lack of success. The [[Steelers\u2013Ravens rivalry]] is considered the [[spiritual successor]] by fans in Pittsburgh and is one of the most heated current rivalries in the NFL.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 New NFL Rivalries|url=http://images.si.com/multimedia/photo_gallery/2005/12/15/gallery.newrivals/content.9.html|magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=December 15, 2005|accessdate=June 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219071621/http://images.si.com/multimedia/photo_gallery/2005/12/15/gallery.newrivals/content.9.html|archive-date=February 19, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Since returning to the NFL, the Browns and Steelers rivalry has been largely one-sided in favor of Pittsburgh; although the rivalry is not as intense in Pittsburgh, Browns fans still consider it their top rivalry despite the Browns' recent struggles against the Steelers.\n\nBecause of continual financial hardships, the NFL directed Modell to initiate the sale of his franchise. On March 27, 2000, NFL owners approved the sale of 49 percent of the Ravens to [[Steve Bisciotti]].<ref name=bisciotti1>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=NewsLibrary&p_multi=APAB&d_place=APAB&p_theme=newslibrary2&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F89B8E00CF79536&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Bisciotti approved as co-owner of Ravens|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=2011-03-12|date=2000-03-27}}</ref> In the deal, Bisciotti had an option to purchase the remaining 51 percent for $325 million in 2004 from Art Modell. On April 8, 2004, the NFL approved Steve Bisciotti's purchase of the majority stake in the club.<ref name=bisciotti2>{{cite news|title=Bisciotti takes control of Ravens|url=http://www.nfl.com/teams/story/BAL/7242066|agency=Associated Press|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|date=April 8, 2004|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616162759/http://www.nfl.com/teams/story/BAL/7242066|archivedate=June 16, 2004|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Modell later retired and had relinquished control of the Ravens, he is still despised in Cleveland, not only for moving the Browns, but also for his firing of legendary head coach [[Paul Brown]] in 1963. Some considered the Browns' move and subsequent lawsuits costing Modell a spot in the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]], which is in [[Canton, Ohio]], 60 miles south of Cleveland and is both part of the Cleveland television market and part of the Browns' territorial rights.<ref name=LivingstonModell>{{cite news|last=Livingston|first=Bill|title=Upon further review, Art Modell's case for Canton gets weaker every year|url=http://www.cleveland.com/livingston/index.ssf/2010/12/upon_further_review_art_modell.html|newspaper=[[The Plain Dealer]]|date=December 12, 2010|accessdate=June 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Clayton|first=John|title=Modell was mostly a model owner|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/8344634/nfl-modell-was-model-owner-many-ways|publisher=ESPN|date=September 6, 2012|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> Modell died in 2012, having never returned to Cleveland.<ref name=\"McFaddenNYTimes\" /> The Browns were the only home team that did not acknowledge, much less commemorate, Modell's death the following Sunday. The team opted not to do so at the request of David Modell, who feared that the announcement would be met with anger by Browns fans still upset about the move.<ref>https://www.cleveland.com/browns/index.ssf/2012/09/cleveland_browns_cancel_their.html</ref>\n\n==Effect on teams in other sports leagues==\n\n===Major League Baseball===\n*The [[Minnesota Twins]], when they signed their deal with [[Hennepin County, Minnesota]] for [[Target Field]] in 2006, agreed to a provision that was signed into law that allows the state of Minnesota the right of first refusal to buy the team if it is ever sold. Also, it requires that the name, colors, [[World Series]] trophies, and history of the team remain in Minnesota if the Twins are ever moved out of state. The deal is similar to what Modell agreed to with the city of Cleveland during the move.\n\n===Major League Soccer===\n*In December 2005, the [[San Jose Earthquakes]] moved to [[Houston]] to become the [[Houston Dynamo]]. At the time, it was announced by the league that while players and staff would move with the team, the team name, colors, logo, and records (including two championship trophies) would stay in San Jose for when a new expansion team arrives.<ref>{{cite news|last=Halpin|first=Jason|title=Earthquakes set to move to Houston|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2010/01/22/earthquakes-set-move-houston|publisher=MLS Digital|date=December 15, 2005|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=San Jose's MLS team moving to Houston|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/mls/quakes/2005-12-15-relocation-houston_x.htm|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=December 15, 2005|accessdate=2009-03-02}}</ref> In 2008, the Earthquakes returned under the ownership of [[Lew Wolff]].\n*The Browns move in 1996 had a direct effect on a proposed move of [[Columbus Crew SC]] to [[Austin, Texas]]; the Modell Law, which was implemented in 1996, prohibits sports teams that benefited from public facilities or financial assistance from moving to another city without a six-month notice and an attempt to sell the team to a local ownership group. A lawsuit was filed by Ohio Attorney General [[Mike DeWine]] and the [[Columbus, Ohio|city of Columbus]]. Rather ironically, Cleveland Browns owner [[Jimmy Haslam|Jimmy]] and [[Dee Haslam]], along with other investors, offered to buy the Columbus Crew in order to keep them in Columbus.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Statement from Dee and Jimmy Haslam on interest in Columbus Crew|url=https://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/statement-from-dee-and-jimmy-haslam-on-interest-in-columbus-crew|publisher=NFL Enterprises, LLC|website=ClevelandBrowns.com|date=October 12, 2018|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> The proposed sale would sell the operational rights of the Crew to the new buyers, while previous Crew owner [[Anthony Precourt]] would keep his equity stake in MLS, and would have ownership of a [[Austin FC|new franchise in Austin]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wahl |first1=Grant |title=Columbus Crew Set to Avoid Austin Move After New Local Buyers Emerge |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2018/10/12/columbus-crew-saved-austin-move-precourt-haslam-mls |accessdate=3 December 2018 |publisher=Sports Illustrated |date=12 October 2018}}</ref> The sale of the Crew to Haslam's ownership group was announced as agreed to on December 28, 2018, and was completed in January 2019. As part of the deal, the lawsuit was dismissed that day; the Modell Law remains untested as a result.<ref>{{cite news|last=Carlisle|first=Jeff|title=MLS: Haslam family has 'agreement in principle' to take over Columbus Crew SC|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/major-league-soccer/story/3738154/mls-haslam-family-has-agreement-in-principle-to-take-over-columbus-crew-sc|agency=ESPN|date=December 28, 2018|accessdate=2018-12-28}}</ref>\n\n===National Hockey League===\n*After the [[Quebec Nordiques]] moved to [[Denver]] in 1995 to become the [[Colorado Avalanche]], the franchise's retired numbers, name, logos, and historical stats remained in Quebec City and are expected to be used by any [[Potential National Hockey League expansion#Quebec City|future Quebec City NHL franchise]] that may be established or move there. Upon arrival at Denver, the Nordiques' retired numbers were placed back into circulation.\n*In 2011, a team took the name of a city's previous team (as the Baltimore Stallions did when the Ravens forced their move to Montreal). That saga began in 1996, when the [[Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)|Winnipeg Jets]] left [[Manitoba]] for [[Phoenix, Arizona]], and become the [[Phoenix Coyotes]]. Thirteen years later, the [[Phoenix Coyotes bankruptcy and sale|Coyotes went bankrupt]] and were taken over by the league. Winnipeg-based [[True North Sports & Entertainment]] offered to buy the team and return it to Winnipeg, where it presumably would have re-assumed the Jets' name and history. The NHL turned down that proposal \u2014 they were still looking for an owner to operate the franchise in Phoenix, whose municipal government had agreed to subsidize the team's financial losses \u2014 but said that moving the team back to Winnipeg was their preferred backup option. But when the [[Atlanta Thrashers]] came up for sale a year later, the league decided that there was no chance of finding an owner to operate a franchise in Georgia, so they arranged for True North to purchase the Atlanta franchise and move it to Winnipeg for the {{NHL Year|2011}} NHL season. The league decided to let True North and the [[Winnipeg Jets|new Jets]] use the identity of the old Winnipeg team, but not its history, which remained in Arizona with the Coyotes. The new Jets organization highlighted this change by quickly re-issuing the team's #9 jersey \u2014 retired by the old Jets in honor of superstar [[Bobby Hull]] \u2014 to forward [[Evander Kane]], who had worn the number in Atlanta.\n\n===National Basketball Association===\n*The [[Seattle SuperSonics relocation to Oklahoma City|Seattle SuperSonics' move to Oklahoma City]] in 2008 included an agreement that the [[Seattle SuperSonics|SuperSonics]]' name, logo, colors, and history would all be left in [[Seattle]]. This also includes banners and trophies, which would be displayed in [[Museum of History & Industry (MOHAI)|a museum]] until a new franchise is brought to Seattle to be hung from the rafters of its arena.<ref>{{cite press release|title=THE PROFESSIONAL BASKETBALL CLUB, LLC AND CITY OF SEATTLE SETTLEMENT AGREEMENT|url=http://www.seattle.gov/Documents/Departments/CityAttorney/Reports/2008SonicsSettlementAgreement.pdf#page=3|publisher=City of Seattle, Washington|date=July 2, 2008|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> The original franchise, now the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]], continue to keep the SuperSonics tie-ins, including records, championships, and retired numbers, until a new SuperSonics franchise is brought to Seattle. Both the Thunder and a potential new SuperSonics franchise would \"share\" the original SuperSonics history.\n*Similar to the Winnipeg Jets scenario in the NHL, the NBA first entered [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]] in {{nbay|1988|start}} in the form of the [[Charlotte Hornets]]. That team remained in Charlotte until moving to [[New Orleans]] after the {{nbay|2001|app=season}}, retaining the Hornets name. The league returned to Charlotte for the {{nbay|2004|app=season}} with a new team, the Charlotte Bobcats. After the New Orleans franchise changed its name to the [[New Orleans Pelicans|Pelicans]] after the {{nbay|2012|app=season}}, the Bobcats announced that they would reclaim the \"Hornets\" name effective with the {{nbay|2014|app=season}}. When the name change from Bobcats to Hornets became official in May 2014, it was also announced that the Hornets, Pelicans, and the NBA had reached an agreement that all history and records of the original Charlotte Hornets would be transferred to the revived Hornets. As a result, the Hornets are now considered to have been established in 1988, suspended operations in 2002, and resumed in 2004 (as the Bobcats, then again changing their name back to the Hornets in 2014), while the Pelicans are now considered a 2002 expansion team.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Charlotte Hornets Name Returns to Carolinas|url=http://www.nba.com/hornets/charlotte-hornets-name-returns-carolinas|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=Hornets.com|date=May 20, 2014|accessdate=May 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Relocation of professional sports teams]]\n* [[Cleveland sports curse]]\n* [[Browns\u2013Ravens rivalry]]\n* [[History of the Cleveland Browns]]\n* [[History of the Baltimore Ravens]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|title=Cleveland Browns History|author=Henkel, Frank M.|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7385-3428-2|ref=CITEREFHenkel2005}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.latimes.com/sports/bal-modell121795,0,1763650,full.story Inside the Browns deal.] A ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' article on the Cleveland Browns' move.\n* {{YouTube|6J7Sc2Uaa0E|Cleveland Browns relocation}} on [[The NFL on NBC pregame show]].\n{{Cleveland Browns}}\n{{Baltimore Ravens}}\n{{NFL on NBC}}\n\n[[Category:National Football League controversies]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Ravens]]\n[[Category:National Football League franchise relocations]]\n", "name_user": "Rupertslander", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSettlement", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cleveland_Browns_relocation_controversy"}
{"title_page": "Rajesh Hamal", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|Nepalese film actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rajesh Hamal\n| image              = [[File:Rajesh Hamal in Sydney 2014.jpg|220px]]\n| caption            = Rajesh Hamal in Sydney, 2014\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date        = July 13, 1971 [[Tansen, Nepal|Tansen]], [[Palpa District]], [[Nepal]]\n| nationality        = Nepalese\n| relatives          = [[Deepak Rayamajhi]] (maternal uncle)\n| residence          = [[Kathmandu]], Nepal\n| education          = [[Bhanubhakta Memorial Higher Secondary School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Delhi]]\n| occupation         = [[Actor]]\n| spouse             = Madhu Bhattarai (m. 2014)\n| yearsactive        = \n| awards             = \n| other names        = \n}}\n'''Rajesh Hamal''' ( {{Audio|Rajesh Hamal Audio.ogg|Listen}}, born in [[Tansen, Nepal|Tansen]], [[Palpa District|Palpa]], [[Nepal]]) is a Nepalese film [[actor]], [[Singing|singer]], [[Model (person)|model]], and [[Television presenter|television host]]. Born in July 13, 1971 [[Tansen, Nepal|Tansen]], [[Palpa District|Palpa]], Nepal, Hamal was one of the highest paid Nepalese actors throughout the 1990s and 2000s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/nepali-films-battle-stiff-odds/cid/697770|title=Nepali films battle stiff odds|website=The Telegraph|location=Kolkota|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514183951/https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/nepali-films-battle-stiff-odds/cid/697770|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=a_fFvk7mS5IC&pg=PA33&dq=Rajesh+Hamal#v=onepage&q=Rajesh%20Hamal&f=false|title=The Rotarian|last=International|first=Rotary|date=August 2010|publisher=Rotary International}}</ref>\n\nHamal debuted as an actor in his [[Deepak Rayamajhi|uncle's]] film ''[[Yug Dekhi Yug Samma]]'' in 1991. Since then, he has appeared in over 200 films in a career spanning nearly three decades.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reelnepal.com/name/532/rajesh-hamal/filmography|title=Rajesh Hamal \u2013 Filmography, Full Movies, Recent Movies, Upcoming Movies List|website=reelnepal|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616133629/https://reelnepal.com/name/532/rajesh-hamal/filmography|archive-date=16 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He is widely regarded as one of the most influential personalities in Nepalese cinema.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tgg.org.np/mentor/rajesh-hamal/|title=Rajesh Hamal {{!}} The Generation Green|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514191743/http://tgg.org.np/mentor/rajesh-hamal/|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hamal starred in ''Yug Dekhi Yug Samma'' (1991), [[Kasam (1992 film)|''Kasam'']] (1992), ''[[Deuta]]'' (1993), ''[[Ek Number Ko Pakhe]]'' (1999), ''[[Hami Tin Bhai]]'' (2004), ''[[Ajambari Naataa]]'' (2005) and ''[[Mukhauta]]'' (2014). He also hosted the first season of Nepalese version of ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' titled ''[[Ko Bancha Crorepati]]'' (2019).\n\n== Personal life ==\nHamal was born in [[Tansen, Nepal|Tansen]], [[Palpa District|Palpa]]. His father, Chuda Bahadur Hamal was the [[Nepal\u2013Pakistan relations|Nepalese ambassador to Pakistan]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2012-12-06/envoy-to-egypt-dies-of-heart-attack.html|title=Envoy to Egypt dies of heart attack|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514183348/http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2012-12-06/envoy-to-egypt-dies-of-heart-attack.html|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hamal did not communicate much with his father, telling ''Wavemag'', \"Every day of my life, I regret not bidding him with a proper goodbye. Additionally, I should have made an effort to properly communicate with my father, and talk about my aspirations and passion in a better way.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wavemag.com.np/my-3-mistakes-rajesh-hamal/|title=My 3 Mistakes \u2013 Rajesh Hamal {{!}} Wave Magazine|access-date=15 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515143730/https://wavemag.com.np/my-3-mistakes-rajesh-hamal/|archive-date=15 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Whilst his mother Renu K.C.'s profession is unknown,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rhamal.tripod.com/2001/renu/index.htm|title=July 2001|website=rhamal.tripod.com|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514181334/http://rhamal.tripod.com/2001/renu/index.htm|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hamal told Moviemandu, \"Death of my mother is due to the cause of mental health and cigarette, with these cause mother passed away for the lifetime\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moviemandu.com/rajeshhamal-3/|title=Rajesh Hamal Reveals How His Mother Died : EXCLUSIVE|access-date=15 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514180534/http://www.moviemandu.com/rajeshhamal-3/|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He is the third child, with four siblings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/valentine-day-special-love-story-of-rajesh-hamal-and-his-parents/|title=Valentine Day special \u2013 Love story of Rajesh Hamal and his parents|date=11 February 2017|website=Nepali Movies, films|access-date=24 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514180335/https://xnepali.net/valentine-day-special-love-story-of-rajesh-hamal-and-his-parents/|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHamal is currently married to Madhu Bhattarai.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.977mag.net/superstar-rajesh-hamal-his-model-wife-had-first-meet-in-lux-beauty-contest/|title=Superstar Rajesh Hamal & His Model Wife Had First Meet in Lux Beauty Contest|date=2 July 2017|website=Nepali Film News|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514183345/http://www.977mag.net/superstar-rajesh-hamal-his-model-wife-had-first-meet-in-lux-beauty-contest/|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> They first met at the Lux Beauty Pageant in 2004.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2014-05-24/actor-rajesh-hamal-gets-hitched.html|title=Actor Rajesh Hamal gets hitched|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711170611/https://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2014-05-24/actor-rajesh-hamal-gets-hitched.html|archive-date=11 July 2019|url-status=live|access-date=11 July 2019}}</ref> Hamal had proposed Bhattarai on 14 May, then he got married on 24 May 2014 in a private wedding ceremony on Hotel Annapurna, [[Kathmandu]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Hamal said he was impressed by Bhattarai's talent at the Lux Beauty Pageant in 2004, Bhattarai was nervous to see her favourite actor as a judge that she couldn't answer his questions properly.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/art-entertainment/2014/05/13/wedding-bells|title=Wedding bells|website=kathmandupost.com|access-date=5 August 2019}}</ref> Hamal and Bhattarai managed to keep their relationship secret for five years, the couple admitted they were on a relationship two years before getting married.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Career ==\n=== Acting career ===\n{{See also|Rajesh Hamal filmography}}\nBefore entering the film industry Hamal modeled for a magazine in India named Fashion Net whilst studying at [[University of Delhi]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://tnm.com.np/rajesh-hamal-like-never-before/|title=RAJESH HAMAL: LIKE NEVER BEFORE.|website=TNM|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514205234/http://tnm.com.np/rajesh-hamal-like-never-before/|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He appeared in a fashion show organised by the Indian Embassy Women Association in the late 1980s.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nHamal's first starring role was set to be in ''Bhagya Rekha'' (1989) opposite of [[Karishma Manandhar]]. Later Manandhar left the project, which led Kristi Mainali to join the project. After Mainali joined the filming began however after the film director [[Deepak Rayamajhi]] was rumoured to suspected an affair between the lead actors, which led two of the lead actors leaving the project. Both were replaced by Rabindra Khadka, and Mausami Malla. After the film's release it became a blockbuster, the film also lad the film director Deepak Rayamajhi to become a credible film director in early Nepalese cinema industry.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/first-scandal-of-nepali-movie-industry-rajesh-hamal-and-kristi-kc-kicked-out-of-bhagya-rekha/|title=First Scandal of Nepali movie industry \u2013 Rajesh Hamal and Kristi KC kicked out of Bhagya Rekha \u2013 Nepali Movies, films|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520170439/https://xnepali.net/first-scandal-of-nepali-movie-industry-rajesh-hamal-and-kristi-kc-kicked-out-of-bhagya-rekha/|archive-date=20 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe affair of Kristi Mainali, and Hamal became highly popular throughout Nepal, and after [[Deepak Rayamajhi]] successful film director debut he signed Mainali and Hamal into his next project titled ''[[Yug Dekhi Yug Samma]]'' (1991).<ref name=\":0\" /> The film follows two young couples who are amidst the pressure of their family rivalries. Along the side of lead actors debut, it was also the film producer Chhabiraj Ojha, and action director Rajendra Khadgi film debut too.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/nepali-movie-yug-dekhi-yug-samma/|title=Nepali Movie \u2013 Yug Dekhi Yug Samma \u2013 Nepali Movies, films|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520171237/https://xnepali.net/nepali-movie-yug-dekhi-yug-samma/|archive-date=20 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hamal later told ''Teenz, \"''Actually somewhere inside I always wanted to act. More than acting, I was fascinated by films. I wanted to something in the field, but I did not know how to begin. Luckily, my cousin was a part of the film industry and he offered me a role. That was in 1990, and at that time. I did not know I would be doing films for the next 20 years\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://teenz.com.np/article/my-teenage-days/rajesh-hamal.html|title=Rajesh Hamal \u2013 My teenage days \u2013 Teenz|website=teenz.com.np|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514193657/http://teenz.com.np/article/my-teenage-days/rajesh-hamal.html|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After the success of the film it was later remade with the same title in 2009, directed by [[Dipendra K Khanal]], and the film starred [[Nandita K.C.]], and Hamal in the lead roles.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Yug Dekhi Yug Samma|url=https://www.lensnepal.com/movie/the-yug-dekhi-yug-samma/casts.html|access-date=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n<nowiki> </nowiki>In 1993 Hamal joined up with [[Tulsi Ghimire]] for the first time, in his directorial film project called ''[[Deuta]].'' The film starred Hamal in the lead role beside the film also starred [[Shrawan Ghimire]], Srijana Basnet, and Tulsi Ghimire in the supporting roles.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/nepali-movie-deuta/|title=Nepali Movie \u2013 Deuta|date=3 October 2009|website=Nepali Movies, films|access-date=4 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904010055/https://xnepali.net/nepali-movie-deuta/|archive-date=4 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Upon film's release it became super hit at the box office of Nepal.<ref name=\":4\" /> The film is also considered the film that launched his stardom in the [[Cinema of Nepal|Nepalese film industry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2011-12-30/silver-screen-milestones.html|title=Silver screen milestones|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|access-date=4 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504115541/http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2011-12-30/silver-screen-milestones.html|archive-date=4 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'' wrote, \"Incidentally, this was also the film that catapulted Hamal into stardom and while that alone could place Deuta in a Kollywood Hall of Fame (if such a thing existed), the movie is much more than that\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2011-12-30/silver-screen-milestones.html|title=Silver screen milestones|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|access-date=15 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515134600/http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2011-12-30/silver-screen-milestones.html|archive-date=15 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000 Hamal was cast in actor [[Neer Shah]] directorial film titled [[Basanti (2000 film)|''Basanti'']] (2000). In the film Hamal portrayed the role of [[Gagan Singh Bhandari|Gagan Singh Khawas]], alongside Hamal appeared with [[Karishma Manandhar]], [[Gauri Malla]], and [[Divya Dutta]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Basanti|url=https://www.lensnepal.com/movie/basanti.html|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021001607/http://www.lensnepal.com/movie/basanti.html|archive-date=21 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The film is based on the novel of the same written by [[Diamond Shumsher Rana]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmsofnepal.com/nepali-film-seto-bagh-2015/|title=Nepali Film \u2013 Seto Bagh (2015)|date=3 April 2015|website=Films of Nepal|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815142021/https://filmsofnepal.com/nepali-film-seto-bagh-2015/|archive-date=15 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The film was also listed in \"Top 10 Nepali movies you shouldn't miss\" on the number six made by ''Xnepali.net.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/top-10-nepali-movies-you-shouldnt-miss/|title=Top 10 Nepali movies you shouldn't miss (Full movies) \u2013 Nepali Movies, films|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130062430/https://xnepali.net/top-10-nepali-movies-you-shouldnt-miss/|archive-date=30 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Hamal considers his favourite film to be ''[[Deuta]]'' (1991), and ''Basanti'' (2000).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/rajesh-hamal/|title=Rajesh Hamal Biography \u2013 Nepali Movies, films|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515093018/https://xnepali.net/rajesh-hamal/|archive-date=15 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Bijaya Adhikari of ''OnlineKhabar'' wrote, \"However, filmmakers like Nir Shah, one of the forerunners of the historical period drama genre, has been consistently making successful films in the genre like Basanti, Masaan and Seto Bagh.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.onlinekhabar.com/successful-nepali-filmmakers-historical-genre.html|title=How successful have Nepali filmmakers been with the historical genre? \u2013 OnlineKhabar|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520182011/http://english.onlinekhabar.com/successful-nepali-filmmakers-historical-genre.html|archive-date=20 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Rachana Chettri, and Preena Shrestha of ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'' also wrote, \"Cinematographically, the film achieves its purpose of bringing the old palaces and courtyards populated by royals and their supporters back to life.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2011-12-30/silver-screen-milestones.html|title=Silver screen milestones|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515134600/http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2011-12-30/silver-screen-milestones.html|archive-date=15 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThen in 2004 Hamal appeared in a Shiva Regmi directorial film named ''[[Hami Tin Bhai]]'' (2004). The film starred an [[ensemble cast]] of [[Shree Krishna Shrestha]], [[Nikhil Upreti]], [[Jharana Thapa]], [[Nandita K.C.]], and [[Rekha Thapa]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Fy9uAAAAMAAJ&q=Hami+Teen+Bhai&dq=Hami+Teen+Bhai|title=Nepal Yearbook|date=2006|publisher=Institute for Integrated Development Studies|language=en}}</ref> In 2018 it was announced the sequel of the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nepalifeed.com/%e0%a4%9a%e0%a4%b0%e0%a5%8d%e0%a4%9a%e0%a4%bf%e0%a4%a4-%e0%a4%ab%e0%a4%bf%e0%a4%b2%e0%a5%8d%e0%a4%ae-%e0%a4%b9%e0%a4%be%e0%a4%ae%e0%a5%80-%e0%a5%a9-%e0%a4%ad%e0%a4%be%e0%a4%88-%e0%a4%95%e0%a5%8b/|title=\u091a\u0930\u094d\u091a\u093f\u0924 \u092b\u093f\u0932\u094d\u092e \"\u0939\u093e\u092e\u0940 \u0969 \u092d\u093e\u0908\" \u0915\u094b \u0938\u093f\u0915\u094d\u0935\u0947\u0932\u092e\u093e \u0969 \u092d\u093e\u0907 \u092c\u0928\u094d\u0926\u0948 \u0905\u0928\u092e\u094b\u0932, \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0926\u0940\u092a \u0930 \u092a\u0932 !|date=22 November 2018|website=Nepali Feed|access-date=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Television hosting ===\nHamal has twice been judge for [[Miss Nepal]], once in 1997 with Kamal Rupakheti, Laxmi Keshari Manandhar, and Sanjaya Agarwal, the event was won by [[Jharana Bajracharya]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tghFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA63&dq=Rajesh+Hamal#v=onepage&q=Rajesh%20Hamal&f=false|title=Miss Nepal Unofficial: Everything about Miss Nepal|last=Nepal|first=Anand|date=1 January 2018|publisher=ebookbhandar.com|isbn=9781546778721}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missnepal.com.np/archive/1997|title=Miss Nepal - The Hidden Treasure|website=missnepal.com.np|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514201808/https://www.missnepal.com.np/archive/1997|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After 10 years later he was the chief judge of [[Miss Nepal 2007]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missnepal.com.np/archive/2007|title=Miss Nepal \u2013 The Hidden Treasure|website=missnepal.com.np|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514205323/https://www.missnepal.com.np/archive/2007|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> he judged alongside [[Malvika Subba]], and [[Bhusan Dahal]], the event was won by [[Sitashma Chand]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/entertainment/sitashma-is-miss-nepal-2007/|title=Sitashma is Miss Nepal 2007|date=7 April 2007|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514210616/https://thehimalayantimes.com/entertainment/sitashma-is-miss-nepal-2007/|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, he was hosting the [[Ko Banchha Crorepati|Nepalese version]] of ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/multimedia/video-gallery/world/ko-banchha-crorepati-premiers-in-nepal-78696.htm|title=\"Ko Banchha Crorepati\" premiers in Nepal|work=Business Standard India|access-date=4 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504120756/https://www.business-standard.com/multimedia/video-gallery/world/ko-banchha-crorepati-premiers-in-nepal-78696.htm|archive-date=4 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== In the media ==\nHamal is often referred to as \"Mahanayak\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/40289/|title=Mahanayak Rajesh Hamal gets five \u2013 year \u2013 old admitted to school|website=My Republica|access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref> and \"Rajesh Dai\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.onlinekhabar.com/looking-for-quick-success-and-fame-listen-to-what-rajesh-hamal-has-to-say.html|title=Looking for quick fame? Listen to what Rajesh Hamal has to say \u2013 OnlineKhabar|access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref> [[Karishma Manandhar]], Nepalese actress said, if Hamal ran for Mayor of Kathmandu she would vote for him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/art-entertainment/2017/04/18/would-you-vote-for-rajesh-hamal-karishmaa-would|title=Would you vote for Rajesh Hamal? Karishmaa would|website=kathmandupost.com|access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 Hamal was compared to Indian actors [[Amitabh Bachchan]], and [[Shah Rukh Khan]] by Indian media ''[[Aaj Tak]]''.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/70919/|title=Rajesh Hamal Shines in India, being compared to Amitabh and Shahrukh|last=Republica|website=My City|access-date=9 August 2019}}</ref> ''[[Aaj Tak]]'' wrote, \"Rajesh is such a superstar who has conferred with the title of megastar. Also Rajesh who is 55-years-old is still popular among Nepali film enthusiast which is similar to the fandom of Bollywood super stars \u2014Amitabh and Shahrukh\".<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aajtak.intoday.in/gallery/amitabh-bachchan-of-nepali-cinema-mahanayak-actor-rajesh-hamal-tmov-5-37039.html|title=\u092f\u0947 \u0939\u0948\u0902 \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0940 \u0938\u093f\u0928\u0947\u092e\u093e \u0915\u0947 '\u0905\u092e\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092d', 22 \u0938\u093e\u0932 \u091b\u094b\u091f\u0940 \u092e\u0949\u0921\u0932 \u0938\u0947 \u0915\u0940 \u0925\u0940 \u0936\u093e\u0926\u0940 \u2013 Entertainment Gallery AajTak|website=India Today|language=hi|access-date=9 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Film\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|1991\n|[[National Film Awards (Nepal)|National Film Awards]]\n|{{N/A}}\n|Yug Dekhi Yug Samma\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulf-times.com/story/522692|title=All set for 'Nepali-Bhojpuri Mega Star Night'|date=28 November 2016|website=Gulf Times|language=ar|access-date=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2003\n|Lux Film Awards\n|Best Actor\n|''[[Muktidata]]''\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/dec/01nepal.htm|title=Now, Nepal has its own film awards, too!|publisher=Rediff.com|access-date=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1101742}}\n{{Sister project links}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Nepal|Film|Biography|Arts  }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamal, Rajesh}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:People from Palpa District]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male actors]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male models]]\n[[Category:20th-century Nepalese male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Nepalese male actors]]\n[[Category:Thakuri]]\n[[Category:Nepalese film producers]]\n[[Category:Television presenters]]\n[[Category:Game show hosts]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male television actors]]\n[[Category:Male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male film actors]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male singers]]\n[[Category:Nepalese musicians]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male dancers]]\n[[Category:Nepalese businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|Nepalese film actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rajesh Hamal\n| image              = [[File:Rajesh Hamal in Sydney 2014.jpg|220px]]\n| caption            = Rajesh Hamal in Sydney, 2014\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_place        = [[Tansen, Nepal|Tansen]], [[Palpa District]], [[Nepal]]\n| nationality        = Nepalese\n| relatives          = [[Deepak Rayamajhi]] (maternal uncle)\n| residence          = [[Kathmandu]], Nepal\n| education          = [[Bhanubhakta Memorial Higher Secondary School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Delhi]]\n| occupation         = [[Actor]]\n| spouse             = Madhu Bhattarai (m. 2014)\n| yearsactive        = \n| awards             = \n| other names        = \n}}\n'''Rajesh Hamal''' ( {{Audio|Rajesh Hamal Audio.ogg|Listen}}, born in [[Tansen, Nepal|Tansen]], [[Palpa District|Palpa]], [[Nepal]]) is a Nepalese film [[actor]], [[Singing|singer]], [[Model (person)|model]], and [[Television presenter|television host]]. Born in [[Tansen, Nepal|Tansen]], [[Palpa District|Palpa]], Nepal, Hamal was one of the highest paid Nepalese actors throughout the 1990s and 2000s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/nepali-films-battle-stiff-odds/cid/697770|title=Nepali films battle stiff odds|website=The Telegraph|location=Kolkota|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514183951/https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/west-bengal/nepali-films-battle-stiff-odds/cid/697770|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=a_fFvk7mS5IC&pg=PA33&dq=Rajesh+Hamal#v=onepage&q=Rajesh%20Hamal&f=false|title=The Rotarian|last=International|first=Rotary|date=August 2010|publisher=Rotary International}}</ref>\n\nHamal debuted as an actor in his [[Deepak Rayamajhi|uncle's]] film ''[[Yug Dekhi Yug Samma]]'' in 1991. Since then, he has appeared in over 200 films in a career spanning nearly three decades.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://reelnepal.com/name/532/rajesh-hamal/filmography|title=Rajesh Hamal \u2013 Filmography, Full Movies, Recent Movies, Upcoming Movies List|website=reelnepal|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616133629/https://reelnepal.com/name/532/rajesh-hamal/filmography|archive-date=16 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He is widely regarded as one of the most influential personalities in Nepalese cinema.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tgg.org.np/mentor/rajesh-hamal/|title=Rajesh Hamal {{!}} The Generation Green|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514191743/http://tgg.org.np/mentor/rajesh-hamal/|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hamal starred in ''Yug Dekhi Yug Samma'' (1991), [[Kasam (1992 film)|''Kasam'']] (1992), ''[[Deuta]]'' (1993), ''[[Ek Number Ko Pakhe]]'' (1999), ''[[Hami Tin Bhai]]'' (2004), ''[[Ajambari Naataa]]'' (2005) and ''[[Mukhauta]]'' (2014). He also hosted the first season of Nepalese version of ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' titled ''[[Ko Bancha Crorepati]]'' (2019).\n\n== Personal life ==\nHamal was born in [[Tansen, Nepal|Tansen]], [[Palpa District|Palpa]]. His father, Chuda Bahadur Hamal was the [[Nepal\u2013Pakistan relations|Nepalese ambassador to Pakistan]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2012-12-06/envoy-to-egypt-dies-of-heart-attack.html|title=Envoy to Egypt dies of heart attack|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514183348/http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2012-12-06/envoy-to-egypt-dies-of-heart-attack.html|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hamal did not communicate much with his father, telling ''Wavemag'', \"Every day of my life, I regret not bidding him with a proper goodbye. Additionally, I should have made an effort to properly communicate with my father, and talk about my aspirations and passion in a better way.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wavemag.com.np/my-3-mistakes-rajesh-hamal/|title=My 3 Mistakes \u2013 Rajesh Hamal {{!}} Wave Magazine|access-date=15 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515143730/https://wavemag.com.np/my-3-mistakes-rajesh-hamal/|archive-date=15 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Whilst his mother Renu K.C.'s profession is unknown,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rhamal.tripod.com/2001/renu/index.htm|title=July 2001|website=rhamal.tripod.com|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514181334/http://rhamal.tripod.com/2001/renu/index.htm|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hamal told Moviemandu, \"Death of my mother is due to the cause of mental health and cigarette, with these cause mother passed away for the lifetime\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moviemandu.com/rajeshhamal-3/|title=Rajesh Hamal Reveals How His Mother Died : EXCLUSIVE|access-date=15 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514180534/http://www.moviemandu.com/rajeshhamal-3/|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He is the third child, with four siblings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/valentine-day-special-love-story-of-rajesh-hamal-and-his-parents/|title=Valentine Day special \u2013 Love story of Rajesh Hamal and his parents|date=11 February 2017|website=Nepali Movies, films|access-date=24 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514180335/https://xnepali.net/valentine-day-special-love-story-of-rajesh-hamal-and-his-parents/|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHamal is currently married to Madhu Bhattarai.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.977mag.net/superstar-rajesh-hamal-his-model-wife-had-first-meet-in-lux-beauty-contest/|title=Superstar Rajesh Hamal & His Model Wife Had First Meet in Lux Beauty Contest|date=2 July 2017|website=Nepali Film News|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514183345/http://www.977mag.net/superstar-rajesh-hamal-his-model-wife-had-first-meet-in-lux-beauty-contest/|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> They first met at the Lux Beauty Pageant in 2004.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2014-05-24/actor-rajesh-hamal-gets-hitched.html|title=Actor Rajesh Hamal gets hitched|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711170611/https://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2014-05-24/actor-rajesh-hamal-gets-hitched.html|archive-date=11 July 2019|url-status=live|access-date=11 July 2019}}</ref> Hamal had proposed Bhattarai on 14 May, then he got married on 24 May 2014 in a private wedding ceremony on Hotel Annapurna, [[Kathmandu]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Hamal said he was impressed by Bhattarai's talent at the Lux Beauty Pageant in 2004, Bhattarai was nervous to see her favourite actor as a judge that she couldn't answer his questions properly.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/art-entertainment/2014/05/13/wedding-bells|title=Wedding bells|website=kathmandupost.com|access-date=5 August 2019}}</ref> Hamal and Bhattarai managed to keep their relationship secret for five years, the couple admitted they were on a relationship two years before getting married.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Career ==\n=== Acting career ===\n{{See also|Rajesh Hamal filmography}}\nBefore entering the film industry Hamal modeled for a magazine in India named Fashion Net whilst studying at [[University of Delhi]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://tnm.com.np/rajesh-hamal-like-never-before/|title=RAJESH HAMAL: LIKE NEVER BEFORE.|website=TNM|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514205234/http://tnm.com.np/rajesh-hamal-like-never-before/|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He appeared in a fashion show organised by the Indian Embassy Women Association in the late 1980s.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nHamal's first starring role was set to be in ''Bhagya Rekha'' (1989) opposite of [[Karishma Manandhar]]. Later Manandhar left the project, which led Kristi Mainali to join the project. After Mainali joined the filming began however after the film director [[Deepak Rayamajhi]] was rumoured to suspected an affair between the lead actors, which led two of the lead actors leaving the project. Both were replaced by Rabindra Khadka, and Mausami Malla. After the film's release it became a blockbuster, the film also lad the film director Deepak Rayamajhi to become a credible film director in early Nepalese cinema industry.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/first-scandal-of-nepali-movie-industry-rajesh-hamal-and-kristi-kc-kicked-out-of-bhagya-rekha/|title=First Scandal of Nepali movie industry \u2013 Rajesh Hamal and Kristi KC kicked out of Bhagya Rekha \u2013 Nepali Movies, films|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520170439/https://xnepali.net/first-scandal-of-nepali-movie-industry-rajesh-hamal-and-kristi-kc-kicked-out-of-bhagya-rekha/|archive-date=20 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe affair of Kristi Mainali, and Hamal became highly popular throughout Nepal, and after [[Deepak Rayamajhi]] successful film director debut he signed Mainali and Hamal into his next project titled ''[[Yug Dekhi Yug Samma]]'' (1991).<ref name=\":0\" /> The film follows two young couples who are amidst the pressure of their family rivalries. Along the side of lead actors debut, it was also the film producer Chhabiraj Ojha, and action director Rajendra Khadgi film debut too.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/nepali-movie-yug-dekhi-yug-samma/|title=Nepali Movie \u2013 Yug Dekhi Yug Samma \u2013 Nepali Movies, films|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520171237/https://xnepali.net/nepali-movie-yug-dekhi-yug-samma/|archive-date=20 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Hamal later told ''Teenz, \"''Actually somewhere inside I always wanted to act. More than acting, I was fascinated by films. I wanted to something in the field, but I did not know how to begin. Luckily, my cousin was a part of the film industry and he offered me a role. That was in 1990, and at that time. I did not know I would be doing films for the next 20 years\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://teenz.com.np/article/my-teenage-days/rajesh-hamal.html|title=Rajesh Hamal \u2013 My teenage days \u2013 Teenz|website=teenz.com.np|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514193657/http://teenz.com.np/article/my-teenage-days/rajesh-hamal.html|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After the success of the film it was later remade with the same title in 2009, directed by [[Dipendra K Khanal]], and the film starred [[Nandita K.C.]], and Hamal in the lead roles.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Yug Dekhi Yug Samma|url=https://www.lensnepal.com/movie/the-yug-dekhi-yug-samma/casts.html|access-date=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n<nowiki> </nowiki>In 1993 Hamal joined up with [[Tulsi Ghimire]] for the first time, in his directorial film project called ''[[Deuta]].'' The film starred Hamal in the lead role beside the film also starred [[Shrawan Ghimire]], Srijana Basnet, and Tulsi Ghimire in the supporting roles.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/nepali-movie-deuta/|title=Nepali Movie \u2013 Deuta|date=3 October 2009|website=Nepali Movies, films|access-date=4 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904010055/https://xnepali.net/nepali-movie-deuta/|archive-date=4 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Upon film's release it became super hit at the box office of Nepal.<ref name=\":4\" /> The film is also considered the film that launched his stardom in the [[Cinema of Nepal|Nepalese film industry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2011-12-30/silver-screen-milestones.html|title=Silver screen milestones|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|access-date=4 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504115541/http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2011-12-30/silver-screen-milestones.html|archive-date=4 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'' wrote, \"Incidentally, this was also the film that catapulted Hamal into stardom and while that alone could place Deuta in a Kollywood Hall of Fame (if such a thing existed), the movie is much more than that\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2011-12-30/silver-screen-milestones.html|title=Silver screen milestones|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|access-date=15 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515134600/http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2011-12-30/silver-screen-milestones.html|archive-date=15 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000 Hamal was cast in actor [[Neer Shah]] directorial film titled [[Basanti (2000 film)|''Basanti'']] (2000). In the film Hamal portrayed the role of [[Gagan Singh Bhandari|Gagan Singh Khawas]], alongside Hamal appeared with [[Karishma Manandhar]], [[Gauri Malla]], and [[Divya Dutta]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Basanti|url=https://www.lensnepal.com/movie/basanti.html|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021001607/http://www.lensnepal.com/movie/basanti.html|archive-date=21 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The film is based on the novel of the same written by [[Diamond Shumsher Rana]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmsofnepal.com/nepali-film-seto-bagh-2015/|title=Nepali Film \u2013 Seto Bagh (2015)|date=3 April 2015|website=Films of Nepal|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815142021/https://filmsofnepal.com/nepali-film-seto-bagh-2015/|archive-date=15 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The film was also listed in \"Top 10 Nepali movies you shouldn't miss\" on the number six made by ''Xnepali.net.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/top-10-nepali-movies-you-shouldnt-miss/|title=Top 10 Nepali movies you shouldn't miss (Full movies) \u2013 Nepali Movies, films|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130062430/https://xnepali.net/top-10-nepali-movies-you-shouldnt-miss/|archive-date=30 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Hamal considers his favourite film to be ''[[Deuta]]'' (1991), and ''Basanti'' (2000).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xnepali.net/rajesh-hamal/|title=Rajesh Hamal Biography \u2013 Nepali Movies, films|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515093018/https://xnepali.net/rajesh-hamal/|archive-date=15 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Bijaya Adhikari of ''OnlineKhabar'' wrote, \"However, filmmakers like Nir Shah, one of the forerunners of the historical period drama genre, has been consistently making successful films in the genre like Basanti, Masaan and Seto Bagh.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.onlinekhabar.com/successful-nepali-filmmakers-historical-genre.html|title=How successful have Nepali filmmakers been with the historical genre? \u2013 OnlineKhabar|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520182011/http://english.onlinekhabar.com/successful-nepali-filmmakers-historical-genre.html|archive-date=20 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Rachana Chettri, and Preena Shrestha of ''[[The Kathmandu Post]]'' also wrote, \"Cinematographically, the film achieves its purpose of bringing the old palaces and courtyards populated by royals and their supporters back to life.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2011-12-30/silver-screen-milestones.html|title=Silver screen milestones|website=kathmandupost.ekantipur.com|access-date=20 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515134600/http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2011-12-30/silver-screen-milestones.html|archive-date=15 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThen in 2004 Hamal appeared in a Shiva Regmi directorial film named ''[[Hami Tin Bhai]]'' (2004). The film starred an [[ensemble cast]] of [[Shree Krishna Shrestha]], [[Nikhil Upreti]], [[Jharana Thapa]], [[Nandita K.C.]], and [[Rekha Thapa]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Fy9uAAAAMAAJ&q=Hami+Teen+Bhai&dq=Hami+Teen+Bhai|title=Nepal Yearbook|date=2006|publisher=Institute for Integrated Development Studies|language=en}}</ref> In 2018 it was announced the sequel of the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nepalifeed.com/%e0%a4%9a%e0%a4%b0%e0%a5%8d%e0%a4%9a%e0%a4%bf%e0%a4%a4-%e0%a4%ab%e0%a4%bf%e0%a4%b2%e0%a5%8d%e0%a4%ae-%e0%a4%b9%e0%a4%be%e0%a4%ae%e0%a5%80-%e0%a5%a9-%e0%a4%ad%e0%a4%be%e0%a4%88-%e0%a4%95%e0%a5%8b/|title=\u091a\u0930\u094d\u091a\u093f\u0924 \u092b\u093f\u0932\u094d\u092e \"\u0939\u093e\u092e\u0940 \u0969 \u092d\u093e\u0908\" \u0915\u094b \u0938\u093f\u0915\u094d\u0935\u0947\u0932\u092e\u093e \u0969 \u092d\u093e\u0907 \u092c\u0928\u094d\u0926\u0948 \u0905\u0928\u092e\u094b\u0932, \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0926\u0940\u092a \u0930 \u092a\u0932 !|date=22 November 2018|website=Nepali Feed|access-date=20 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Television hosting ===\nHamal has twice been judge for [[Miss Nepal]], once in 1997 with Kamal Rupakheti, Laxmi Keshari Manandhar, and Sanjaya Agarwal, the event was won by [[Jharana Bajracharya]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tghFDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA63&dq=Rajesh+Hamal#v=onepage&q=Rajesh%20Hamal&f=false|title=Miss Nepal Unofficial: Everything about Miss Nepal|last=Nepal|first=Anand|date=1 January 2018|publisher=ebookbhandar.com|isbn=9781546778721}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missnepal.com.np/archive/1997|title=Miss Nepal - The Hidden Treasure|website=missnepal.com.np|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514201808/https://www.missnepal.com.np/archive/1997|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After 10 years later he was the chief judge of [[Miss Nepal 2007]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missnepal.com.np/archive/2007|title=Miss Nepal \u2013 The Hidden Treasure|website=missnepal.com.np|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514205323/https://www.missnepal.com.np/archive/2007|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> he judged alongside [[Malvika Subba]], and [[Bhusan Dahal]], the event was won by [[Sitashma Chand]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/entertainment/sitashma-is-miss-nepal-2007/|title=Sitashma is Miss Nepal 2007|date=7 April 2007|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=14 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514210616/https://thehimalayantimes.com/entertainment/sitashma-is-miss-nepal-2007/|archive-date=14 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, he was hosting the [[Ko Banchha Crorepati|Nepalese version]] of ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/multimedia/video-gallery/world/ko-banchha-crorepati-premiers-in-nepal-78696.htm|title=\"Ko Banchha Crorepati\" premiers in Nepal|work=Business Standard India|access-date=4 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504120756/https://www.business-standard.com/multimedia/video-gallery/world/ko-banchha-crorepati-premiers-in-nepal-78696.htm|archive-date=4 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== In the media ==\nHamal is often referred to as \"Mahanayak\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/40289/|title=Mahanayak Rajesh Hamal gets five \u2013 year \u2013 old admitted to school|website=My Republica|access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref> and \"Rajesh Dai\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.onlinekhabar.com/looking-for-quick-success-and-fame-listen-to-what-rajesh-hamal-has-to-say.html|title=Looking for quick fame? Listen to what Rajesh Hamal has to say \u2013 OnlineKhabar|access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref> [[Karishma Manandhar]], Nepalese actress said, if Hamal ran for Mayor of Kathmandu she would vote for him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kathmandupost.com/art-entertainment/2017/04/18/would-you-vote-for-rajesh-hamal-karishmaa-would|title=Would you vote for Rajesh Hamal? Karishmaa would|website=kathmandupost.com|access-date=10 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 Hamal was compared to Indian actors [[Amitabh Bachchan]], and [[Shah Rukh Khan]] by Indian media ''[[Aaj Tak]]''.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/70919/|title=Rajesh Hamal Shines in India, being compared to Amitabh and Shahrukh|last=Republica|website=My City|access-date=9 August 2019}}</ref> ''[[Aaj Tak]]'' wrote, \"Rajesh is such a superstar who has conferred with the title of megastar. Also Rajesh who is 55-years-old is still popular among Nepali film enthusiast which is similar to the fandom of Bollywood super stars \u2014Amitabh and Shahrukh\".<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aajtak.intoday.in/gallery/amitabh-bachchan-of-nepali-cinema-mahanayak-actor-rajesh-hamal-tmov-5-37039.html|title=\u092f\u0947 \u0939\u0948\u0902 \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0940 \u0938\u093f\u0928\u0947\u092e\u093e \u0915\u0947 '\u0905\u092e\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092d', 22 \u0938\u093e\u0932 \u091b\u094b\u091f\u0940 \u092e\u0949\u0921\u0932 \u0938\u0947 \u0915\u0940 \u0925\u0940 \u0936\u093e\u0926\u0940 \u2013 Entertainment Gallery AajTak|website=India Today|language=hi|access-date=9 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Film\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|1991\n|[[National Film Awards (Nepal)|National Film Awards]]\n|{{N/A}}\n|Yug Dekhi Yug Samma\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulf-times.com/story/522692|title=All set for 'Nepali-Bhojpuri Mega Star Night'|date=28 November 2016|website=Gulf Times|language=ar|access-date=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2003\n|Lux Film Awards\n|Best Actor\n|''[[Muktidata]]''\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/dec/01nepal.htm|title=Now, Nepal has its own film awards, too!|publisher=Rediff.com|access-date=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1101742}}\n{{Sister project links}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Nepal|Film|Biography|Arts  }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamal, Rajesh}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:People from Palpa District]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male actors]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male models]]\n[[Category:20th-century Nepalese male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Nepalese male actors]]\n[[Category:Thakuri]]\n[[Category:Nepalese film producers]]\n[[Category:Television presenters]]\n[[Category:Game show hosts]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male television actors]]\n[[Category:Male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male film actors]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male singers]]\n[[Category:Nepalese musicians]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male dancers]]\n[[Category:Nepalese businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "68.82.250.68", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rajesh_Hamal"}
{"title_page": "Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi", "text_new": "[[Grand Ayatollah]] [[Mirza]] '''Mahdi al-Husayni al-Shirazi ''' ({{Lang-ar| \u0645\u0647\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0632\u064a}}; {{lang-fa|{{nq|\u0645\u0647\u062f\u0649 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u0649 \u0634\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0632\u0649}}}}; 9 May 1887 \u2013  15 February 1961), also known as '''Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi''', was an [[Iraqis|Iraqi]]-[[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] [[Twelver]] [[Shia]] [[Marja'|marja]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://persian.shirazi.ir/shownews.php?Code=2681|title=Gusha-e Az Zendegani Ayat Ullah al-Uzma Mirza Mahdi Husayni Shirazi Qudisah Siruh|last=|first=|date=|website=Official Website of Ayatollah Shirazi|language=fa|trans-title=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://annabaa.org/arabic/historic/11149|title=Thikra Wafat al-Sayyid Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi Fi 28 Shaban|last=|first=|date=|website=An-Nabaa Information Network|language=ar|trans-title=Ayatollah Sayyid al-Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi's death anniversary on the 28th of Shaban (lunar calendar)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.varesoon.ir/shiite-scholars-biographies/references-ayatollahs110/785-ayatollah-seyed-mehdi-shirazi.html|title=Hazrat Ayat Ullah Sayyid Mahdi Shirazi|last=|first=|date=|website=Varesoon|language=fa|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%B9%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1_%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A1_%D9%88%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%B1%D9%87%D8%A7.html?id=L3ltAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Asha'er Karbala Wa 'Usariha|date=|publisher=Dar al-Mahaja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=78\u20139|language=ar|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=al-\u02bb\u0100mil\u012b|first=Mu\u1e25sin al-\u1e24usayn\u012b|url=https://www.noorlib.ir/View/ar/Book/BookView/Text/22735/1/213|title=A\u02bby\u0101n al-Sh\u012b\u02bbah|publisher=Dar al-Ta'arof lil-Matboo'at|year=1982|isbn=|volume=50|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=115|language=Arabic|trans-title=Prominent Figures of the Shia}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Zanjani|first=Ibrahim|url=http://alfeker.net/library.php?id=1240|title=Jawla Fi al-Amakin al-Muqadasah|publisher=Dar al-A'lami Lil Matb'ooat|year=1984|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=103\u20135|trans-title=A Stroll In Religious Sites}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=al-A'lami|first=Muhammad-Husayn|url=http://archive.org/details/olomnasb_ymail_20180204|title=Manar al-Huda Fi al-Ansab|publisher=Maktabat Uloom al-Ansab|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=230\u201331|language=ar|trans-title=The Path of Guidance In Lineages}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ScQ-AQAAIAAJ|title=Mashahir al-Madfunin Fi Karbala|publisher=Dar al-Safwa|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=88|language=ar|trans-title=Famous Figures Buried In Karbala}}</ref>{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Shia Islam]]\n| name       = Mahdi al-Husayni al-Shirazi\n| image      = File:Sayyidmahdishirazi.png\n| caption    = \n| title      = [[Grand Ayatollah]] \n| birth_date = {{birth date|1887|5|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place= [[Karbala]], [[Baghdad Vilayet]], [[Ottoman Empire]] \n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1961|2|15|1887|5|9|df=y}}\n| death_place= [[Karbala]], [[Republic of Iraq]]\n| Maddhab    =  \n| school_tradition = \n| region           = \n| main_interests   = \n| notable_ideas    =\n| works            = \n| influences       =\n| influenced       = \n| website          =\n|honorific prefix=[[Grand Ayatollah]] [[Mirza]]|children=[[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad]] <br /> [[Hassan al-Shirazi|Hassan]] <br /> [[Sadiq Hussaini Shirazi|Sadiq]] <br /> [[Mujtaba Hussaini Shirazi|Mujtaba]]|relatives=[[Mirza Shirazi]] (great uncle) <br /> [[Mirza Taqi al-Shirazi]] (maternal uncle) <br /> [[Mohammed Ridha al-Shirazi]] (grandson) <br /> [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi]] (grandson) <br /> [[Hadi al-Modarresi]] (grandson) <br /> [[Ali Akbar al-Modarresi]] (grandson)|resting_place=[[Imam Husayn Shrine]]|office1=|native_name=\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0631\u0632\u0627 \u0645\u0647\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0632\u064a|background=#ABE9CC}}After the deah of [[Abu l-Hasan al-Isfahani|Abu al-Hasan al-Esfehani]] and Hossein Tabatabaei Qomi, Mirza Mahdi was considered to be the highest ranking cleric in Karbala,<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Fiqari|first=Dr. Nasir|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4doPCwAAQBAJ|title=Usul Mathhab al-Shia al-Imamiya al-Ithna Ashariya (Ardh Wa Naqd)|publisher=|year=1993|isbn=|volume=1|location=|pages=1038|language=ar|trans-title=The Foundations of the Twelver Shia Imami Madhhab (Display and Critique)}}</ref> and one of the highest in Iraq, along with [[Muhsin al-Hakim]] and his second cousin once removed, [[Abd al-Hadi al-Shirazi]] in Najaf.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Azzawi|first=Dr. Fadhil|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JGl_DwAAQBAJ|title=Khafaya al-Mu'amarat al-Duwaliya Li Isqat al-Hukm al-Watani al-Qawmi Fi al-Iraq Munth Ta'sisahu Aam 1921 Wa Lighayat Ihtilalih Aam 2003|date=2017-01-01|publisher=Al Manhal|year=|isbn=9796500275406|location=|pages=34|language=ar|trans-title=Hidden State Conspiracies To Befall The National Patriotic Governance In Iraq From Its Conception In 1921 Til Its Invasion In 2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Shahroudi|first=Nur al-Din|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A9_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9.html?id=b2hWXwAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Tarikh al-Haraka al-Ilmiya Fi Karbala|date=1990|publisher=Dar al-Uloom Liltahqeeq Wal Tiba'a Wal Nashr Wal Towzee'|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=202|language=ar|trans-title=The History of the Clerical Movement of Karbala}}</ref>\n\nMirza Mahdi was the [[Imam]] of the [[Imam Husayn Shrine]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life ===\nHe was born in the city of Karbala to the prominent religious [[Shirazi family]]. His father was Mirza Habibullah al-Shirazi, and his mother was Radhiya Golshan-Shirazi (daughter of Muhib Ali Golshan-Shirazi). Mirza Mahdi is the fourth of eight children. His eldest brother, Muhammd-Sadiq, died young. The remaining two of his brothers were also clerics; his older brother, Abdullah al-Shirazi (grandfather of [[Ali al-Sistani|Ali al-Sistani's]] wife; also known as al-Tawasuli), and younger brother, Jafar al-Shirazi. His elder sister, Um Moosa, was married to his cousin, senior cleric, Abd al-Hadi al-Shirazi.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMirza Mahdi began his religious education at a very early age, carrying out his introductory studies in Karbala, under his brother, Abdullah al-Tawasuli, Sayyid Husayn Khayr al-Din and Sayyid Muhammad-Hassan Agha Mir al-Qazwini.<ref name=\":5\" /> After his father, Mirza Habibullah passed away in 1902, he moved to [[Najaf]], to study under the two greats, [[Akhund Khorasani|Akhund Khurasani]] and [[Mohammed Kazem Yazdi|Muhammad-Kadhim Yazdi]]. He then travelled to [[Samarra]] with his family, to study in its seminary - under his maternal uncle, [[Mirza Taqi al-Shirazi|Mirza Muhammad-Taqi al-Shirazi]] and Hasan al-Sadr - which the former was managing at the time.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDuring the [[Siege of Kut|siege of Kut]], Mirza Mahdi travelled to [[Kadhimiya]], with his uncle Mirza Taqi, who feared that Samarra could end up like Kut, and that way many from the religious sphere would die. They remained in Kadhimiya for approximately a year and a half, living a life of dire poverty, until they returned to Karbala, where Mirza Taqi, was preparing to lead the [[Iraqi revolt of 1920|independence movement]] against the British. He remained in Karbala, and played an active supporting role with his uncle in the Iraqi revolt, until his uncle was poisoned in 1920.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alshirazi.net/karbala/olama/09.htm|title=al-Thikra al-Tasi'a Wal Arbaoon Liraheel al-Marja al-Muqadas Ayatollah al-Udhma al-Sayyid Mirza Mahdi al-Husayni al-Shirazi Qudisa Siruh|last=|first=|date=|website=Official Website of Ayatollah Shirazi|trans-title=The 49th anniversary of the demise of the divine jurist Grand Ayatollah Sayyid Mirza Mahdi al-Husayni al-Shirazi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Lukitz|first=Liora|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hk-RAgAAQBAJ|title=Iraq: The Search for National Identity|date=2005-07-05|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-135-77820-0|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\nAfter the death of his uncle, he moved back to Najaf, to resume his religious education, and studied under his first cousin once removed, Mirza Ali Agha al-Shirazi, as well as [[Muhammad Hossein Naini|al-Muhaqiq al-Naini]] and [[Agha Zia ol Din Araghi|al-Muhaqiq al-Iraqi]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />[[File:Mirzamehdi.jpg|thumb|200px|Mirza Mahdi (centre left) with his teacher Hossein Qomi (centre right)|alt=|left]]\n\n=== Return to Karbala ===\nIn 1935, senior cleric Hossein Tabatabaei Qomi was exiled from Iran, by [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi|Muhammed Reza Shah]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shakibi|first=Zhand|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4k6_DwAAQBAJ|title=Pahlavi Iran and the Politics of Occidentalism: The Shah and the Rastakhiz Party|date=2019-12-12|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|year=|isbn=978-1-78673-630-7|location=|pages=123|language=en}}</ref> So Qomi emigrated to Karbala, and sent a request for Mirza Mahdi to return to Karbala, so that he may join him in his quest to revive its seminary, to which Mirza Mahdi accepted and returned to his birthplace. After the death of Qomi in 1947, Mirza Mahdi became the head of the seminary of Karbala, and its most senior jurist. This was also solidified further, with the death of notable cleric, Muhammad-Hadi al-Khurasani in 1949.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Dr Shaykh Muhammad-Sadiq|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Of-PDwAAQBAJ|title=Adhwa' Ala Madinat al-Husayn (Qism al-Haraka al-Ilmiyah Fi al-Ha'ir|date=2017-10-16|publisher=Hussaini Centre for Research, London.|year=|isbn=978-1-78403-023-0|volume=1|location=London, UK|pages=66|language=ar|trans-title=Lights on the City of Husayn (The Religious Movement in the Haer)}}</ref>\n\n=== Karbala Seminary Term ===\nThe [[hawza]] of Karbala grew immensely under Mirza Mahdi's term as head, as he innovated new methods to teach religious studies, which attracted many youth to join the seminary.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=al-Shahroudi|first=Nur al-Din|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A9_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9.html?id=b2hWXwAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Tarikh al-Haraka al-Ilmiya Fi Karbala|date=1990|publisher=Dar al-Uloom Liltahqeeq Wal Tiba'a Wal Nashr Wal Towzee'|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=206|language=ar|trans-title=The History of the Clerical Movement of Karbala}}</ref> He taught many that later became influential scholars like Sheikh Muhammad al-Karbassi, Sayyid Muhammad-Sadiq al-Qazwini, Sheikh Muhammad al-Shahroudi, \u0650Sayyid Abdullah al-Khoei, Sayyid Ahmed al-Fali and Sheikh Jafar al-Rashti.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Dr Shaykh Muhammad-Sadiq|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Of-PDwAAQBAJ|title=Adhwa' Ala Madinat al-Husayn (Qism al-Haraka al-Ilmiyah Fi al-Ha'ir|date=2017-10-16|publisher=Hussaini Centre for Research, London.|year=|isbn=978-1-78403-023-0|volume=1|location=London, UK|pages=67|language=ar|trans-title=Lights on the City of Husayn (The Religious Movement in the Haer)}}</ref> Under his term, many different festivals were innovated, including the recitation of the renowned [[Maqtal al-Husayn|maqtal]], that was recited in the shrine of Imam Husayn for the first time, by his student, Sheikh [[Abd al-Zahra al-Kaabi|Abd al-Zahra al-Ka'bi]], in [[Muharram]] 1379 (1959 AD).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hasan|first=Dakhil|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ey5HCwAAQBAJ|title=Mu'jam al-Khutaba'|publisher=al-Mu'asasa al-Alamiya Lil Thaqafa Wal I'lam|year=1996|isbn=|volume=1|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=231|language=ar|trans-title=The Orator Glossary}}</ref>\n\n=== Iraqi citizenship protest ===\nMirza Mahdi was active in the Iranian community of Karbala (whether in the seminary or in social circles). This was in 1958, a time where the Iranian community was being politically isolated, in the face of an [[Iraqi Republic (1958\u201368)|Iraqi government]] that was raising the banner of [[Arab nationalism]]. Due to this situation, Mirza Mahdi sent a letter to the governor of Karbala, Fuad Arif,<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.com/?id=obYxAAAAIAAJ|title=Karbal\u0101\u02bc F\u012b al-Dh\u0101kirah|date=1988|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=51|language=ar|trans-title=Memories Of Karbala}}</ref> who was of Kurdish descent, objecting the treatment of the Iranians. This angered Fuad, and so he responded by accusing Mirza Mahdi of being Iranian himself, and that he had no right to interfere with Iraqi matters. Mirza Mahdi retorted, but this time with an angry tone, reminding Fuad, that it was us that ignited the 1920 revolt, and ended up kicking the British out, saving the independence and honour of Iraq. He also told him that if he did not want to work in accordance to their demands, then he can leave the city.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=al-Azzawi|first=Dr. Fadhil|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JGl_DwAAQBAJ|title=Khafaya al-Mu'amarat al-Duwaliya Li Isqat al-Hukm al-Watani al-Qawmi Fi al-Iraq Munth Ta'sisahu Aam 1921 Wa Lighayat Ihtilalih Aam 2003|date=2017-01-01|publisher=Al Manhal|year=|isbn=9796500275406|location=|pages=31\u20132|language=ar|trans-title=Hidden State Conspiracies To Befall The National Patriotic Governance In Iraq From Its Conception In 1921 Til Its Invasion In 2003}}</ref>\n\nAfter this, Mirza Mahdi founded a new philosophy, which was that he was not going to hold an Iraqi citizenship, deeming it as an imperialistic innovation, invented to crush the ranks of the Muslims. He also claimed that it violated the liberty of man and the [[sharia]], and would create mental barriers within the minds of people. He also explained, that the citizenship was a devotion of dominance by the [[Abd al-Karim Qasim|ruling Sunni]] government over the Shia.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Stand against communism ===\nAfter the [[14 July Revolution|14 July coup]], Abd al-Karim Qasim allowed [[communism]] to flourish in his new republic. Within six months, Iraq was turned into a blood bath of pro-communist protests, attacking the homes of religious clerics and nationalists. It was so bad, it is reported that a Muslim would feel estranged in a city like Najaf.\n\nOne time, a protest was formed in Karbala, with some of the leaders of the city's communist movement. They had a list of fifty two names (this included Mirza Mahdi's son [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad]]), of the people they planned to attack their homes and kill, for the reason that they 'stood against communism and the \"red tide\"'.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=552\u201353|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref>\n\nThis is when the senior jurists of the time decided to take a stand to counter this wave of terror. A meeting was held consisting of Mirza Mahdi, Muhsin al-Hakim and [[Abu al-Qasim al-Khoei]] in Mirza Mahdi's home in Karbala. The result was that they were going to issue religious [[fatwa]]s branding the [[Iraqi Communist Party|Communist party]] as [[Kafir|infidels]]. They also began to coordinate activities to counter their alleged corrupt ideology. These measures were considered to be the beginning of the end of communism in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Shirazi|first=Muhammad|title=al-Iraq Bayn al-Madhi Wal Hadhir Wal Mustaqbal|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=887|language=ar|trans-title=Iraq Between The Past, Present and Future}}</ref>\n\nMirza Mahdi issued several fatwa's condemning adherence to the Communist party, going as far as stating that a true Muslim could not buy meat from a communist butcher.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=90|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMirza Mahdi was married to his second cousin's daughter, Halima al-Shirazi with whom he had ten children; four sons (Muhammad, Hassan, [[Sadiq Hussaini Shirazi|Sadiq]], [[Mujtaba Hussaini Shirazi|Mujtaba]]) and six daughters. One of his daughters was married to [[Mohammed Kadhim al-Modarresi|Muhammad-Kadhim al-Modarresi]], and another was married to [[Mohammed Kadhim al-Qazwini|Muhammad-Kadhim al-Qazwini]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nbo.ir/%D8%B3%DB%8C%D8%AF-%D9%85%D9%87%D8%AF%DB%8C-%D8%AD%D8%B3%DB%8C%D9%86%DB%8C-%D8%B4%DB%8C%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B2%DB%8C__a-470.aspx|title=Sayyid Mahdi Husayni Shirazi|last=|first=|date=|website=The Shia Educational and Cultural Centre|language=fa|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Works==\n\n=== Books ===\nMirza Mahdi authored a large number of books, which includes some of his most important ones:\n\n* ''Sharh al-Urwat al-Wuthqa'' (Dissecting [[Urwa al-Wuthqa|The Firmest Bond]])\n* ''Thakhirat al-Ibad'' (The Worshippers' Provisions)\n* ''Manasek al-Haj'' ([[Hajj]] Rituals)\n* ''Kashkool Fi Mukhtalaf al-'Uloom'' (An Assortment In Different Sciences)\n\n=== Poetry ===\nMirza Mahdi also wrote poetry in praise of the [[Ahl al-Bayt|Ahlulbayt]]. His most known poem was written on the auspicious birth anniversary of [[Fatimah|Fatima]], which begins with:<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Dr Shaykh Muhammad-Sadiq|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pzoKv4vsOcwC|title=al-Madkhal Ila al-Shi'r al-Husayni|publisher=Hussaini Centre for Research|year=|isbn=978-1-902490-19-9|volume=1|location=London, UK|pages=41|language=ar|trans-title=The Gateway to Husayni Poetry}}</ref>{{Verse translation|{{lang|ar|rtl=yes|\n\u062f\u0631\u0651\u0629 \u0623\u0634\u0631\u0642\u062a \u0628\u0623\u0628\u0647\u0649 \u0633\u0646\u0627\u0647\u0627\n\u0641\u062a\u0644\u0623\u0644\u0623 \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0631\u0649 \u0641\u064a\u0627 \u0628\u064f\u0634\u0631\u0627\u0647\u0627\n\u0644\u0645\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u0646 \u0645\u0646 \u0633\u0646\u0627 \u0646\u0648\u0631 \u0642\u062f\u0633\n\u0628\u0633\u0646\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0623\u0636\u0627\u0621 \u0637\u0648\u0627\u0647\u0627}}|A pearl has risen with prestigious light,\nThe world has been illuminated, glad tidings.\nThe universe shines from the divine light,\nWith His light, he illuminated her valley.|italicsoff=y|rtl1=y}}\n\n== Death ==\n[[File:Mirzamehdi3.jpg|thumb|249x249px|Funeral of Mirza Mahdi, Karbala|alt=]]Mirza Mahdi died in the early hours of Wednesday, February 15, 1961. During the bathing of his corpse, there was a partial [[Solar eclipse of February 15, 1961|solar eclipse]] that took place, with 67% obscurity<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEgoogle/SEgoogle1951/SE1961Feb15Tgoogle.html|title=NASA - Total Solar Eclipse of 1961 Feb 15|website=eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> that darkened the city of Karbala for just under an hour, as witnessed by the people of the city, who rushed to pray the [[Sign prayer|Ayat prayer]], before resuming with the funeral. He was buried in the south eastern side of the Imam Husayn Shrine.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Reactions ===\nThe Shia world was struck upon Mirza Mahdi's death. It is reported that [[Hossein Borujerdi]], who was in [[Qom]], cried for a few minutes over the news of Mirza Mahdi's demise.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shirazi, Seyed Mahdi Hosseini}}\n[[Category:Iraqi grand ayatollahs]]\n[[Category:People from Karbala]]\n[[Category:Shia clerics]]\n[[Category:Iranian Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "[[Grand Ayatollah]] [[Mirza]] '''Mahdi al-Husayni al-Shirazi ''' ({{Lang-ar| \u0645\u0647\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0632\u064a}}; {{lang-fa|{{nq|\u0645\u0647\u062f\u0649 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u0649 \u0634\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0632\u0649}}}}; 9 May 1887 \u2013  15 February 1961), also known as '''Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi''', was an [[Iraqis|Iraqi]]-[[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] [[Twelver]] [[Shia]] [[Marja'|marja]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://persian.shirazi.ir/shownews.php?Code=2681|title=Gusha-e Az Zendegani Ayat Ullah al-Uzma Mirza Mahdi Husayni Shirazi Qudisah Siruh|last=|first=|date=|website=Official Website of Ayatollah Shirazi|language=fa|trans-title=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://annabaa.org/arabic/historic/11149|title=Thikra Wafat al-Sayyid Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi Fi 28 Shaban|last=|first=|date=|website=An-Nabaa Information Network|language=ar|trans-title=Ayatollah Sayyid al-Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi's death anniversary on the 28th of Shaban (lunar calendar)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.varesoon.ir/shiite-scholars-biographies/references-ayatollahs110/785-ayatollah-seyed-mehdi-shirazi.html|title=Hazrat Ayat Ullah Sayyid Mahdi Shirazi|last=|first=|date=|website=Varesoon|language=fa|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%B9%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1_%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A1_%D9%88%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%B1%D9%87%D8%A7.html?id=L3ltAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Asha'er Karbala Wa 'Usariha|date=|publisher=Dar al-Mahaja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=78\u20139|language=ar|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=al-\u02bb\u0100mil\u012b|first=Mu\u1e25sin al-\u1e24usayn\u012b|url=https://www.noorlib.ir/View/ar/Book/BookView/Text/22735/1/213|title=A\u02bby\u0101n al-Sh\u012b\u02bbah|publisher=Dar al-Ta'arof lil-Matboo'at|year=1982|isbn=|volume=50|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=115|language=Arabic|trans-title=Prominent Figures of the Shia}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Zanjani|first=Ibrahim|url=http://alfeker.net/library.php?id=1240|title=Jawla Fi al-Amakin al-Muqadasah|publisher=Dar al-A'lami Lil Matb'ooat|year=1984|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=103\u20135|trans-title=A Stroll In Religious Sites}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=al-A'lami|first=Muhammad-Husayn|url=http://archive.org/details/olomnasb_ymail_20180204|title=Manar al-Huda Fi al-Ansab|publisher=Maktabat Uloom al-Ansab|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=230\u201331|language=ar|trans-title=The Path of Guidance In Lineages}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ScQ-AQAAIAAJ|title=Mashahir al-Madfunin Fi Karbala|publisher=Dar al-Safwa|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=88|language=ar|trans-title=Famous Figures Buried In Karbala}}</ref>{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Shia Islam]]\n| name       = Mahdi al-Husayni al-Shirazi\n| image      = File:Sayyidmahdishirazi.png\n| caption    = \n| title      = [[Grand Ayatollah]] \n| birth_date = {{birth date|1887|5|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place= [[Karbala]], [[Baghdad Vilayet]], [[Ottoman Empire]] \n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1961|2|15|1887|5|9|df=y}}\n| death_place= [[Karbala]], [[Republic of Iraq]]\n| Maddhab    =  \n| school_tradition = \n| region           = \n| main_interests   = \n| notable_ideas    =\n| works            = \n| influences       =\n| influenced       = \n| website          =\n|honorific prefix=[[Grand Ayatollah]] [[Mirza]]|children=[[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad]] <br /> [[Hassan al-Shirazi|Hassan]] <br /> [[Sadiq Hussaini Shirazi|Sadiq]] <br /> [[Mujtaba Hussaini Shirazi|Mujtaba]]|relatives=[[Mirza Shirazi]] (great uncle) <br /> [[Mirza Taqi al-Shirazi]] (maternal uncle) <br /> [[Mohammed Ridha al-Shirazi]] (grandson) <br /> [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi]] (grandson) <br /> [[Hadi al-Modarresi]] (grandson) <br /> [[Ali Akbar al-Modarresi]] (grandson)|resting_place=[[Imam Husayn Shrine]]|office1=|native_name=\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0631\u0632\u0627 \u0645\u0647\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0632\u064a|background=#ABE9CC}}After the deah of [[Abu l-Hasan al-Isfahani|Abu al-Hasan al-Esfehani]] and Hossein Tabatabaei Qomi, Mirza Mahdi was considered to be the highest ranking cleric in Karbala,<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Fiqari|first=Dr. Nasir|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4doPCwAAQBAJ|title=Usul Mathhab al-Shia al-Imamiya al-Ithna Ashariya (Ardh Wa Naqd)|publisher=|year=1993|isbn=|volume=1|location=|pages=1038|language=ar|trans-title=The Foundations of the Twelver Shia Imami Madhhab (Display and Critique)}}</ref> and one of the highest in Iraq, along with [[Muhsin al-Hakim]] and his second cousin once removed, [[Abd al-Hadi al-Shirazi]] in Najaf.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Azzawi|first=Dr. Fadhil|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JGl_DwAAQBAJ|title=Khafaya al-Mu'amarat al-Duwaliya Li Isqat al-Hukm al-Watani al-Qawmi Fi al-Iraq Munth Ta'sisahu Aam 1921 Wa Lighayat Ihtilalih Aam 2003|date=2017-01-01|publisher=Al Manhal|year=|isbn=9796500275406|location=|pages=34|language=ar|trans-title=Hidden State Conspiracies To Befall The National Patriotic Governance In Iraq From Its Conception In 1921 Til Its Invasion In 2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Shahroudi|first=Nur al-Din|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A9_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9.html?id=b2hWXwAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Tarikh al-Haraka al-Ilmiya Fi Karbala|date=1990|publisher=Dar al-Uloom Liltahqeeq Wal Tiba'a Wal Nashr Wal Towzee'|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=202|language=ar|trans-title=The History of the Clerical Movement of Karbala}}</ref>\n\nMirza Mahdi was the [[Imam]] of the [[Imam Husayn Shrine]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life ===\nHe was born in the city of Karbala to the prominent religious [[Shirazi family]]. His father was Mirza Habibullah al-Shirazi, and his mother was Radhiya Golshan-Shirazi (daughter of Muhib Ali Golshan-Shirazi). Mirza Mahdi is the fourth of eight children. His eldest brother, Muhammd-Sadiq, died young. The remaining two of his brothers were also clerics; his older brother, Abdullah al-Shirazi (grandfather of [[Ali al-Sistani|Ali al-Sistani's]] wife; also known as al-Tawasuli), and younger brother, Jafar al-Shirazi. His elder sister, Um Moosa, was married to his cousin, senior cleric, Abd al-Hadi al-Shirazi.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMirza Mahdi began his religious education at a very early age, carrying out his introductory studies in Karbala, under his brother, Abdullah al-Tawasuli, Sayyid Husayn Khayr al-Din and Sayyid Muhammad-Hassan Agha Mir al-Qazwini.<ref name=\":5\" /> After his father, Mirza Habibullah passed away in 1902, he moved to [[Najaf]], to study under the two greats, [[Akhund Khorasani|Akhund Khurasani]] and [[Mohammed Kazem Yazdi|Muhammad-Kadhim Yazdi]]. He then travelled to [[Samarra]] with his family, to study in its seminary - under his maternal uncle, [[Mirza Taqi al-Shirazi|Mirza Muhammad-Taqi al-Shirazi]] and Hasan al-Sadr - which the former was managing at the time.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDuring the [[Siege of Kut|siege of Kut]], Mirza Mahdi travelled to [[Kadhimiya]], with his uncle Mirza Taqi, who feared that Samarra could end up like Kut, and that way many from the religious sphere would die. They remained in Kadhimiya for approximately a year and a half, living a life of dire poverty, until they returned to Karbala, where Mirza Taqi, was preparing to lead the [[Iraqi revolt of 1920|independence movement]] against the British. He remained in Karbala, and played an active supporting role with his uncle in the Iraqi revolt, until his uncle was poisoned in 1920.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alshirazi.net/karbala/olama/09.htm|title=al-Thikra al-Tasi'a Wal Arbaoon Liraheel al-Marja al-Muqadas Ayatollah al-Udhma al-Sayyid Mirza Mahdi al-Husayni al-Shirazi Qudisa Siruh|last=|first=|date=|website=Official Website of Ayatollah Shirazi|trans-title=The 49th anniversary of the demise of the divine jurist Grand Ayatollah Sayyid Mirza Mahdi al-Husayni al-Shirazi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Lukitz|first=Liora|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hk-RAgAAQBAJ|title=Iraq: The Search for National Identity|date=2005-07-05|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-135-77820-0|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\nAfter the death of his uncle, he moved back to Najaf, to resume his religious education, and studied under his first cousin once removed, Mirza Ali Agha al-Shirazi, as well as [[Muhammad Hossein Naini|al-Muhaqiq al-Naini]] and [[Agha Zia ol Din Araghi|al-Muhaqiq al-Iraqi]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />[[File:Mirzamehdi.jpg|thumb|200px|Mirza Mahdi (centre left) with his teacher Hossein Qomi (centre right)|alt=|left]]\n\n=== Return to Karbala ===\nIn 1935, senior cleric Hossein Tabatabaei Qomi was exiled from Iran, by [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi|Muhammed Reza Shah]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shakibi|first=Zhand|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4k6_DwAAQBAJ|title=Pahlavi Iran and the Politics of Occidentalism: The Shah and the Rastakhiz Party|date=2019-12-12|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|year=|isbn=978-1-78673-630-7|location=|pages=123|language=en}}</ref> So Qomi emigrated to Karbala, and sent a request for Mirza Mahdi to return to Karbala, so that he may join him in his quest to revive its seminary, to which Mirza Mahdi accepted and returned to his birthplace. After the death of Qomi in 1947, Mirza Mahdi became the head of the seminary of Karbala, and its most senior jurist. This was also solidified further, with the death of notable cleric, Muhammad-Hadi al-Khurasani in 1949.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Dr Shaykh Muhammad-Sadiq|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Of-PDwAAQBAJ|title=Adhwa' Ala Madinat al-Husayn (Qism al-Haraka al-Ilmiyah Fi al-Ha'ir|date=2017-10-16|publisher=Hussaini Centre for Research, London.|year=|isbn=978-1-78403-023-0|volume=1|location=London, UK|pages=66|language=ar|trans-title=Lights on the City of Husayn (The Religious Movement in the Haer)}}</ref>\n\n=== Karbala Seminary Term ===\nThe [[hawza]] of Karbala grew immensely under Mirza Mahdi's term as head, as he innovated new methods to teach religious studies, which attracted many youth to join the seminary.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=al-Shahroudi|first=Nur al-Din|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%AE_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A9_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%A9.html?id=b2hWXwAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Tarikh al-Haraka al-Ilmiya Fi Karbala|date=1990|publisher=Dar al-Uloom Liltahqeeq Wal Tiba'a Wal Nashr Wal Towzee'|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=206|language=ar|trans-title=The History of the Clerical Movement of Karbala}}</ref> He taught many that later became influential scholars like Sheikh Muhammad al-Karbassi, Sayyid Muhammad-Sadiq al-Qazwini, Sheikh Muhammad al-Shahroudi, \u0650Sayyid Abdullah al-Khoei, Sayyid Ahmed al-Fali and Sheikh Jafar al-Rashti.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Dr Shaykh Muhammad-Sadiq|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Of-PDwAAQBAJ|title=Adhwa' Ala Madinat al-Husayn (Qism al-Haraka al-Ilmiyah Fi al-Ha'ir|date=2017-10-16|publisher=Hussaini Centre for Research, London.|year=|isbn=978-1-78403-023-0|volume=1|location=London, UK|pages=67|language=ar|trans-title=Lights on the City of Husayn (The Religious Movement in the Haer)}}</ref> Under his term, many different festivals were innovated, including the recitation of the renowned [[Maqtal al-Husayn|maqtal]], that was recited in the shrine of Imam Husayn for the first time, by his student, Sheikh [[Abd al-Zahra al-Kaabi|Abd al-Zahra al-Ka'bi]], in [[Muharram]] 1379 (1959 AD).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hasan|first=Dakhil|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ey5HCwAAQBAJ|title=Mu'jam al-Khutaba'|publisher=al-Mu'asasa al-Alamiya Lil Thaqafa Wal I'lam|year=1996|isbn=|volume=1|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=231|language=ar|trans-title=The Orator Glossary}}</ref>\n\n=== Iraqi citizenship protest ===\nMirza Mahdi was active in the Iranian community of Karbala (whether in the seminary or in social circles). This was in 1958, a time where the Iranian community was being politically isolated, in the face of an [[Iraqi Republic (1958\u201368)|Iraqi government]] that was raising the banner of [[Arab nationalism]]. Due to this situation, Mirza Mahdi sent a letter to the governor of Karbala, Fuad Arif,<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.com/?id=obYxAAAAIAAJ|title=Karbal\u0101\u02bc F\u012b al-Dh\u0101kirah|date=1988|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=51|language=ar|trans-title=Memories Of Karbala}}</ref> who was of Kurdish descent, objecting the treatment of the Iranians. This angered Fuad, and so he responded by accusing Mirza Mahdi of being Iranian himself, and that he had no right to interfere with Iraqi matters. Mirza Mahdi retorted, but this time with an angry tone, reminding Fuad, that it was us that ignited the 1920 revolt, and ended up kicking the British out, saving the independence and honour of Iraq. He also told him that if he did not want to work in accordance to their demands, then he can leave the city.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=al-Azzawi|first=Dr. Fadhil|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JGl_DwAAQBAJ|title=Khafaya al-Mu'amarat al-Duwaliya Li Isqat al-Hukm al-Watani al-Qawmi Fi al-Iraq Munth Ta'sisahu Aam 1921 Wa Lighayat Ihtilalih Aam 2003|date=2017-01-01|publisher=Al Manhal|year=|isbn=9796500275406|location=|pages=31\u20132|language=ar|trans-title=Hidden State Conspiracies To Befall The National Patriotic Governance In Iraq From Its Conception In 1921 Til Its Invasion In 2003}}</ref>\n\nAfter this, Mirza Mahdi founded a new philosophy, which was that he was not going to hold an Iraqi citizenship, deeming it as an imperialistic innovation, invented to crush the ranks of the Muslims. He also claimed that it violated the liberty of man and the [[sharia]], and would create mental barriers within the minds of people. He also explained, that the citizenship was a devotion of dominance by the [[Abd al-Karim Qasim|ruling Sunni]] government over the Shia.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Stand against communism ===\nAfter the [[14 July Revolution|14 July coup]], Abd al-Karim Qasim allowed [[communism]] to flourish in his new republic. Within six months, Iraq was turned into a blood bath of pro-communist protests, attacking the homes of religious clerics and nationalists. It was so bad, it is reported that a Muslim would feel estranged in a city like Najaf.\n\nOne time, a protest was formed in Karbala, with some of the leaders of the city's communist movement. They had a list of fifty two names (this included Mirza Mahdi's son [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad]]), of the people they planned to attack their homes and kill, for the reason that they 'stood against communism and the \"red tide\"'.<ref name=\":03\">{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=552\u201353|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref>\n\nThis is when the senior jurists of the time decided to take a stand to counter this wave of terror. A meeting was held consisting of Mirza Mahdi, Muhsin al-Hakim and [[Abu al-Qasim al-Khoei]] in Mirza Mahdi's home in Karbala. The result was that they were going to issue religious [[fatwa]]s branding the [[Iraqi Communist Party|Communist party]] as [[Kafir|infidels]]. They also began to coordinate activities to counter their alleged corrupt ideology. These measures were considered to be the beginning of the end of communism in Iraq.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Shirazi|first=Muhammad|title=al-Iraq Bayn al-Madhi Wal Hadhir Wal Mustaqbal|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=887|language=ar|trans-title=Iraq Between The Past, Present and Future}}</ref>\n\nMirza Mahdi issued several fatwa's condemning adherence to the Communist party, going as far as stating that a true Muslim could not buy meat from a communist butcher.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=90|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMirza Mahdi was married to his second cousin's daughter, Halima al-Shirazi with whom he had ten children; four sons (Muhammad, Hassan, [[Sadiq Hussaini Shirazi|Sadiq]], [[Mujtaba Hussaini Shirazi|Mujtaba]]) and six daughters. His daughter Siddiqa was married to [[Mohammed Kadhim al-Modarresi|Muhammad-Kadhim al-Modarresi]]. His daughter Zahra was married to [[Mohammed Kadhim al-Qazwini|Muhammad-Kadhim al-Qazwini]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nbo.ir/%D8%B3%DB%8C%D8%AF-%D9%85%D9%87%D8%AF%DB%8C-%D8%AD%D8%B3%DB%8C%D9%86%DB%8C-%D8%B4%DB%8C%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B2%DB%8C__a-470.aspx|title=Sayyid Mahdi Husayni Shirazi|last=|first=|date=|website=The Shia Educational and Cultural Centre|language=fa|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Works==\n\n=== Books ===\nMirza Mahdi authored a large number of books, which includes some of his most important ones:\n\n* ''Sharh al-Urwat al-Wuthqa'' (Dissecting [[Urwa al-Wuthqa|The Firmest Bond]])\n* ''Thakhirat al-Ibad'' (The Worshippers' Provisions)\n* ''Manasek al-Haj'' ([[Hajj]] Rituals)\n* ''Kashkool Fi Mukhtalaf al-'Uloom'' (An Assortment In Different Sciences)\n\n=== Poetry ===\nMirza Mahdi also wrote poetry in praise of the [[Ahl al-Bayt|Ahlulbayt]]. His most known poem was written on the auspicious birth anniversary of [[Fatimah|Fatima]], which begins with:<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Dr Shaykh Muhammad-Sadiq|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pzoKv4vsOcwC|title=al-Madkhal Ila al-Shi'r al-Husayni|publisher=Hussaini Centre for Research|year=|isbn=978-1-902490-19-9|volume=1|location=London, UK|pages=41|language=ar|trans-title=The Gateway to Husayni Poetry}}</ref>{{Verse translation|{{lang|ar|rtl=yes|\n\u062f\u0631\u0651\u0629 \u0623\u0634\u0631\u0642\u062a \u0628\u0623\u0628\u0647\u0649 \u0633\u0646\u0627\u0647\u0627\n\u0641\u062a\u0644\u0623\u0644\u0623 \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0631\u0649 \u0641\u064a\u0627 \u0628\u064f\u0634\u0631\u0627\u0647\u0627\n\u0644\u0645\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u0646 \u0645\u0646 \u0633\u0646\u0627 \u0646\u0648\u0631 \u0642\u062f\u0633\n\u0628\u0633\u0646\u0627 \u0646\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0623\u0636\u0627\u0621 \u0637\u0648\u0627\u0647\u0627}}|A pearl has risen with prestigious light,\nThe world has been illuminated, glad tidings.\nThe universe shines from the divine light,\nWith His light, he illuminated her valley.|italicsoff=y|rtl1=y}}\n\n== Death ==\n[[File:Mirzamehdi3.jpg|thumb|249x249px|Funeral of Mirza Mahdi, Karbala|alt=]]Mirza Mahdi died in the early hours of Wednesday, February 15, 1961. During the bathing of his corpse, there was a partial [[Solar eclipse of February 15, 1961|solar eclipse]] that took place, with 67% obscurity<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEgoogle/SEgoogle1951/SE1961Feb15Tgoogle.html|title=NASA - Total Solar Eclipse of 1961 Feb 15|website=eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> that darkened the city of Karbala for just under an hour, as witnessed by the people of the city, who rushed to pray the [[Sign prayer|Ayat prayer]], before resuming with the funeral. He was buried in the south eastern side of the Imam Husayn Shrine.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Reactions ===\nThe Shia world was struck upon Mirza Mahdi's death. It is reported that [[Hossein Borujerdi]], who was in [[Qom]], cried for a few minutes over the news of Mirza Mahdi's demise.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shirazi, Seyed Mahdi Hosseini}}\n[[Category:Iraqi grand ayatollahs]]\n[[Category:People from Karbala]]\n[[Category:Shia clerics]]\n[[Category:Iranian Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Sourceofgrace", "label": "safe", "comment": "No citations found for information.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirza_Mahdi_al-Shirazi"}
